{These are the two ideas I am most proud of, as they embody the old way of playing the Nimzo-Indian, just as I used to do in the past. I hope you have enjoyed this brief glimpse of what the course has to offer. Now, I would like to provide a heads-up. This opening was created by a top-level player, and it is intended to be useful for other top-level players. My style of chess analysis does not prioritize flashy lines, although they certainly intrigue me. My goal is always to discover the objective truth. This means I delve very deeply into certain variations to determine what is acceptable for Black, and my threshold for what is acceptable is quite high. When I invest this much time in creating a course, I want it to be beneficial not only for you, the student but also good enough for me to utilize in my own games. Therefore, the analysis in this course is at a 2630 level!  I recommend that all of you keep this in mind while studying the course. I would also like to give a shoutout to the Chessable Pro feature that assists in limiting the depth of moves you wish to study. If you are a super pro, you may want to learn everything. However, if your rating is on the lower side, I recommend focusing on the first 6-7 moves until you have truly mastered them before expanding to more moves.   Regardless of your level, I hope you can reap maximum benefits from my course, and I welcome you to embark on the journey of learning Hammer's Nimzo-Indian!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This opening revolves around fighting for central control and swift development. Black has the ability to castle as early as move 4, which is the fastest possible in chess. I also introduce some new ideas, which is why I want to showcase two variations that I am particularly proud of. These variations demonstrate how our approach combines the good and the old with the new and exciting:} ({A) First of all, I am really proud of my approach against f3 , where white's aggressive intentions of pushing all of the pawns in the center of the board are obvious. This is a strategy employed by aggressive white players, and I struggled for a long time to find a way to play against it without creating chaos.  However, I discovered an idea that had not been used for many years, which aligns with our objectives:} 3... d5 4. a3 Be7 5. e4 {. One might think that capturing on e4 and playing c5 immediately is the main line these days, as it avoids having two central pawns next to each other controlling the board. However, I found an unconventional idea with} dxc4 {. We allow White to enjoy their beautiful center, but one of their main issues in this line is finding a good way to develop the knight to f3 .  I was so excited about this line that I posted it on Twitter, indicating that it would be my response to the f3 line in the Nimzo. Some strong players must have seen my tweet because ever since, the interest in this variation has skyrocketed. Andrey Esipenko from Russia was the first to play it, using it against Radosław Wojtaszek, a highly skilled player with the white pieces. Esipenko managed to defeat Wojtaszek after} 6. Be3 {by playing} b5 {(a line we will thoroughly explore in the  f3 chapter ) sacrificing the b-pawn for quick development. By playing} 7. Nxb5 Ba6 {indirectly defending the c4 -pawn, as} 8. Bxc4 {is met with} c6 $1 {Thus began the story of how Andrey Esipenko adopted my recommendation against the f3 Nimzo! He later employed it against Alexey Sarana, who captured on c5 after Bxc4 c5} 9. Ne2 O-O {Be3 Nc6 dxc5 . Esipenko responded with Ne5 , attacking the bishop, and after the retreat} 10. Ba2 {, he unleashed Nd3 . And now after Kf1 instead of recapturing the pawn on c5 , he played b6! This move enables the bishop to attack the white king with Ba6 in the near future, which is precisely what I recommend and what Esipenko executed in his game against Sarana.  Even in the game continuation c6} Bc5 {, they continued to follow the course, and Esipenko secured another victory in this variation against top-tier players! It is safe to say that this opening is causing a stir on the circuit, and I am delighted to present you with the full ideas.}) ({B) Another line I am very satisfied with is one of the main lines after Qc2 . Most top-level players here simply castle, while occasionally some opt for} 3... d5 {, and after} 4. cxd5 {, they recapture with their pawn. As the second choice on move 4 and the second choice on move 5, I recommend} Qxd5 {. This move gained significant popularity during the 2000s and was even played in a World Championship match between Vishy Anand and Vladimir Kramnik, where an amazing new idea was introduced after} 5. Nf3 Qf5 6. Qb3 Nc6 7. Bd2 {O-O . The key idea here is h3 , highlighting the vulnerability of Black's queen on f5 , while White's light-squared bishop will also eye the h1 - a8 soon after g4 - Bg2 . Kramnik played} b6 {, which was honestly a bad move. After} 8. g4 {, his queen was in trouble, and he was subsequently crushed. The modern way of playing this line is} a5 {, and now after g4 Qg6 , a critical point arises that alters everyone's opinion of this line. After} 9. a3 {, almost everyone plays} a4 {. However,} 10. Qd1 {proves to be quite strong, and after Bxc3 Bxc3 , Black cannot exploit the superior development with} e5 {due to} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ne4 {Qd3 . The key point here is that after the exchange of knights, White's bishop will be able to pose threats along the diagonal.  Nevertheless, I have found an improvement in this line. When the bishop is threatened with a3 , we allow the trade with Bxc3 Bxc3 , and now we go for the sacrifice e5! In some lines, it is highly advantageous that our light-squared bishop gains a tempo on the queen. Furthermore, if White attempts to play similarly to the previous line with Nxe5 , it turns out to be a mistake due to Qe4! This move attacks the rook in the corner and targets the pawn in the center. If White tries} 13. f3 {, then} Qf4 {prevents the king from castling queenside while attempting to infiltrate through the g3 -square. Even if White retreats with Nf3 , Re8 attacks the knight on f3 ! And now, after O-O-O , the move Nb4 creates a massive attack for Black.}) *

