1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {If you want the Catalan opening, you'd normally go 3. g3 , but with the insertion of 3. Nc3 and Bb4 , this instead becomes a Nimzo-Catalan hybrid. White hopes to see a magnificent bishop on g2 controlling the whole board, including the important e4 central square.} Bxc3+ {I'll admit this is a weird move, but hear me out: I'd like to compare this to the line with 4. a3 , where the positions after Bxc3 are considered nice for Black. 4. g3 didn't actually do much to help White's development. In the 4. a3 -lines, white normally goes for a bishop placement on d3 to point towards h7 and Black's king.  Also, Bg5 is often a very annoying move to face for Black, but with the pawn on g3 this becomes impossible. Bg5 is met by h6 , when Bh4 is no longer a possibility on account of g5 trapping the bishop.  So the move g3 , while it might be considered a free move compared to a3 , is detrimental to White's position if you play the same plans as in 4. a3 . And I'm gonna prove that the plans unique to this move order aren't that impressive either.} (4... c5 {is a worthwhile alternative for Black, when} 5. Nf3 {is White's best option, transposing back to the 4. Nf3 -lines .}) 5. bxc3 d6 {As always when we take on c3 and give White doubled pawns, we're placing our pawns on dark squares to compensate for losing our dark-squared bishop.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. e4 {is a very ambitious option for White, but White's lack of development doesn't justify this early aggression.} e5 8. Ne2 {This gets the knight out while keeping the pawn on e4 protected by the bishop, but puts no pressure on Black, who can concentrate on a different White pawn in trouble now.} b6 {Opening up for the bishop to attack c4 .} 9. f4 {Aggression is the only justification for the inevitable loss of the c4 -pawn.} Ba6 10. O-O Bxc4 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Bg5 {The bishop gets its great placement on g5 , pointing towards the black queen, but there's a simple defense...} Nbd7 {When Black is a pawn up and keeps the kingside protected.} *

