1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {This is known as the Kasparov variation, which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4.e3-line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line 4.e3 c5 5.Ne2 is considered favorable for white. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .} c5 5. g3 {This is white's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when black can't block its path with pawns. That's why white chooses to go for the fianchetto when black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but Black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while White's king remains in the danger zone.} d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black gets the knight involved, but at the same time, White gets pressure against the d5 -knight too. That's important because it increases the likelihood of the d5 -knight being exchanged, which would leave the g2 -bishop a force to be reckoned with. But first White needs to deal with the threats we've made toward the c3 -knight.} 9. Qb3 {A multi-purpose move: It puts pressure on black's pieces on b4 and d5 , as well as defending the c3 -knight. But black can reenforce all of those squares:} Qa5 10. Bd2 {This is the main line. White tries to neutralize the sting of black's queen and bishop pointing towards white's king.} Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {The bad news is that Black has voluntarily taken on a bad pawn structure. The pawn on c6 will be a target. However, the good news is that the c8 -bishop that often struggles in this line will find a fantastic home on a6 soon.} 12. O-O Bxc3 ({Timing is everything. If} 12... Ba6 $4 {White wins after} 13. Nxd5 Bxd2 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Nxc6 {so it's important to capture on c3 first.}) 13. bxc3 Ba6 {Black got the bishop active and is ready to play Rb8 , starting counterplay against white's queen -- but White still has some tricks.} 14. Rfd1 {A brilliant move. The two most obvious options are Rab8 and Bxe2 , but both are bad.} Qc5 {It's very important to stop white from playing c4 .} (14... Bxe2 $6 15. c4 $1 Bxd1 16. Rxd1 Qc7 17. cxd5 cxd5 {The bishop pair is so good, Black is much worse despite getting a rook and two central pawns in return. So we avoid this line.}) (14... Rab8 $2 15. c4 Qc5 16. cxd5 $3 {A brilliant queen sacrifice!} Rxb3 17. axb3 Bxe2 18. Re1 $1 Bb5 19. dxc6 {White's passed pawn is so strong, white has a winning position despite losing the queen for a rook and bishop. If Black tries to get rid of the pawn with} Bxc6 $2 {then} 20. Rac1 {wins back the bishop, as counterattacking with} Qd6 {allows} 21. Bf4 {when White gets to keep both bishops and win the game.}) 15. e4 {How can Black justify going into this line? White has the bishop pair, and now the well-placed knight in the center is getting kicked back. The key is the c4 -square, where Black is able to place a piece without any White pawns around to prevent them.} Bc4 16. Qa4 (16. Qc2 {Puts white's queen on a less vulnerable square, but it's also a square where she is unable to influence the game.} Nb6 17. a4 (17. Be3 Qa3 {blocks the a-pawn from moving forward.}) 17... Qa5 {it seems awkward to use the queen as a blockader, but we really wanted to stop White from playing a5 next. Now that White's plan has been prevented, Black can focus on plan of their own next. A rook to the d-file, placing pawns on dark squares to work well with the light-squared bishop, and hopefully getting the knight to c4 at some point.}) 16... Nb6 17. Qb4 Qh5 18. Re1 {is a popular move at top-level, but it's a bit of a mystery. It's supposed to be preventive against Black's plan of Be2 , but black has other plans available too, and moving the rook away from the open file feels wrong.} c5 19. Qa5 Rfc8 {Black's major problem in the position is the queenside pawns which need protection. So what's better than a plan involving protecting both a7 and c5 ?   Continue this variation here!} *

