1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move White immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Saemich variation, and frankly if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help White's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give White doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful to stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. Nf3 {It's very unusual for White to place the knight on f3 in these lines, as it stops White's f-pawn from getting involved in the action. The only way for it to make sense with the spirit of the Saemich variation is if White follows up with Qc2 and e4 to dominate the center.} Nc6 7. Qc2 d6 {Black's setup is very reminiscent of the Hübner variation of the 4. Nf3 line. We place the pawns on the dark squares. When White closes the center we focus on getting the f5 pawn break.} 8. e4 e5 9. d5 Ne7 {This is an important move to remember. We're not going after the c4 -pawn because of White's attacking potential on the kingside. Instead, we move the knight over to where the action is taking place. Long-term, Black would like to play f5 to prevent being run over by White's kingside pawns.} 10. g3 {This is generally a useful move for White in this line, as Black often looks to go Ng6 - f4 if the opportunity presents itself.} h6 {I like this move. We use our pawns to restrict the c1 -bishop's options while keeping all our options open.} 11. Bg2 (11. Nh4 {transposes to the 10.Nh4-line .}) 11... O-O 12. O-O Ng6 {I like the timing of this move. We wait with Ng6 until white has committed to O-O , which means white loses the potentially annoying plan of h4 - h5 with the rook still on h1 .} 13. Ne1 Nh7 {We're ready for f5 next.} 14. Nd3 f5 {We've completed our main plan and can be happy about the opening.} *

