1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move White immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Saemich variation, and frankly if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help White's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give White doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful to stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 {We're going after the c4 -pawn. The bishop needs access to a6 .} 9. e4 {White has developed the bishop and knight. It's time to move forward in the center.} Ne8 {This is a key move in this line. It may look funny, but it's absolutely crucial to prevent Bg5 with a nasty pin. Sometimes this knight also participates in the pressure on the c4 -pawn by going to d6 .} 10. O-O Ba6 {Target acquired.} 11. f4 {White pushes forward to create an attack, but Black is ready to block.} f5 {No further! We grab space and prevent White from marching forward with the f-pawn.} 12. Ng3 {Now it's all about the f5 -pawn.} ({Getting all the captures done immediately with} 12. exf5 exf5 13. dxc5 bxc5 {leads to the same position we study in the 12.Ng3-line after} 14. Be3 d6 15. Ng3 g6 {.}) (12. Be3 $2 {puts pressure on c5 , but after} fxe4 13. Bxe4 Nd6 {Black's knight will go from a dim position on the rim to an amazing one on c4 in no time. Black is much better.}) 12... g6 {It feels risky putting all the pawns on light squares when we've given up our dark-squared bishop, but here it's all about blockading. White's bishops are unable to prove their worth in a closed position.} 13. dxc5 {White tries to exchange off the central pawns, which were getting in the way of the bishops.} bxc5 14. exf5 exf5 15. Be3 d6 {The threat to c5 is easily parried by Black. This is actually a pawn sacrifice, but white would be ill-advised to take it.} 16. Re1 {This maneuvering scheme was played by Magnus Carlsen, but it doesn't do anything to stop Black's main plan.} Nf6 {It's time for the knight to return to the center.} 17. Bf2 {White hopes to find a home for the bishop on h4 , where it won't be shut out of play by pawns.} Na5 {We've been so focused on the stuff going on in the middle, it's easy to forget the target on c4 is still there for the taking.  See how this variation ends here!} *

