1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.   However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that white gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory -- which frankly is precisely what a 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the White player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, White just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center with} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps White's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. dxc5 {This was actually Garry Kasparov's choice, in the only top-tier outing this variation has ever had. The early queen trade should give Black a nice game.} Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 10. e5 {This early aggression is met by a surprising pawn sacrifice!} Nd5 11. Bxd5 exd5 12. Nxd5 {The threat of Nc7 means Black's counterplay is delayed by one move, which gives white some time to neutralize the initiative.} Na6 13. Be3 Be6 {This is a very cool move! Black plans an exchange sacrifice.} 14. Nc7+ Nxc7 15. Bxc5 b6 16. Be3 Nd5 17. Bd2 O-O {Gives black amazing light-squared control, and with it very good compensation for a pawn. Black will place one rook on d8 , aiming at the king, and the other on e8 , eyeing the e5 -pawn.} *

