1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.   However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that white gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory -- which frankly is precisely what a 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the White player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, White just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center with} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps White's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. Nge2 {By far white's most logical move.} (8. Be3 $6 {This is a bad way to defend the pawn, as it allows Black to develop with a threat after} cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 {and White will have to move the bishop again without putting pressure on Black's development.}) 8... O-O {We want to castle before playing Nc6 to avoid funky lines with d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. dxc5 {As we will see, this is actually a risky move. But it's definitely also the most testing one for Black's concept.} (10. O-O {gives Black very easy play after} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {when White will have to trade away any hope of an advantage.}) 10... Ne5 11. Ba2 Nd3+ 12. Kf1 {It's a big concession for White to move the king, but white is hoping it doesn't matter in an endgame. However, Black doesn't have to acquiesce to White's plan.} b6 {This is the key move! Black has no intention to cashing in on the pawn just yet. Instead, the bishop gets a route to a6 , from where it will point down towards White's king.} (12... Bxc5 $2 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. e5 {would play straight into White's hands, when the uncastled white king would not be a major feature in the position as Black has no pieces in attacking positions.}) 13. c6 {keeps a thorn deep inside Black's position, but not to worry.} Bc5 {Black keeps good counterplay.} 14. Bxc5 bxc5 {is a very nice change of pawn structure for Black. By getting the pawn to c5 , Black prevents white's b4 - b5 pawn advance, which would block the c8 -bishop's planned diagonal from a6 .} 15. Bc4 {Stops Ba6 , but allows black to get the pawn back...} Nxb2 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Bb5 a6 18. Ba4 Ra7 {The Black rook keeps White's c-pawn under control, and with Rc7 coming next it's likely Black will capture the dangerous pawn in the very near future.} *

