1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 {We strike immediately!} 5. e3 {Defending the center is sensible, but unimpressive.} cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {You can't go wrong with putting pawns in the middle!} 7. a3 {White gets the bishop pair, but also a terrible isolated pawn on d4 .} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 dxc4 {We're happy to let White develop the bishop in one go since isolating the d4 -pawn is devastating to White's pawn structure long-term.} 9. Bxc4 O-O {Black has a very easy plan of b6 and Ba6 next.} *

