1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 {We strike immediately!} 5. dxc5 {When playing minimalistic openings, you have to appreciate the small things in life. In this case: White gives up the central pawn to make Black's bishop move for a second time.} Bxc5 6. g3 {Going for the fianchetto is the only way to make independent of the lines where White played e3 on move four.} O-O 7. Bg2 d5 {I don't make a habit out of giving myself an isolated queen's pawn (IQP), so when I do, you know it's good. Play becomes very reminiscent of the Tarrasch opening, but there's a major difference: White's knight on c3 is a bigger target than normal because White has captured on c5 early, which enables d4 from Black.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nf3 {This gives Black the perfect setup.} Re8 {Rooks belong on open files, but there are other sensible development moves too. We're prioritizing this move because it gives the bishop an escape square on f8 .} 10. O-O d4 11. Na4 Bf8 {Black has nice pressure down the center.} 12. e3 {This may very well be White's best option.} dxe3 13. Bxe3 Nc6 {There's no doubt Black is fine.} *

