1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Nf4 {This is an aggressive placement for the knight, but Black is still able to strike back in the center.} c6 {With White's knight on f4 , we can change our plan of pawn breaks in the center. In this c6 -line, we're planning e5 instead of c5 to attack White's center.} 8. Bd3 dxc4 {We force White to move the bishop for the second time in a row.} 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Our knight makes us ready for the e5 -break next.} 10. O-O e5 {The pawn break gives White a decision: Either allow Black's knight a great square in the center or retreat your knight.} 11. Nfe2 {Retreating is the better option. The knight can find a good square on d4 if Black trades.} Bd6 {The bishop moves for the second time in the opening, but Black has a nice re-organizing scheme for the pieces.} 12. h3 Re8 13. Qc2 Qe7 {Coordination is good. Now we're ready to make the trade on d4 .  See the continuation of this variation here!} *

