1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. cxd5 {This exchange is often considered unfavorable for White, as it opens up for Black's light-squared bishop. Even so, in this position, it is the only way to fight for an opening advantage. The key is that White's development of the knight to e2 has prevented quick development, and White needs to buy some time to get castled before Black makes a breakthrough in the center.  By making the trade, White prevents the standard plan of dxc4 followed by c5 to remove all the pawns from the middle. After the trade, however, if Black wants to go c5 now, they'll have to accept an isolated pawn in the center.} exd5 8. Nf4 {The knight puts pressure towards d5 , which means c5 isn't viable for Black.} c6 {Solidifying the center, but surprisingly also getting the c7 -square ready for a different piece!} 9. Bd3 Na6 {Our knight is headed for c7 , where it will give extra protection to the d5 -pawn (which is needed if we want to go c5 later), or it can move further to e6 to make some trades.} 10. O-O Nc7 11. f3 {White's long-term objective is to take control with the pawns in the center. This is step one of that plan.} Re8 {I like this move because it's the most clear-cut plan. Once White goes f3 , Black wants to play c5 and argue the pawn on e3 is just as weak as its counterpart on d5 . However, in this moment c5 is not good because the can be pushed away from its attack on the e3 -pawn. Therefore we need this move in preparation of c5 .} 12. Nce2 {White understands the c5 -break cannot be prevented and gets ready for how to deal with it when it does happen.} c5 {We're not discouraged by a knight planning to land on d4 .} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd4 {This was White's idea. The knight prevents the c5 -bishop's pressure on e3 .} Ne6 {I like this move, as we change the pawn structure for the second move in a row. Our d5 -pawn doesn't have to be lonely anymore.} 15. Nfxe6 fxe6 {No more isolani on d5 . Black is ready to advance in the center and generally has well-placed pieces. The position is unbalanced, but with even chances.} *

