1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . We will also see White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 {I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines...} 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {One of the key points here is that White no longer has Bg5 available.} 9. O-O Nc6 {Black essentially treats the position as if the trade of knights has already happened and develops according to what would be good with a pawn on d5 instead of a knight.} 10. a3 {This doesn't really make much sense to me, as White forces the bishop to the d6 -square, where we want it to go anyway. However, it was played in 2021 by Caruana, so it deserves our attention. In general White's concept is to avoid the trade of knights on d5 , which will make it difficult to get the c8 -bishop into play.} Bd6 {As always this is where we want our bishop.} 11. Re1 {White is simply improving their positioning while avoiding the trade on d5 .} Qh4 {At the time of writing this has never been played before, but it has become a standard move for us in this opening, and I think it works okay here too.} 12. g3 {Stopping the checkmate while gaining time on Black's queen.} Qh5 13. Be4 {This tries to continue the plan of not capturing on d5 .} Nf6 14. Bg2 {An unorthodox way to fianchetto the bishop!} Rd8 {The pressure on the d4 -pawn is unpleasant to face for White.} *

