[PlyCount "24"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 {This is the main line, but we need to study an unusual seventh move.} d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several White weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. cxd5 {This is actually a pawn sacrifice -- a sacrifice I believe Black should not accept.} exd5 {Simplicity! The bishop is ready to enter the game via g4 .} 10. O-O {White's king gets out of the center, but at the same time this allows an annoying pin on White's knight.} Bg4 {White faces a tough decision. Do you move the queen, allowing Black to double the pawns and open up in front of White's king? Do you push the pawns forward in front of the king to kick Black's bishop out? Or do you retreat your own bishop to stop the pin?} 11. h3 Bh5 {We want to keep the annoying pin. And if anything White has forced the bishop to a better square, as we now have the option of offering the bishop trade on g6 .} 12. g4 {This is a very risky concept for White, because just like Qe1 , it weakens the king's pawn protection -- but in addition, it allows Black to trade off White's bishop pair next move.} Bg6 {We're happy to provoke weaknesses around White's king. Black has a good position.} *

