1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 ({Previously Black usually played} 8... cxd4 {here, which left white with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 . However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.}) 9. a3 {This is the main line, asking the bishop to declare its intentions.} (9. Bd3 {This seems weird, as it just moves the bishop back where it came from, but white is waiting for Black to capture on d4 , and chooses piece placements with that exchange in mind. However, White is not the only one who can play a waiting game. Black has a clever little move in} h6 $1 {when we permanently prevent Bg5 in the future, while keeping our options open depending on white's response. After} 10. a3 {Black doesn't want to give up the bishop and strengthen White's center, so we go} Ba5 {which is actually the same position we study in the mainline beginning with 9. a3 .}) 9... Ba5 {We don't want to give away the bishop pair AND reinforce White's center, so we retreat.} 10. dxc5 {Tries to exploit the bishop's retreat, but we can try to exploit the change in pawn structure by using this moment to give up the bishop.} Bxc3 11. Qxd8 {There's no need to be concerned about this since we just get our rook in a better position.} Rxd8 12. bxc3 Ne4 {Black will regain the pawn.} *

