1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. Nf3 {White is staying flexible -- not committing to either cxd5 or a3 just yet. The disadvantage of this strategy is that the pawn on c4 is unprotected, and I don't see any reason to let it live.} dxc4 {We're going to make an effort to keep this pawn, punishing White's nonchalance.} {Bg5 this transposes to the lines with 5.Bg5.} 6. e4 {This is by far White's most aggressive try. But we're going to use the e4 -pawn as a target.} b5 {First things first: protecting the c4 -pawn.} 7. a4 {White tries to force c6 , which shuts down the a8 - h1 -diagonal for our bishop. Instead I'm recommending a line based on immediate threats on White's position. We'll give back the pawn we won, but get active piece play.} Bb7 {A counter-threat on the e4 -pawn.} 8. e5 {White keeps the central pawn protected while also attacking Black's knight. As a result White will have time to win the b5 -pawn next. But it has come at a cost: Black enjoys a wonderful diagonal for the b7 -bishop.} Nd5 9. axb5 Nb6 {Unfortunately our knight couldn't stay on the nice d5 -square, as it was needed as a replacement defender of our c4 -pawn when the b5 -pawn was captured.} 10. Be2 a6 {This is the key to Black's entire setup. We're creating threats on the queenside before White has time to get the king to safety and start attacking the vulnerable c4 -pawn.} 11. bxa6 {Making the trade helps Black get the knight to a good position.} Nxa6 12. O-O Be7 {A key move! The b4 -square belongs to Black's knight, not the bishop. As the knight lands on b4 it will also kick White's queen away from the c2 -square, which in turn stops White from building pressure on the c4 -pawn.   The b7 -bishop enjoys an excellent diagonal and the knight may use the d5 -square in the future. Black has good chances in an unbalanced position.} *

