1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. e3 {Just like in the 9. Nf3 line, White prioritizes getting the pieces out, but Black gets the opportunity to bring the queen out and take back the c5 -pawn.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Nxd2 {Bye bishops!} 11. Qxd2 dxc4 {We're at a crossroads. White can exchange queens, but then the black knight will get involved and protect the c4 -pawn. Alternately white can go after the c4 -pawn immediately, but then Black is free to capture on c5 . Either way Black is doing fine.} 12. Bxc4 {This is currently white's main try in this line, but it's very minimalistic. Black gets a symmetrical position...} Qxc5 {White is slightly ahead on development and has the more active bishop. But at the same time, we have no weaknesses in our position. It's all about calmly developing.} 13. Rc1 Qe7 {That's a big 'no, thank you' to having the queen on the same file as White's rook.} 14. Nf3 O-O 15. b4 {White gets ready for b5 to push Black's knight back, while also giving the queen a nice hiding spot on b2 .} Rd8 16. Qb2 a6 {The knight does such a good job on c6 , it's worth playing a6 to keep it there.} 17. O-O Bd7 {Once again we just get the rooks ready.} 18. Rfd1 Rac8 {Be8 next. Maybe Na7 and Bb5 at some point in the future if we're feeling funky. Black has no problems.} *

