ing gets stuck in the center.} (13. Bd2 $4 {is simply a blunder. Black wins after} Nxd2 14. Nxd2 (14. Bxf5 Nxf3+ {Nasty double-check.}) (14. Qxd2 Bxd3 {exploits the pin.}) 14... Nb4 {when White is forced to give up the exchange under very bad circumstances.} 15. axb4 Qxa1+ 16. Qb1 Qxb1+ 17. Bxb1 Bxb1 18. Nxb1 a5 {There's no way of keeping the queenside pawns defended and Black will win with the extra rook.}) 13... b6 {An excellent response for Black. We need to get the rooks involved pronto.} 14. Bd2 {White desperately needs to get the pieces out.} (14. cxb6 $2 {is inadvisable. After} Qxb6 {Black will get the rook to the c-file and cause all sorts of problems.}) 14... Nxd2 15. Bxf5 {This is White's best to keep the positon chaotic.} Nxf3 16. gxf3 (16. Bxh7+ {There are some subtle differences depending on when white captures on h7 -- but most of the time it just transposes back to the main line. For example} Kh8 17. gxf3 bxc5 18. b4 Qb5+ 19. Qd3 c4 20. Qf5 g6 21. Bxg6 fxg6 22. Qxg6 Ne7 {With the same position we study in the main line.}) 16... bxc5 {White's king is very vulnerable in the center, but it turns out Black's king won't be safe either as the h7 -pawn is lost. Both players keep attacking, with very unclear consequences.   See how this variation could continue here!} *

