1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 {This is very similar to the 6.e3 -line where White plays 8.bxc3 . The only difference is that White has played a3 instead of Bd2 .} b6 {It's important to get the c8 -bishop involved early. Preferably to a6 , where it will trade off White's bishop pair.} 9. f3 {This becomes a mix of two different plans for White, while Black is happy to demonstrate their main plan.} cxd4 {By trading on d4 we delay White's option to play e4 , since the d4 -pawn will then remain undefended.} 10. cxd4 O-O {Let's get the king to safety to avoid any Qa4 + embarrassment.} 11. Bb2 Ba6 {Black manages to trade off White's bishop pair and will create counterplay against White's nice center by creating threats down the c-file.} *

