1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qxf5 exf5 {This endgame is considered very decent for Black.} 8. a3 {Immediately forcing the bishop to show its intentions.} Bd6 {I think there's no doubt d6 is the best square for the bishop, but there's a question of whether Black should fear losing the bishop pair to Nb5 . Studying the lines has made me decide there's no reason to worry.} 9. g3 {Having put most of the pawns on dark squares, White tries to get the dark-squared bishops exchanged off.} Be6 10. Bg2 c6 {We use the pawns on b7 and c6 to block the bishop's diagonal.} 11. Bf4 {White is happy to accept doubled pawns if it means getting a favorable bishop trade.} Bxf4 {The bishop trade may be good news for White, but it's not the end of the world for black either. Black's position is extremely solid.} 12. gxf4 a5 {I like this move. Black grabs space on the queenside and prevents b4 . The latter is important because the only way for white to breathe some life into the g2 -bishop would be to go b4 - b5 to hack at the b7 / c6 -pawn wall Black erected.} 13. e3 Nbd7 14. Ne5 Ke7 {Black is well-prepared for this queenless middlegame.} *

