1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. h3 {While h3 and g4 is a common plan in this line to trouble Black's queen, it's unusual to see it this early.} a5 {The early pawn advance works out very well for Black because White's queen gets kicked around.} 9. Bd2 {Covering with the bishop comes a move too late.} a4 10. Nxa4 {White successfully stopped the queen from getting chased, but it comes at too high a price.} (10. Qc4 {is better, but Black seizes the initiative with} a3) 10... Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 Nxd4 {White's whole position collapsed when the knight was lured out to a4 .} *

