1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 {How come Qc2 is so popular, while no one cares about Qb3 ? After all, white is putting pressure on Black's bishop in addition to defending the knight. However, there are two major drawbacks: White has no control of the e4 -square, where a black knight could easily jump and cause trouble. Also, when White plays a3 , Black will have the unusual option of Ba5 , which is unique to this line since following up with b4 is impossible for White.} c5 {Putting pressure on the center while also defending the bishop. It's our best move.} 5. e3 {Keeps White's control in the center, but doesn't do anything to challenge Black.} O-O 6. Nf3 (6. a3 Ba5 {transposes to the 5.a3-line .}) 6... b6 {Black gets all the pieces in good positions.} 7. Be2 Ne4 {It's important to make this move before white's king runs away.} 8. Bd2 {To avoid horrible doubled pawns, White has to give up the bishop pair.} Nxd2 9. Nxd2 Bb7 {The bishop found an excellent diagonal from b7 . Black has a good position.} *

