1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 {How come Qc2 is so popular, while no one cares about Qb3 ? After all, white is putting pressure on Black's bishop in addition to defending the knight. However, there are two major drawbacks: White has no control of the e4 -square, where a black knight could easily jump and cause trouble. Also, when White plays a3 , Black will have the unusual option of Ba5 , which is unique to this line since following up with b4 is impossible for White.} c5 {Putting pressure on the center while also defending the bishop. It's our best move.} 5. a3 {Puts pressure on the bishop, but as noted earlier, Black doesn't have to give up the bishop just yet.} Ba5 6. e3 (6. dxc5 Ne4 {is similar to the main line.}) 6... O-O 7. dxc5 {Taking on c5 is the logical way of punishing Black for moving the bishop away from b4 , but at the same time it allows for Black to wreak havoc on White's pawn structure.} (7. Nf3 b6 {gives Black an easy development plan going forward, with Ne4 and Bb7 coming up.}) 7... Ne4 8. Nge2 {Trying to keep the pawn structure intact this way doesn't work well either.} Qh4 {When there are too many threats on White's position.} 9. g3 Nxc5 10. Qc2 Qxc4 {when Black is a pawn up, in addition to having scary threats such as Nd3 +.} *

