1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 {How come Qc2 is so popular, while no one cares about Qb3 ? After all, white is putting pressure on Black's bishop in addition to defending the knight. However, there are two major drawbacks: White has no control of the e4 -square, where a black knight could easily jump and cause trouble. Also, when White plays a3 , Black will have the unusual option of Ba5 , which is unique to this line since following up with b4 is impossible for White.} c5 {Putting pressure on the center while also defending the bishop. It's our best move.} 5. dxc5 (5. Nf3 O-O 6. e3 {transposes to the 5.e3-line .}) 5... Nc6 {Black wants to keep the bishop pointing towards White's king, and continues quick development over recapturing on c5 .} 6. a3 Nd4 {With the help of tactics, Black forces the queen back.} 7. Qd1 {Now that White's queen is pushed back, we can ruin the pawn structure.} (7. Qxb4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Nc2+ {forking everything.}) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc6 {Going back and forth with the knight was time-consuming for Black, but it has left white with a pawn structure that will give nightmares for the rest of the game. All in all the wasted time was well invested.} *

