1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bf4 {Despite looking logical, this is a very unusual developing move. I think it’s because it does nothing to help get the king out of the center, while also failing to make Black’s pawn pushes in the center more difficult.} c5 {We strike in the center immediately!} 5. e3 d5 {We get all the center pawns involved!} 6. Nf3 (6. dxc5 $6 {is met by} Nbd7 $1 {After} 7. Nf3 Nxc5 {we’ve gotten the pawn back while also continuing the pressure from our Nimzo bishop on White’s king.}) 6... cxd4 {It’s time to make the trade.} 7. exd4 O-O {We’re delaying the second trade until White has moved their bishop out, in effect winning a free move.} 8. Bd3 dxc4 {Now is the time!} 9. Bxc4 Nd5 {This immediate confrontation equalizes the game for Black.} 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qc7 {Very clever!} 12. Qe2 (12. Qb3 $2 {The queen is misplaced here. It might give Black easier access to the c4 -square with Nc6 - a5 in the future, but the undefended knight on f3 is also a problem when Black gets the bishop on the long diagonal.} Bd6 13. O-O b6 {A good plan for Black. All the diagonal pieces are pointed at White’s king, and White needs to avoid the damaged pawn structure that could arise after Bxf3 too. Black is well on top.}) 12... b5 {I insist your c4 -bishop moves away.} 13. cxb4 (13. Bxb5 Bxc3 {is very slightly better for Black due to the isolated d4 -pawn.}) 13... Qxc4 14. Qxc4 bxc4 15. Rc1 {White targets the c4 -pawn, but we don’t really mind it being captured because then it will stop blocking our own bishop.} Nd7 16. Rxc4 Ba6 17. Rc7 Bb5 {White’s bishop is being blocked by their own pawns, while Black’s bishop is thriving, currently preventing castling for White. The h1 -rook will struggle to get into the game, and in the meantime, Black can take control of the c-file and maneuver the knight up to some juicy light squares.} *

