1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {If you want the Catalan opening, you'd normally go 3. g3 , but with the insertion of 3. Nc3 and Bb4 , this instead becomes a Nimzo-Catalan hybrid. White hopes to see a magnificent bishop on g2 controlling the whole board, including the important e4 central square.} Bxc3+ {I'll admit this is a weird move, but hear me out: I'd like to compare this to the line with 4. a3 , where the positions after Bxc3 are considered nice for Black. 4. g3 didn't actually do much to help white's development. In the 4. a3 lines, white normally goes for a bishop placement on d3 to point towards h7 and Black's king.  Also, Bg5 is often a very annoying move to face for Black, but with the pawn on g3 this becomes impossible. Bg5 is met by h6 , when Bh4 is no longer a possibility on account of g5 trapping the bishop.  So the move g3 , while it might be considered a free move compared to a3 , is detrimental to White's position if you play the same plans as in 4. a3 . And I'm gonna prove that the plans unique to this move order aren't that impressive either.} (4... c5 {is a worthwhile alternative for Black, when} 5. Nf3 {is White's best option, transposing back to the 4. Nf3 -lines .}) 5. bxc3 d6 {As always when we take on c3 and give White doubled pawns, we're placing our pawns on dark squares to compensate for losing our dark-squared bishop.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. e4 {is a very ambitious option for White, but White's lack of development doesn't justify this early aggression.} e5 8. Nf3 {Allows exchanges in the center...} Nxe4 9. O-O {when Black shouldn't get too greedy capturing pawns, and instead focusing on development.} Nc6 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Bxe4 exd4 {White won back the central pawn, but will have to give up their prized possession, the fianchettoed bishop, to retain material equality.} 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 {Black is happy to make the exchanges.} 14. cxd4 Ba6 15. Bf4 Bxc4 16. Rfc1 Bd5 17. Bxc7 Rfe8 {You'd think the position is just a draw with opposite-colored bishops, but Black's bishop is a monster compared to White's, and there is genuine hope of creating trouble towards the weak light squares surrounding White's king.} *

