1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {If you want the Catalan opening, you'd normally go 3. g3 , but with the insertion of 3. Nc3 and Bb4 , this instead becomes a Nimzo-Catalan hybrid. White hopes to see a magnificent bishop on g2 controlling the whole board, including the important e4 central square.} Bxc3+ {I'll admit this is a weird move, but hear me out: I'd like to compare this to the line with 4. a3 , where the positions after Bxc3 are considered nice for Black. 4. g3 didn't actually do much to help white's development. In the 4. a3 lines, white normally goes for a bishop placement on d3 to point towards h7 and Black's king.  Also, Bg5 is often a very annoying move to face for Black, but with the pawn on g3 this becomes impossible. Bg5 is met by h6 , when Bh4 is no longer a possibility on account of g5 trapping the bishop.  So the move g3 , while it might be considered a free move compared to a3 , is detrimental to White's position if you play the same plans as in 4. a3 . And I'm gonna prove that the plans unique to this move order aren't that impressive either.} (4... c5 {is a worthwhile alternative for Black, when} 5. Nf3 {is White's best option, transposing back to the 4. Nf3 -lines .}) 5. bxc3 d6 {As always when we take on c3 and give White doubled pawns, we're placing our pawns on dark squares to compensate for losing our dark-squared bishop.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Qd3 {This is an interesting try to avoid Black pushing forward in the center.} e5 9. Nd2 {The point of Qd3 is revealed, as white could play Nd2 and take central control without losing the protection of the d4 -pawn. However, this was time-consuming, and Black has a good counter plan to go e4 , grabbing space in the center and blocking White's great bishop diagonal.} Re8 10. O-O Qe7 {Black is ready for e4 next.} 11. e4 {This is the only way to stop black from taking space with e4 , but the unfortunate consequence is blocking white's bishop from its wonderful g2 - a8 diagonal.} b6 {Black immediately exploits that white's bishop isn't putting pressure on the c6 -knight, which allows Black's bishop to get to its favorite square in these pawn structures: a6 .} 12. f4 {Aggressive play makes perfect sense as White is saddled with a long-term weakness. Black might just get a sweet strategic win if white can't make anything happen fast.} Ba6 13. Ba3 {White threatens fxe5 , so the queen needs to move.} Qd8 (13... Qd7 $6 {would be a mistake, as it allows} 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Rxf6 $1 {an exchange sacrifice, ruining the pawns around Black's king. After} gxf6 16. d5 {it's a chaotic position where white has good attacking chances.}) 14. Rad1 Na5 15. Bb4 {White tries to scare Black into thinking doubled pawns on the side is bad, but we welcome it.} c5 16. Bxa5 bxa5 {The pawn on c4 remains a target and white's bishop will be blocked by its own pawns for the forseeable future.} *

