1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {If you want the Catalan opening, you'd normally go 3. g3 , but with the insertion of 3. Nc3 and Bb4 , this instead becomes a Nimzo-Catalan hybrid. White hopes to see a magnificent bishop on g2 controlling the whole board, including the important e4 central square.} Bxc3+ {I'll admit this is a weird move, but hear me out: I'd like to compare this to the line with 4. a3 , where the positions after Bxc3 are considered nice for Black. 4. g3 didn't actually do much to help white's development. In the 4. a3 lines, white normally goes for a bishop placement on d3 to point towards h7 and Black's king.  Also, Bg5 is often a very annoying move to face for Black, but with the pawn on g3 this becomes impossible. Bg5 is met by h6 , when Bh4 is no longer a possibility on account of g5 trapping the bishop.  So the move g3 , while it might be considered a free move compared to a3 , is detrimental to White's position if you play the same plans as in 4. a3 . And I'm gonna prove that the plans unique to this move order aren't that impressive either.} (4... c5 {is a worthwhile alternative for Black, when} 5. Nf3 {is White's best option, transposing back to the 4. Nf3 -lines .}) 5. bxc3 d6 {As always when we take on c3 and give White doubled pawns, we're placing our pawns on dark squares to compensate for losing our dark-squared bishop.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Qd3 {This is an interesting try to avoid Black pushing forward in the center.} e5 9. Nd2 {The point of Qd3 is revealed, as white could play Nd2 and take central control without losing the protection of the d4 -pawn. However, this was time-consuming, and Black has a good counter plan to go e4 , grabbing space in the center and blocking White's great bishop diagonal.} Re8 10. O-O Qe7 {Black is ready for e4 next.} 11. e4 {This is the only way to stop black from taking space with e4 , but the unfortunate consequence is blocking white's bishop from its wonderful g2 - a8 diagonal.} b6 12. Nb3 {This has been recommended by Jose Gonzalez. White’s big issue in these positions is the long-term problem of the dark-squared bishop, so they try to exchange it off before rushing Black with pawns.} Ba6 {Black’s plan remains the same: Target the c4 -pawn.} 13. Bg5 h6 {We need to get rid of White’s bishop immediately, as the pin on the knight will destroy us if White is allowed to combine it with f4 next.} 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. f4 Qe7 {There’s a lot of pressure in the center, but our e5 -pawn stands its ground against White’s onslaught.} 16. Rf2 {White gets ready to bring both rooks pointing down the f-file.} Na5 {This is the key idea! Nb3 was aimed at stopping this, but it turns out we’re not afraid of doubled side pawns, because it gives us options down the b-file.} 17. Nxa5 bxa5 {In my opinion, White is suffering here despite the impressive center. The pawn on c4 needs constant attention from White’s queen, while the e4 -pawn is blocking White’s bishop from contributing. Black has an easy plan of getting rooks involved on the b-file, and can stunt the f-file pressure easily by playing f6 . I think Black has the much more comfortable position.} *

