1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {If you want the Catalan opening, you'd normally go 3. g3 , but with the insertion of 3. Nc3 and Bb4 , this instead becomes a Nimzo-Catalan hybrid. White hopes to see a magnificent bishop on g2 controlling the whole board, including the important e4 central square.} Bxc3+ {I'll admit this is a weird move, but hear me out: I'd like to compare this to the line with 4. a3 , where the positions after Bxc3 are considered nice for Black. 4. g3 didn't actually do much to help white's development. In the 4. a3 lines, white normally goes for a bishop placement on d3 to point towards h7 and Black's king.  Also, Bg5 is often a very annoying move to face for Black, but with the pawn on g3 this becomes impossible. Bg5 is met by h6 , when Bh4 is no longer a possibility on account of g5 trapping the bishop.  So the move g3 , while it might be considered a free move compared to a3 , is detrimental to White's position if you play the same plans as in 4. a3 . And I'm gonna prove that the plans unique to this move order aren't that impressive either.} (4... c5 {is a worthwhile alternative for Black, when} 5. Nf3 {is White's best option, transposing back to the 4. Nf3 -lines .}) 5. bxc3 d6 {As always when we take on c3 and give White doubled pawns, we're placing our pawns on dark squares to compensate for losing our dark-squared bishop.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O e5 9. Rb1 {This stops the c8 -bishop from developing because of the threat against the b7 -pawn, but it gives Black time to play for e4 , a plan to limit the g2 -bishop's scope.} h6 {First we go ... h6 to prevent Bg5 , and thereby make sure the f6 -knight will stay on the board to control the e4 -square. White also wants control of e4 , but to play Nd2 you have to exchange in the center first to avoid losing the d4 -pawn.} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nd2 Re8 {When pushing the pawn forward to e4 is very much on the agenda.} 12. Qc2 Qe7 {Doesn't change the situation much.} 13. Ne4 {Forced- which blocks the bishop's diagonal, making it easier for Black to achieve the move b6 which will ease the combined pressure of the g2 -bishop and b1 -rook. When we've successfully neutralized those threats, we can start focusing on the c4 -pawn, which is a major long-term weakness.} Rb8 {is my preferred choice, as it prepares both b6 (by stepping out of the g2 -bishop's diagonal) and Bf5 (by protecting the b7 -pawn).} *

