1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {In response to Black's pin, white counters in kind. However, I believe this is simply not a good line. Even though the g5 -bishop got outside White's pawn chain, it still struggles to find its role in the game. Sometimes the bishop becomes a punching ball, as Black targets it with aggressive pawn advances on the kingside.} c5 {Putting immediate pressure on the center.} 5. d5 {This is almost universially played. The alternatives all have issues.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure after White has shown their hand in the center.} 6. bxc3 h6 7. Bh4 d6 8. f3 {is rare, but grabs lots of space. It's important for Black to avoid being suffocated, so we need some aggressive pawn play -- but with the right timing.} e5 {Closing down the center is a big decision, but the general rule is: The more blocked the position, the worse are the working conditions for bishops. And White has more bishops prone to becoming useless here.} 9. Qc2 {To illustrate an awesome idea for Black, I wanted to include what can happen if White doesn't push the central pawn forward.} e4 {An amazing move! Black takes space in the center and opens up the e5 -square for a knight. White wins a pawn...} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qxe4+ Kd8 12. Qc2 g5 {But Black has cool compensation with dark-squared control, open e-file for the rook, safe king on c7 , and a knight coming to e5 . This illustrates how all the strategic pluses can be combined with aggression. It's an exciting position where Black has the easy plans.} *

