1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {In response to Black's pin, white counters in kind. However, I believe this is simply not a good line. Even though the g5 -bishop got outside White's pawn chain, it still struggles to find its role in the game. Sometimes the bishop becomes a punching ball, as Black targets it with aggressive pawn advances on the kingside.} c5 {Putting immediate pressure on the center.} 5. d5 {This is almost universially played. The alternatives all have issues.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure after White has shown their hand in the center.} 6. bxc3 h6 7. Bh4 d6 8. e3 {White doesn't want to commit the pawn to e4 , as it would often be blocking its own bishop or standing in the way of a white knight coming to e4 instead.} e5 9. Bd3 {is a mistake...} e4 {When Black grabs important space in the center.} 10. Bc2 (10. Bxf6 $2 {is met by} Qxf6 {when} 11. Bxe4 Qxc3+ {leads to trouble for White. The king must move,} 12. Kf1 {, and then we swipe another pawn on c4} Qxc4+ {with check and a winning position.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Ne2 O-O {The pawn on e4 is extremely annoying for White's development. White already lost the normal option of playing the knight to d2 via f3 , but now Ng3 is impossible due to g5 , trapping the bishop. In the meantime, Black has more than enough pieces ready to go to the e-file and support the advanced pawn, not to mention the potential of a supreme knight placement on e5 in the future.} *

