1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {In response to Black's pin, white counters in kind. However, I believe this is simply not a good line. Even though the g5 -bishop got outside White's pawn chain, it still struggles to find its role in the game. Sometimes the bishop becomes a punching ball, as Black targets it with aggressive pawn advances on the kingside.} c5 {Putting immediate pressure on the center.} 5. d5 {This is almost universially played. The alternatives all have issues.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure after White has shown their hand in the center.} 6. bxc3 h6 7. Bh4 d6 8. e3 {White doesn't want to commit the pawn to e4 , as it would often be blocking its own bishop or standing in the way of a white knight coming to e4 instead.} e5 9. Qc2 {This is the mainline of the 4. Bg5 line, but here I have a awesome plan, suggested by the strategic brilliance of the AI-engine Leela.} Kd7 {Black wants to go aggressive with the pawns on the kingside, but that would leave the king exposed. So first order of business: Get the king safe. Then push pawns.} 10. Nf3 Kc7 11. Nd2 {White continues the standard maneuvering, but Black's plan is significantly more intimidating.} g5 {Push 'em!} 12. Bg3 Nh5 {This isn't about capturing white's bishop pair at all -- in fact the bishop on g3 is white's worst piece, completely shut out of play by Black's pawns. Our plan is f5 , getting even more pawns involved.} 13. Be2 Ng7 14. O-O {Feels wrong, with Black's pawn storm about to begin on that side of the board.} f5 15. f4 {White really needs to play this to block Black's advances.} gxf4 16. exf4 e4 {I don't see white doing anything scary close to Black's king, while Black is ready for h5 - h4 , and using the open g-file to pressure towards White's king. Black is much better.} *

