1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {In response to Black's pin, white counters in kind. However, I believe this is simply not a good line. Even though the g5 -bishop got outside White's pawn chain, it still struggles to find its role in the game. Sometimes the bishop becomes a punching ball, as Black targets it with aggressive pawn advances on the kingside.} c5 {Putting immediate pressure on the center.} 5. d5 {This is almost universially played. The alternatives all have issues.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure after White has shown their hand in the center.} 6. bxc3 h6 7. Bh4 d6 8. Nf3 {A sensible developing move, but it doesn’t help in controlling e4 , so the knight will have to continue to d2 afterwards.} g5 9. Bg3 e5 {Once again Black chooses to close down the position. Placing the pawns on the dark squares limits the scope of White’s bishop.} 10. Nd2 ({White is ready for e4,  but in this variation, there’s no reason to let them do it.} 10. Qc2 {prevents ... Bf5 , but when you move the queen away from d1 it makes the plan with ... Nh5 followed by ... f5 much easier than when the queen is on d1 eyeing the h5 -square.} Nh5 11. Nd2 f5 {Black starts a kingside expansion. In a perfect world, we’ll manage to follow it up with the very clever ... Kd7 - c7 -plan to get the king out of trouble, before resuming the kingside aggression. Black has very interesting chances.}) 10... Bf5 {The bishop gets a great location, and we stop e4 in the process.} 11. f3 {White tries to get ready for e4 once again, but we’re in time to stop it.} e4 12. Qb1 {This is an attempt at punishing Black’s concept, with both b7 and e4 under attack. Fortunately, we can protect both:} Qe7 13. fxe4 (13. Bxd6 $4 {This doesn't work out for White, as the queen will get stuck on a8 .} Qxd6 14. Qxb7 e3 {This is a nice move to further prevent White's development.} 15. Qxa8 Qb6 {I love this move for its in-your-face attributes. The pawn on e3 is completely restricting White, so we won't give it up, even for a piece.} 16. Nb3 O-O {-+ The queen will be trapped on a8 after ... Bd7 and ... Na6 and there's nothing White can do to stop it.}) 13... Bg6 {Brilliant! We want to take back on e4 , but the timing has to be right. It's not like the pawn is running away.} 14. e3 Nbd7 {Getting the knight to e5 is top priority, and it turns out the pawn on b7 is very poisonous.} 15. Bd3 ({If} 15. Qxb7 $4 {Black can start a devastating attack.} Rb8 16. Qc6 {The queen is seemingly in a good attacking position, but it was needed in defense, and the next moves showcase why.} Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Qxe4 18. Be2 Qxe3 {White's king is unable to run away, and will be checkmated momentarily!}) 15... Nh5 {Amazing play! Get rid of the bishop and then establish the knight safely on e5 . Black has a great position despite being down on material because of White's horrible pawn structure and passive pieces.} *

