1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Qb3 {Attempts to put immediate pressure on the bishop, hoping to push it away from its pressure towards White's king.} Bxc3+ {Black gives up the bishop pair voluntarily but hopes to exploit what has become a significant development advantage.} 8. Qxc3 d5 9. Bg2 {is the main move.} e5 {This transposes to the line starting with 8.Qb3 .} *

