1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Qb3 {Attempts to put immediate pressure on the bishop, hoping to push it away from its pressure towards White's king.} Bxc3+ {Black gives up the bishop pair voluntarily but hopes to exploit what has become a significant development advantage.} 8. Qxc3 d5 9. Bg5 {This is a super interesting attempt from White and leads to very complicated play.} (9. Bg2 {is the main move, but after} e5 {it transposes to the line starting with 8. Qb3 .}) 9... e5 {Black strikes in the center.} 10. Nb3 {This is the best square for the knight, since now White has a good response to 10... d4 .} dxc4 {That's why we go for this, when we open up files and diagonals to exploit Black's development advantage.} (10... d4 {namely} 11. Qa5 {with good play for White who has the bishop pair and a fantastic diagonal for the soon-to-be fianchettoed bishop on g2 .}) 11. Qxc4 {Allows Black to coordinate the pieces well.} Be6 12. Qh4 Nbd7 {The bishop found a good home and the other knight protects its buddy from giving Black doubled pawns.} 13. Bg2 h6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 {Black got the better of it from the opening, as there is no need to fear Bxb7 .} 15. Bxb7 Rb8 {Black's rook will have nice pressure down the newly opened b-file.} *

