1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. Qb3 {Since the main line with cxd5 allows black to get the knight involved, this is the move white would like to play -- however, it has its own drawbacks.} Bxc3+ {There's no time to lose -- we give away the bishop pair to then exploit our development advantage.} 9. Qxc3 e5 10. Nb3 (10. Nf3 $2 {this allows black to advance in the center with} d4 11. Qd2 Nc6 {when black has a good position.}) 10... Nc6 ({In this line I don't like} 10... d4 {because of} 11. Qa5 {when white sits pretty with the bishop pair and a brilliant diagonal for the g2 -bishop.}) 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Qc5 {Puts immediate pressure on black's center, but it also allows nice coordination between black's pieces.} Be6 13. O-O Rc8 {Black got the pieces out fast, and white's queen is vulnerable on c5 .} 14. Rd1 {is the only question, but then the tactics work in black's favor:} Nd4 15. Qxa7 Nc3 16. bxc3 Nxe2+ 17. Kh1 Qxd1+ {With checkmate next.} *

