night to d4 , and need to eliminate White's knight to make it happen.} 14. axb3 Nd4 15. O-O {It was absolutely crucial to get the king to safety, even at the cost of a pawn.} Nxe2+ 16. Kh1 h6 17. Be3 {White is down a pawn, but it's still a question of whether white is better or not. The bishops are brilliantly placed pointing towards Black's queenside pawns, and black is happy to give away a pawn to get rid of white's bishop pair. Also, losing the b-pawn isn't the end of the world, as it allows for a rook to put pressure on White's doubled b-pawns.} Nd4 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. Bg2 {Black will lose the a7 -pawn at some point, but likewise it will be very difficult to keep hold of the b-pawns for white. The most likely scenario is that Black will give away a pawn in the center to get rid of White's bishop pair, and we're left with an equal position. Beware of the potential undermining move f4 though -- it's still Black who needs to be accurate.} a5 {My recommended line starts here.} 20. Rfd1 (20. Qxa5 $6 Nc2 {achieves what we're trying to do: Exchange off the dark-squared bishop.}) 20... Qe8 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Qxd4 Rxb3 23. Rxa5 Qe2 {When Black will regain the b2 -pawn with an equal position.} *

