1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. Qb3 {Since the main line with cxd5 allows black to get the knight involved, this is the move white would like to play -- however, it has its own drawbacks.} Bxc3+ {There's no time to lose -- we give away the bishop pair to then exploit our development advantage.} 9. bxc3 {This may look weird, but it's not really doubling the pawns as the pawn on c4 will be exchanged very soon. However, doubled or not, the pawn on c3 is a strategic disadvantage as a black rook may put pressure down the c-file.} Nc6 (9... dxc4 $6 {is not advised on account of} 10. Qa3 {this is a cool pawn sacrifice where white gets open files for the rooks, great diagonals and the bishop pair. Also, note how the c3 -pawn is no longer a weakness since there's a black pawn blocking the c-file! I would advise staying away from this line as Black.}) 10. cxd5 {White undoubles the pawns at the first opportunity.} Na5 ({In this situation we want to take back on d5 with the knight, to keep our pawn structure intact} 10... Z0 {but now we need to avoid Nxc6 , so the knight moves away with an attack on white's queen. If white had played} 11. Nxc6 {first, we would be happy, as then} bxc6 {cxd5 cxd5 keeps the pawns together and gives us an extra pawn in the center.}) 11. Qc2 Nxd5 12. O-O Bd7 {Black's plan is very straight-forward: We want the rook on the c-file to put pressure on the c3 -pawn as soon as possible.} 13. e4 Nb6 {White managed to chase our knight away, but at a big cost: the White pawn on e4 is now blocking for the bishop. White's strategic problems with the c3 -pawn mean conventional play will only bring misery -- White needs to attack immediately!} 14. e5 Rc8 15. Be4 h6 {White put pressure on our pawn, and since we don't want to play g6 and weaken the dark squares, we play h6 instead. But here white has a very scary attack planned.} 16. Qe2 {White's scheme the last couple of moves seem pretty silly, but there's a lot of venom to it. The plan is moving the bishop back and then creating the queen and bishop battery towards Black's king. A plan that's difficult to stop since we've committed to h6 , so any g6 -move to block the diagonal will leave the h6 -pawn in trouble. Accuracy is needed.} Nd5 (16... Na4 $6 {I would not recommend this move, but I'm using it as an illustration of how much trouble White's plan can create.} 17. Bc2 Nxc3 18. Qd3 {Yes, black won a pawn, but White managed to complete their plan. Black's king is in serious danger after} f5 $1 19. exf6 Qxf6 20. Ba3 {White's rook is coming to e1 , the queen to h7 -- I would be very uncomfortable as Black.}) 17. Bc2 Ba4 {This fantastic move is why we went to d5 with the knight instead of a4 : We wanted to keep the a4 -square available for the bishop!} 18. Bd3 (18. Bxa4 $2 {allows a sweet tactic with} Nxc3 19. Qg4 Qxd4 $1 20. Qxd4 Ne2+ 21. Kg2 Nxd4 {when Black won a pawn.}) 18... Nxc3 {The key difference is that White can't play Qd3 now, so the immediate assault is thwarted.} 19. Qg4 {White's attack is still going on though, so Black should strike immediately.} f5 {Enabling more defensive pieces around Black's king.} 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Qxe6+ {The problem with Ba4 is that the pawn on e6 is now undefended, but Black is happy to exchange queens, as White's attacking chances immediately disappear, and in the position that ensues, Black's pieces are incredibly well-placed.} Qxe6 22. Nxe6 Rfe8 23. Nd4 Nc4 {Yes, White has the bishop pair, but how to use it?} 24. Bf4 g5 {White's pieces are unable to find safe positions. Black is better.} *

