1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. O-O {This is a clever attempt to get the king out of the way, while also luring Black to move the pawn away from d5 which will open up for White's bishop on g2 . However, a pawn is a pawn, so we'll take the challenge.} dxc4 9. Qa4 {We wanna make it as difficult as possible for white to regain the pawn on c4 , so the bishop isn't going anywhere. Black normally plays Na6 here, but I think using the pawn instead might be even better.} a5 10. Rd1 {Protects the knight on d4 while preparing Qb5 , which will cause trouble for the c4 -pawn.} (10. Ndb5 $2 {This is a common move if Black plays Na6 instead of a5 , but here it leaves white in trouble.} Bd7 11. Bxb7 $2 Ra7 {This is the key difference! Since we used our pawn to protect the bishop on b4 , we've also created an escape square for the rook.} 12. Bg2 Qe8 {The pin on White's knight will result in a great position for Black.}) 10... Bd7 {A nice development move, but also a key move that stops White's plan of Qb5 .} 11. Qc2 Qb6 {White is struggling to win back the pawn on c4 .} 12. Ne4 {This is a good try from white: Opening up for the queen towards Black's pawn, while also trying to remove a defender of Black's king.} Nd5 {This is a brilliant defence! In short: It's about keeping the knights on the board, so that White's bishop on c1 can't find a safe square. We're willing to give up the pawn on c4 , since that will allow Black's rooks to enter the game.} 13. Ng5 (13. Qxc4 Nc6 14. Nc2 Rac8 {is nice for Black. White's queen struggles to find a safe square.}) 13... Nf6 14. Be3 {White's bishop finds a great square, pointing towards Black's queen -- but it's only temporary.} Qa6 {Moving the queen away from the e3 -bishop's diagonal while simultaneously defending the c4 -pawn -- can you ask for more from a single move?} 15. Rac1 h6 16. Ne4 Nd5 {This is the key. We've managed to keep the knights on the board, and after chasing White's attacking knight away with h6 , we can go back to d5 and harrass White's bishop on e3 . We will capture it next move if allowed, and Black is doing fine.} *

