1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black gets the knight involved, but at the same time White gets pressure against the d5 -knight too. That's important because it increases the likelihood of the d5 -knight being exchanged, which would leave the g2 -bishop a force to be reckoned with. But first White needs to deal with the threats we've made toward the c3 -knight.} 9. Bd2 {Looks very innocent, but it gets the pieces out quickly.} Nxc3 {I prefer to keep the bishop pair in this instance.} 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Rb1 {White immediately coordinates the forces against Black's b7 -pawn, but we solve the problem with a pawn sacrifice.} Nd7 {We're willing to give up the b7 -pawn in order to get the pieces out, and hopefully a fantastic knight on c4 long-term.} 12. Bxb7 {This is the straight-forward method of winning a pawn, but Black gets very nice coordination:} Bxb7 13. Rxb7 Qc8 14. Rb1 Nb6 15. O-O Nc4 {White got castled and has a pawn up, but even so Black has an excellent position. There are nice files for the rooks to put pressure on, and the knight on c4 is an absolute beast.} *

