1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black gets the knight involved, but at the same time White gets pressure against the d5 -knight too. That's important because it increases the likelihood of the d5 -knight being exchanged, which would leave the g2 -bishop a force to be reckoned with. But first White needs to deal with the threats we've made toward the c3 -knight.} 9. Bd2 {Looks very innocent, but it gets the pieces out quickly.} Nxc3 {I prefer to keep the bishop pair in this instance.} 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Rb1 {White immediately coordinates the forces against Black's b7 -pawn, but we solve the problem with a pawn sacrifice.} Nd7 {We're willing to give up the b7 -pawn in order to get the pieces out, and hopefully a fantastic knight on c4 long-term.} 12. Rxb7 {This is the fancy way of winning a pawn, and forcing further exchanges in the process.} (12. O-O {White can try to keep the tension, claiming that the b7 -pawn will be a long-term target, but that allows us to guard against the threats.} Nb6 {Black wants to go e5 without having to worry about the white knight getting to f5 . If White tries to stop it with} 13. Bf4 {Black can change focus to targeting the f4 -bishop, while using the knight to block White's rook/bishop combo towards the b7 -pawn.} Nd5 {Black is doing well.}) 12... Bxb7 13. Bxb7 Bf6 (13... Rb8 $2 {fails to} 14. Nc6 {when white gets to keep the all-important bishop, while still getting back the rook.}) 14. Bxa8 Qxa8 15. O-O {Since white has castled with an extra pawn, one could assume Black is in trouble -- but the coordination of Black's forces is about to be supreme.} Rc8 {First put pressure on the c3 -pawn, then maneuver the knight to c4 . If white is careless in trying to protect the extra pawn, they can end up with a very passive position. For example:} 16. Qa1 Nb6 17. Rc1 {White's last moves were natural to make sure the c3 -pawn is well defended, but it also allows Black to demonstrate the importance of active pieces.} Nc4 18. Be1 e5 19. Nf3 Qe4 {Black has a serious initiative. All of White's pieces are passive in their defense of the c3 -pawn.} *

