1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black gets the knight involved, but at the same time White gets pressure against the d5 -knight too. That's important because it increases the likelihood of the d5 -knight being exchanged, which would leave the g2 -bishop a force to be reckoned with. But first White needs to deal with the threats we've made toward the c3 -knight.} 9. Qb3 {A multi-purpose move: It puts pressure on Black's pieces on b4 and d5 , as well as defending the c3 -knight. But Black can reenforce all of those squares:} Qa5 10. O-O {is a tricky pawn sacrifice once played by Carlsen, but accurate play gives Black a nice position.} Nxc3 11. a3 {This is the point: White hunts for the bishop pair -- but a spectacular defensive move renders White's gambit dull.} Nc6 {There's so many available captures, but Black emerges okay in all scenarios.} 12. Bxc6 ({This is the big test of Black's play, as capturing the bishop back with bxc6 gives white the upper hand after} 12. Qxb4 {.}) (12. bxc3 {leads to mass exchanges.} Bxc3 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxc6 Bxa1 15. Bxa8 Ba6 16. Bf3 Bd4 {Black is fine with active bishops.}) 12... Bc5 {This is the key. White faces a difficult choice of which important piece should survive -- the knight on d4 or the bishop on c6 . In either case, getting rid of either eases Black's game.} (12... bxc6 $2 13. Qxb4 Qxb4 14. axb4 Nd5 15. Bd2 {when Black's bishop is a sad sight, and White's rook will enter play much quicker than black's.}) 13. Qxc3 Qxc3 14. bxc3 bxc6 15. Be3 {is one way forward for White...} f6 ({I'm tempted by this cool move, sacrificing a pawn for the long-term advantage of destroying White's pawn structure with e5 next. Note the immediate 15...e5 is not as good because of after} 15... e5 $2 16. Nxc6 Bxe3 17. Ne7+ {when Black's king is unable to join the party. So we need the f7 -square for the king first.}) 16. Nxc6 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Rf7 {Black will get the rook to c7 , the king to f7 , and the pawn to e5 , beautifully restricting White's pieces and with excellent compensation for a pawn.} *

