1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. g3 {This is White's main choice, trying to exploit the long diagonal for the bishop. A fianchettoed bishop is more valuable when Black can't block its path with pawns. That's why White chooses to go for the fianchetto when Black no longer has the option to play c6 .} cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 {The white bishop finds a magnificent home on the long diagonal, but black counters with immediate threats in the center, now that we've gotten our king to safety, while white's king remain in the danger zone.} d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black gets the knight involved, but at the same time White gets pressure against the d5 -knight too. That's important because it increases the likelihood of the d5 -knight being exchanged, which would leave the g2 -bishop a force to be reckoned with. But first White needs to deal with the threats we've made toward the c3 -knight.} 9. Qb3 {A multi-purpose move: It puts pressure on Black's pieces on b4 and d5 , as well as defending the c3 -knight. But Black can reenforce all of those squares:} Qa5 10. Bd2 {This is the main line. White tries to neutralize the sting of Black's queen and bishop pointing towards White's king.} Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {The bad news is that Black has voluntarily taken on a bad pawn structure. The pawn on c6 will be a target. However, the good news is that the c8 -bishop that often struggles in this line will find a fantastic home on a6 soon.} 12. O-O Bxc3 ({Timing is everything. If} 12... Ba6 {White wins after} 13. Nxd5 Bxd2 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Nxc6 {so it's important to capture on c3 first.}) 13. Bxc3 {Gives away White's bishop pair, but in my opinion this is an underrated option.} Nxc3 14. Qxc3 {Gives Black nothing to fear.} Qxc3 15. bxc3 Ba6 16. Bf3 Rab8 {Although some accuracy is still needed.} 17. Rfb1 Rfd8 18. Kf1 c5 19. Rb3 {This is a key motif in these lines. We don't want to capture on b3 , which would unite White's pawns and open up the a-file for White's rook. Fortunately, we can employ the same plan ourselves:} Rb6 {Black is fine.} 20. Rab1 Rdd6 {Allows black to keep control of the b-file.} *

