portant to capture on c3 first.}) 13. bxc3 Ba6 {Black got the bishop active and is ready to play Rb8 , starting counterplay against White's queen -- but White still has some tricks.} 14. Rfd1 {A brilliant move. The two most obvious options are Rab8 and Bxe2 , but both are bad.} Qc5 {It's very important to stop white from playing c4 .} (14... Bxe2 $6 15. c4 $1 Bxd1 16. Rxd1 Qc7 17. cxd5 cxd5 {The bishop pair is so good, black is much worse despite getting a rook and two central pawns in return. So we avoid this line.}) (14... Rab8 $2 15. c4 Qc5 16. cxd5 $3 {A brilliant queen sacrifice!} Rxb3 17. axb3 Bxe2 18. Re1 $1 Bb5 19. dxc6 {White's passed pawn is so strong, White has a winning position despite losing the queen for a rook and bishop. If Black tries to get rid of the pawn with} Bxc6 $2 {then} 20. Rac1 {wins back the bishop, as counterattacking with} Qd6 {allows} 21. Bf4 {when White gets to keep both bishops and win the game.}) 15. e4 {How can Black justify going into this line? White has the bishop pair, and now the well-placed knight in the center is getting kicked back. The key is the c4 -square, where Black is able to place a piece without any white pawns around to prevent them.} Bc4 16. Qa4 (16. Qc2 {Puts White's queen on a less vulnerable square, but it's also a square where she is unable to influence the game.} Nb6 17. a4 (17. Be3 Qa3 {blocks the a-pawn from moving forward.}) 17... Qa5 {it seems awkward to use the queen as a blockader, but we really wanted to stop White from playing a5 next. Now that White's plan has been prevented, Black can focus on plan of their own next. A rook to the d-file, placing pawns on dark squares to work well with the light-squared bishop, and hopefully getting the knight to c4 at some point.}) 16... Nb6 17. Qb4 Qh5 18. Be3 Be2 19. Rd2 Rab8 ({Black needs to be very accurate.} 19... Nc4 {immediately would fall into a very clever trap.} 20. g4 $1 {creating disruption in Black's coordination. After} Qxg4 21. f3 $1 {Black can't save both the knight and the bishop.} Bxf3 22. Qxc4 {with a winning position for white.}) 20. Qd4 {Centralizing the queen causes Black the maximum of troubles.} c5 {After researching the position extensively, I believe this pawn sacrifice is Black's best bet.} ({It's still important to stay away from} 20... Nc4 $4 21. g4 $1 {because of} Qxg4 22. f3 $1 Bxf3 23. Qxc4 {winning for White, just like last time.}) 21. Qxc5 Nc4 {This is the key -- we get the Nc4 -move we've been wanting to play for so long.} 22. Qxh5 {The queen exchange is the best option, as White's extra pawn is surprisingly valuable.} (22. g4 $4 {is just nonsense now, with Black winning a rook after} Qxc5 23. Bxc5 Nxd2) (22. Rc2 {Gets the rook away from danger, but it's kinda stuck on c2 . After} a5 {Black is happy to stay a pawn down since Black's rooks will dominate the open files contrary to their white counterparts, not to mention the fantastic knight on c4 .}) (22. Rd7 $6 {would be good if not for Black's immediate attack after} Ne5 23. Rxa7 $2 Rb5 $1 24. Qd6 Nf3+ 25. Bxf3 Bxf3 {when the material count favors white, yet the position massively favors Black, as the light-squares around White's king reek of Black's checkmating intentions.}) 22... Bxh5 23. Rd7 Nxe3 24. fxe3 {Initially I assumed this position would be an easy draw for Black, as White's pawn structure is absolutely horrible. However, White's a-pawn is capable of creating lots of trouble as black picks up one pawn after another on the other side of the board.} Rfc8 25. Rxa7 Rxc3 26. a4 h6 {Once again we need an escape path for Black's king.} 27. a5 {is too impatient, as Black is able to create counterplay against White's king...} Rbc8 28. a6 Rc1+ 29. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 30. Kf2 Rc2+ 31. Kg1 Rc1+ {There's nowhere to run for the king without losing the bishop.} *

