1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. dxc5 {This could be good if Black had to move the bishop a second time to recapture the pawn, but we have more aggressive intentions.} Ne4 6. Qc2 {Doesn't put enough pressure on Black's position.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nxc5 {Black has successfully destroyed White's pawn structure and regained the pawn. Sooner or later we'll be able to get the rook to the c-file, when it will exert pressure towards the weak white pawns on c4 and c3 .} 8. g3 b6 {is a smart reply, when White is denied any hope of pressure on the long diagonal...} 9. Bg2 Bb7 {Black has achieved everything you dream of in a Nimzo-Indian.} *

