1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. dxc5 {This could be good if Black had to move the bishop a second time to recapture the pawn, but we have more aggressive intentions.} Ne4 6. Qd4 {Queens are best placed in the center! Suddenly there are a lot of threats against Black's positions, but the tactics work in our favor if you know the key move.} Qf6 {A necessity, but also a great move!} 7. Qxe4 {White accepts the challenge.} Bxc3+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Qxb2 {After an intriguing couple of exchanges, Black's queen has gotten in a position to capture a couple of pawns back.} 10. Rb1 Qa3 {I prefer this to Qxa2 , since the c5 -pawn is a bigger threat to Black's position.} 11. g3 Qxc5 12. Bg2 O-O {We started the capture sequence a pawn down, but have reversed that to being a pawn up now! And we even got the king to safety! However, getting the pieces out will be a challenge, and we'll likely give up a pawn to make it happen.} 13. O-O Nc6 14. Qf4 d5 {Yes, the pawn will become weak on d5 , but we're already a pawn up, so getting central control and opening up for the bishop is just as important. Black has a decent game.} *

