1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. dxc5 {This could be good if Black had to move the bishop a second time to recapture the pawn, but we have more aggressive intentions.} Ne4 6. Qd4 {Queens are best placed in the center! Suddenly there are a lot of threats against Black's positions, but the tactics work in our favor if you know the key move.} Qf6 {A necessity, but also a great move!} 7. Qxf6 {is no good, since we are not afraid to give ourselves better central control...} gxf6 {The threat on c3 remains.} 8. Bd2 {This doesn't help as White's doubled pawns are far worse than Black's...} Bxc3 9. bxc3 Na6 {The c4 -pawn is in long-term trouble as Black coordinates the pieces and gets a rook (or two) to the c-file.} *

