[PlyCount "24"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. dxc5 {This could be good if Black had to move the bishop a second time to recapture the pawn, but we have more aggressive intentions.} Ne4 6. Qd4 {Queens are best placed in the center! Suddenly there are a lot of threats against Black's positions, but the tactics work in our favor if you know the key move.} Qf6 {A necessity, but also a great move!} 7. Bd2 {A purely defensive move, and we're happy to take the bishop.} Nxd2 8. Qxf6 {White wants to recapture with the king, but is hesitant to do so with the queens on the board. That's fine by us though, because we don't mind the doubled pawns -- if anything they will give us nice central control.} gxf6 9. Kxd2 Na6 {We could have taken on c5 with the bishop, but it's better to get a knight to that square.} 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Kxc3 Nxc5 12. Nd2 a5 {A key move, making sure white won't be able to play b4 kicking the knight away any time soon. The position is pretty equal.} *

