1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. e3 {White solidifies the center and gets a position that resembles the lines starting with 4. e3 . However, placing the knight on f3 early is a disadvantage compared to its 4. e3 cousin, and Black is in a position to take advantage of that fact.} Bxc3+ {What is this? Black captures on c3 without even being provoked? This is called the Hübner line , and the timing is not accidental. There are very specific elements in the position that makes this the right moment to strike: The knight on f3 means it's difficult for White to flood the center with pawns, as the f2 -pawn is blocked.   We also waited for e3 , since White's dark-squared bishop will be blocked behind its own pawns now. In fact, the c1 -bishop is the key to this line, as Black hopes to get a position with lots of pawns on the board, where the pawns (be it black or white) stand in the way of bishops, making knights more valuable. Hence the exchange of a bishop for a knight.} 6. bxc3 d6 7. Bd3 Nc6 {Notice how black delays castling. We don't want to commit our king too early. In some cases we may want to evacuate him to the queenside instead. In the meantime, in our bishop's absence, we're taking control of dark squares with the pawns. ... e5 is next.} 8. e4 {White tries to attack the center immediately.} e5 9. d5 Ne7 {This pawn structure is the key to the Hübner variation. White has a space advantage, but the blocked nature of the position make the bishop pair insignificant at the moment. Even so, White hopes to dominate all sides of the board by restricting the options for Black's knight before slowly but surely advancing the kingside pawns. This is typically achieved by maneuvering the remaining knight to e3 , while pushing the kingside pawns to f3 , g3 and h4 -- when Black has no active plan and is doomed to passivity until White has coordinated all the forces in optimal positions.  Then White typically advances the pawns even further for a kingside attack. To prevent this, Black often tries to push f5 , opening up the position for Black's f8 -rook and c8 -bishop, while keeping the status quo for White's most horrible piece; the bishop on c1 .} 10. Nd2 {This is part of a plan to stop the f5 -pawn break by maneuvering the knight to e3 . However, Black is in time to disturb White.} Ng6 11. Nf1 Qa5 {Inserting this move ties white's queen to the defence of the c3 -pawn, so that she can't attack Black's pawn on f4 . 'Well, there is no Black pawn on f4 ,' you say -- well: Move along.} 12. Qc2 Nf4 13. Bxf4 ({Forced, since the alternative} 13. Ne3 $2 {doesn't work because of a tactic} Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 Nxe4 {and Black wins.}) 13... exf4 14. g3 {It's absolutely crucial for White to remove the pawn on f4 . Mainly because the knight wants access to e3 , but also because a knight maneuver to e5 by the black knight would be extremely powerful as long as white doesn't have the option to chase the knight away.} fxg3 15. hxg3 Bd7 16. Ne3 O-O-O {White got the knight to e3 , has an open h-file for the rook, has many central pawns. Life is seemingly good, but there's a problem of where to put the king.} 17. f3 h5 {Grabbing space.} 18. Kf2 g5 {In two moves, Black's position went from seemingly bad to very exciting. The pawn advances on the kingside weren't obvious, but now that they're here we can see some sweet black plans -- h4 being the top candidate, loosening up the protection of White's king.} *

