 of the board by restricting the options for Black's knight before slowly but surely advancing the kingside pawns. This is typically achieved by maneuvering the remaining knight to e3 , while pushing the kingside pawns to f3 , g3 and h4 -- when Black has no active plan and is doomed to passivity until White has coordinated all the forces in optimal positions.  Then White typically advances the pawns even further for a kingside attack. To prevent this, Black often tries to push f5 , opening up the position for Black's f8 -rook and c8 -bishop, while keeping the status quo for White's most horrible piece; the bishop on c1 .} 10. O-O {This is one of those rare instances where castling is just plain bad. Black launches a surprise attack!} h6 11. Ne1 g5 {BOOM!} 12. f3 Kd7 {Brilliant! Black's king hides out on the queenside while White's king will find itself under heavy fire on the opposite side.} 13. Rf2 Kc7 14. Rb1 b6 {Before we continue our attack we need to keep the king safe.} 15. Rfb2 Rb8 {We've successfully protected the b6 -square.} 16. a4 a5 {Now there's no breakthrough for white on the queenside, while the kingside is free for the taking. Black has exciting attacking prospects.} *

