1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. e3 {White solidifies the center and gets a position that resembles the lines starting with 4. e3 . However, placing the knight on f3 early is a disadvantage compared to its 4. e3 cousin, and Black is in a position to take advantage of that fact.} Bxc3+ {What is this? Black captures on c3 without even being provoked? This is called the Hübner line , and the timing is not accidental. There are very specific elements in the position that makes this the right moment to strike: The knight on f3 means it's difficult for White to flood the center with pawns, as the f2 -pawn is blocked.   We also waited for e3 , since White's dark-squared bishop will be blocked behind its own pawns now. In fact, the c1 -bishop is the key to this line, as Black hopes to get a position with lots of pawns on the board, where the pawns (be it black or white) stand in the way of bishops, making knights more valuable. Hence the exchange of a bishop for a knight.} 6. bxc3 d6 7. Bd3 Nc6 {Notice how black delays castling. We don't want to commit our king too early. In some cases we may want to evacuate him to the queenside instead. In the meantime, in our bishop's absence, we're taking control of dark squares with the pawns. ... e5 is next.} 8. e4 {White tries to attack the center immediately.} e5 9. d5 Ne7 {This pawn structure is the key to the Hübner variation. White has a space advantage, but the blocked nature of the position make the bishop pair insignificant at the moment. Even so, White hopes to dominate all sides of the board by restricting the options for Black's knight before slowly but surely advancing the kingside pawns. This is typically achieved by maneuvering the remaining knight to e3 , while pushing the kingside pawns to f3 , g3 and h4 -- when Black has no active plan and is doomed to passivity until White has coordinated all the forces in optimal positions.  Then White typically advances the pawns even further for a kingside attack. To prevent this, Black often tries to push f5 , opening up the position for Black's f8 -rook and c8 -bishop, while keeping the status quo for White's most horrible piece; the bishop on c1 .} 10. Nh4 {This is white's main move -- the intention is to meet Ng6 with Nf5 , when Black becomes very cramped. Instead we try for a counterattack.} h6 {It may look like an innocent move, but Black's intention next is playing g5 .} 11. O-O {Given Black's plan, castling was never going to be the right counter. Black charges ahead.} g5 12. Nf5 {Tries to claim White gets the board-wide space advantage, but a tactical sequence gives Black a positional advantage.} Nxf5 13. exf5 e4 14. Re1 Bxf5 15. f3 {White wins back the pawn, but at what cost?} O-O 16. fxe4 Bg4 17. Qb3 Nd7 {Don't you just love it when tactics and strategy work hand-in-hand? The tactics allowed Black to temporarily win a pawn, and during the course of getting the pawn back, white has allowed the most magnificent square for Black's remaining knight on e5 . We don't even care about the pawn on b7 as long as we get to the e5 -square, as White's bishops are completely out of play -- blocked by both their own pawns as well as Black's pawns.} *

