 of the board by restricting the options for Black's knight before slowly but surely advancing the kingside pawns. This is typically achieved by maneuvering the remaining knight to e3 , while pushing the kingside pawns to f3 , g3 and h4 -- when Black has no active plan and is doomed to passivity until White has coordinated all the forces in optimal positions.  Then White typically advances the pawns even further for a kingside attack. To prevent this, Black often tries to push f5 , opening up the position for Black's f8 -rook and c8 -bishop, while keeping the status quo for White's most horrible piece; the bishop on c1 .} 10. Nh4 {This is white's main move -- the intention is to meet Ng6 with Nf5 , when Black becomes very cramped. Instead we try for a counterattack.} h6 {It may look like an innocent move, but Black's intention next is playing g5 .} 11. f4 {This is White's justification of the Nh4 -line. When Black doesn't play Ng6 immediately getting more pawns involved in the center becomes a good option.} ({exf4? may be tempting, but it's a big mistake. After} 11. Bf4 g5 {Black seemingly wins a piece, but White generates a powerful attack, starting with e5↑ It's best to just stay away.}) 11... Ng6 {Perfect timing! The threat against the f4 -pawn means that Nf5 is no longer available for White.} 12. Nxg6 fxg6 {We're not afraid to get doubled pawns. We'll use the f-file to our advantage, and having more pawns close to the king can be beneficial.} 13. O-O O-O 14. f5 {is met by a fantastic counterstrike.} b5 {Creating chaos on White's light-squares.} 15. g4 gxf5 16. gxf5 bxc4 17. Bc2 {This is white's best bet. Playing it like a pawn sacrifice, trying to point pieces towards Black's king. However, we can beat White to that attacking plan.} Kh7 18. Kh1 Rg8 19. Rg1 g6 {As it turns out, White's king is just as vulnerable as Black's when we remove the f5 -pawn and get our c8 -bishop involved. Both sides are attacking, but white's c2 -bishop is out of play. As a result, Black is doing well.} *

