1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. e3 {White solidifies the center and gets a position that resembles the lines starting with 4. e3 . However, placing the knight on f3 early is a disadvantage compared to its 4. e3 cousin, and Black is in a position to take advantage of that fact.} Bxc3+ {What is this? Black captures on c3 without even being provoked? This is called the Hübner line , and the timing is not accidental. There are very specific elements in the position that makes this the right moment to strike: The knight on f3 means it's difficult for White to flood the center with pawns, as the f2 -pawn is blocked.   We also waited for e3 , since White's dark-squared bishop will be blocked behind its own pawns now. In fact, the c1 -bishop is the key to this line, as Black hopes to get a position with lots of pawns on the board, where the pawns (be it black or white) stand in the way of bishops, making knights more valuable. Hence the exchange of a bishop for a knight.} 6. bxc3 d6 7. Bd3 Nc6 {Notice how black delays castling. We don't want to commit our king too early. In some cases we may want to evacuate him to the queenside instead. In the meantime, in our bishop's absence, we're taking control of dark squares with the pawns. ... e5 is next.} 8. O-O e5 9. Ng5 ({is a tricky move, trying to involve the rook on f1.} 9. e4 {is best met by} h6 {when the position remains similar to the lines we’ve examined previously in the chapter. In fact, if White then continues} 10. d5 {we’ve transposed to Kasparov Sidelines where Black will have amazing attacking chances with ... g5 coming soon.}) 9... O-O 10. f4 {It's best to keep the f4 -pawn alive.} exd4 {It's very important to use the e-pawn when capturing on d4 , as otherwise white would be able to open up the f-file for the rook.} 11. cxd4 cxd4 12. exd4 {White's pawn structure may look healthier than we've ever seen before in this line, but we're about to give White a difficult choice. First we kick back White's knight.} h6 13. Nf3 d5 {Now White faces a tough choice. If Black is allowed to take on c4 , white will be left with an isolated pawn in the center. However, the only way to prevent that is by playing c5 , but then the c1 -bishop will once again be blocked by its own. So even though we temporarily corrected white's pawn structure, it remain a source of trouble.} *

