1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 ({This is known as the Kasparov variation,  which in itself is reason enough to take it very seriously. It's a logical developing move, but has one drawback: White loses the flexibility one has in the 4. e3 line, where the knight often is placed on e2 instead. In fact, the line} 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {is considered favorable for White. However, since the knight has committed itself to f3 , we can strike in the center immediately with c5 .}) 4... c5 5. e3 {White solidifies the center and gets a position that resembles the lines starting with 4. e3 . However, placing the knight on f3 early is a disadvantage compared to its 4. e3 cousin, and Black is in a position to take advantage of that fact.} Bxc3+ {What is this? Black captures on c3 without even being provoked? This is called the Hübner line , and the timing is not accidental. There are very specific elements in the position that makes this the right moment to strike: The knight on f3 means it's difficult for White to flood the center with pawns, as the f2 -pawn is blocked.   We also waited for e3 , since White's dark-squared bishop will be blocked behind its own pawns now. In fact, the c1 -bishop is the key to this line, as Black hopes to get a position with lots of pawns on the board, where the pawns (be it black or white) stand in the way of bishops, making knights more valuable. Hence the exchange of a bishop for a knight.} 6. bxc3 d6 7. Bd3 Nc6 {Notice how black delays castling. We don't want to commit our king too early. In some cases we may want to evacuate him to the queenside instead. In the meantime, in our bishop's absence, we're taking control of dark squares with the pawns. ... e5 is next.} 8. O-O e5 9. Nd2 (9. d5 $2 Ne7 10. e4 h6 {transposes to the lines we analyzed previously with 8. e4 , when black can create a cool attack with g5 next.}) 9... O-O {It's okay to castle now because we're in time to play f5 should white close the center.} 10. Re1 {This is best, and a tricky move. White leaves the f1 -square open, so that the knight can maneuver to e3 via f1 in the future, after playing d5 and e4 . The question is: What is the best way for Black to pass the time while waiting for White to make a decision about the central pawns? The most common move is 10... Re8 , but I would rather keep the rook on f8 , to help facilitate the f5 -pawn advance in the future.   After some deliberations, I've decided h6 is the best waiting move. Note that taking the d4 -pawn is ill-advisable.} h6 (10... cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. exd4 Nxd4 {White gets a tremendous pair of bishops pointing down the board after} 13. Bb2 {The whole philosophy of this line is to let White's dark-squared bishop suffer, blockaded by pawns. We don't want to give White this much freedom, even if we do win a pawn in the process.}) 11. d5 Ne7 12. e4 Nh7 {This is the key idea! We're ready to go f5 as soon as possible - so it was very important we kept the rook on f8 , and also found a nice square where the knight could retreat and let the pawn march forward.} 13. Nf1 f5 {Black was successful in playing f5 before white's knight arrived to create trouble. By opening up for the c8 -bishop and f8 -rook, Black has a good game. Keep in mind White's dark-squared bishop is still a horrible piece, its potential blocked by Black's strategy of placing pawns on dark squares.} *

