1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. f3 {This is very aggressive, immediately planning to swarm the center with White pawns. However, it makes for very slow development and in addition that pressure on d4 comes in very handy now.} Nc6 7. e4 d6 {So far, so good. We're preventing White from lunging further forward with e5 , but it's also key that we have the knight and pawn putting pressure on d4 . As a result, White's favored development scheme with Bd3 and Ne2 is temporarily prevented, which means White can't get the pieces out as quickly.} 8. Be3 {White protects d4 while at the same time attacking c5 . But the bishop would rather be on g5 in these lines, and protecting c5 is no problem for Black because b6 is a part of the long-term plan of attacking c4 anyway.} (8. Bd3 $2 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 {is a clean extra pawn for Black.}) 8... b6 {Protecting c5 while also getting ready for a bishop out to a6 .} 9. Bd3 Na5 10. Ne2 {Positions like these would be pretty good for White if the knight could get to d2 and protect c4 , when White would have a free reign on the kingside with a huge space advantage. However, as it is the c4 -pawn creates a huge headache for White.} Ba6 11. O-O Qc7 {By moving the queen we sidestep any Bg5 trouble, while leaving a lot of flexibility in Black's position, including the option to castle queenside.} (11... O-O {? is a strategic mistake. After} 12. Bg5 {White will force black to go h6 and g5 to get the queen out of the g5 -bishop's pin, leaving White with good attacking chances even after the loss of the c4 -pawn.} ({Don't rush with Bxc4?? as White win a piece and the game after Bxc4 Nxc4} 12. Qa4)) 12. f4 O-O-O {Black gets the king out of harm's way while still threatening on c4 and having pressure on White's over-extended center.} *

