1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. f3 {This is very aggressive, immediately planning to swarm the center with White pawns. However, it makes for very slow development and in addition that pressure on d4 comes in very handy now.} Nc6 7. e4 d6 {So far, so good. We're preventing White from lunging further forward with e5 , but it's also key that we have the knight and pawn putting pressure on d4 . As a result, White's favored development scheme with Bd3 and Ne2 is temporarily prevented, which means White can't get the pieces out as quickly.} 8. Ne2 {With this move White tries to get all the pieces quickly to the kingside, creating an attack there. But we're not gonna put our king in the danger zone. It's time to attack the c4 -pawn.} b6 9. Ng3 Na5 {Black has a clear plan of going after the c4 -pawn, while at the same time avoiding kingside castling as that would allow White to go Bg5 and create an attack.} (9... Ba6 $4 {would be a terrible mistake on account of} 10. Qa4 {when there's pressure on both of Black's pieces. If the bishop retreats with} Bb7 {There's still} 11. d5 {winning a piece and the game.}) 10. Bd3 {As the pressure on d4 is released, White is able to get the bishop to its favored location, but at this point, it's all about the c4 -pawn.} Ba6 11. d5 {Pushing in the center protects the c4 -pawn by preventing cxd4 followed by Rc8 , but the c4 -pawn remains a target for Black.} O-O {it's safe to castle because Bg5 is met by h6 , when Bh4 is impossible due to g5 , and we see the unfortunate consequence of having the knight land on g3 early on.} 12. Qe2 {Now that Black has castled, the c4 -pawn needed defending.} (12. Bg5 $2 h6 13. Bh4 $2 g5) 12... Nb3 {There are more aggressive options than this, but I like it for its simplicity. We take out the biggest threat to Black's position: the dark-squared bishop.} 13. Rb1 Nxc1 14. Rxc1 e5 {Pushing forward prevents f4 from white, while showcasing how the dark-squared central pawns work nicely together with Black's bishop. The same can not be said for White's light-squared bishop which is being blocked by its own pawns. In addition, White has to live with the annoying doubled c-pawns for the rest of the game.} 15. h4 Bc8 {Black can play on both sides of the board. Long-term we'd like to play either b5 or f5 . Until then normal moves would be something like Bd7 , Rb8 , a6 , h6 , g6 , Kh7 , Ne8 - g7 .} *

