1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. f3 {This is very aggressive, immediately planning to swarm the center with White pawns. However, it makes for very slow development and in addition that pressure on d4 comes in very handy now.} Nc6 7. e4 d6 {So far, so good. We're preventing White from lunging further forward with e5 , but it's also key that we have the knight and pawn putting pressure on d4 . As a result, White's favored development scheme with Bd3 and Ne2 is temporarily prevented, which means White can't get the pieces out as quickly.} 8. Ne2 {With this move White tries to get all the pieces quickly to the kingside, creating an attack there. But we're not gonna put our king in the danger zone. It's time to attack the c4 -pawn.} b6 9. Ng3 Na5 {Black has a clear plan of going after the c4 -pawn, while at the same time avoiding kingside castling as that would allow White to go Bg5 and create an attack.} (9... Ba6 $4 {would be a terrible mistake on account of} 10. Qa4 {when there's pressure on both of Black's pieces. If the bishop retreats with} Bb7 {There's still} 11. d5 {winning a piece and the game.}) 10. Bd3 {As the pressure on d4 is released, White is able to get the bishop to its favored location, but at this point, it's all about the c4 -pawn.} Ba6 11. O-O {White goes all-in on generating an attack against Black's king, basically admitting that the c4 -pawn will be lost.} cxd4 {Not the move we normally would want to make, as it undoubles White's pawns, but on the plus side we're opening up the c-file for the rook to contribute to the attack on White's c4 -pawn.} (11... Bxc4 $4 {doesn't work because of} 12. Bxc4 Nxc4 13. Qa4+ {winning a piece.}) 12. cxd4 Rc8 {The c4 -pawn has been surrounded.} 13. Bg5 (13. f4 {is White's best bet according to the engines. After} Bxc4 14. f5 h6 {Black prevents Bg5 and it's White who needs to play accurately to secure a draw with a pawn down.}) 13... h6 {The pin on Black's queen must be dealt with immediately.} 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qa4+ {The problem with white luring our queen out on the board is that the king sits there undefended, but we have an unexpected reply.} Kd8 {As it turns out, the king is perfectly safe in the center!} 16. e5 {White tries sacrificing pawns to open up files toward the king.} Qf4 {Calmly played, when there's too many White pieces in trouble, and Black has a winning position.} *

