1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. f3 {This is very aggressive, immediately planning to swarm the center with White pawns. However, it makes for very slow development and in addition that pressure on d4 comes in very handy now.} Nc6 7. e4 d6 {So far, so good. We're preventing White from lunging further forward with e5 , but it's also key that we have the knight and pawn putting pressure on d4 . As a result, White's favored development scheme with Bd3 and Ne2 is temporarily prevented, which means White can't get the pieces out as quickly.} 8. Ne2 b6 9. Bg5 {This is Ivan Sokolov’s recommendation in his Chessable course on the Saemisch, so it may become much more popular than it is currently.} h6 10. Bh4 {White argues the pin on the f6 -knight will be very troublesome for Black. Playing ... g5 will always come with risk, but not getting out of the pin is even worse as it will allow the doubling of the f-pawns.} Na5 {For now we ignore the problem of the pin, and continue our regular plan of targeting the c4 -pawn. Normally we would see White playing the knight to g3 , but then the h4 -bishop would be trapped after g5 , which means the knight will have to find a different route.} 11. Nc1 {This is Sokolov’s concept, and it’s a very interesting one. Next the knight is going to b3 , which will keep the c4 -pawn safe by trading off the a5 -knight.} e5 {Closing the position makes the play very similar to the 4. Bg5 chapter. Black places pawns on the dark squares to restrict White’s dark-squared bishop.} 12. Nb3 Nxb3 13. Qxb3 g5 {It had to be done, but fortunately White doesn’t have enough pieces over on the kingside to punish it.} 14. Bf2 Nh5 ({I like this move because it discourages 15.h4,  which is the main way for White to punish the g5 push. h4?! is poor now after} 14... g4 {, since White doesn’t have the ability to go h5 and have the bishop return to h4 because the h5 -knight is blocking. In addition, the potential of the black knight jumping into f4 makes it difficult to develop the f1 -bishop.}) 15. Qd1 Qe7 16. h4 g4 17. fxg4 Nf6 {and the position is unclear.} *

