1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. f3 {This is very aggressive, immediately planning to swarm the center with White pawns. However, it makes for very slow development and in addition that pressure on d4 comes in very handy now.} Nc6 7. e4 d6 {So far, so good. We're preventing White from lunging further forward with e5 , but it's also key that we have the knight and pawn putting pressure on d4 . As a result, White's favored development scheme with Bd3 and Ne2 is temporarily prevented, which means White can't get the pieces out as quickly.} 8. d5 {This is mentioned as an alternate line for White in Ivan Sokolov’s Chessable course on the Sämisch. It’s a really interesting move where White is simply trying to run Black over in the center.} Na5 {As usual, we target the c4 -pawn.} 9. Bd3 {White is simply going for quick development.} b6 {We continue the plan of capturing the c4 -pawn. The bishop will come to a6 next.} 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. O-O (11. Bg5 $2 {This is an attempt to stop the plan of Nd7 . However, here we’re not afraid of being aggressive with our kingside pawns.} h6 12. Bh4 g5 $1 {There’s no need to be afraid of advancing the pawns because our king isn’t even going to the kingside.} 13. Bf2 Qd7 { We’re not falling for any tricks allowing Qa4 +. Now black is ready to castle queenside, attack the kingside, and win the c4 -pawn. Life is good.}) 11... Qe7 ({We’re going to castle queenside!} 11... Nd7 {Sokolov only mentions this move for Black, but I’m hesitant to recommend it because of} 12. f4 $1 {A move Sokolov doesn’t cover, but it’s very logical taking away the e5 -square Black’s knight wanted to use.   Black is able to win the c4 -pawn long-term, but White plays it as a pawn sacrifice, having amazing control in the center.} O-O 13. Ra2 $1 {The rook may get involved along the second rank.   Here’s an example of the incredible tactics available for White should Black take the pawn.} Bxc4 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. f5 $1 {The knight will try to invade on the light squares via f4 .} Qe8 17. Nf4 $1 exf5 18. Nd5 {White is sacrificing so many pawns, but the trickery works out in their favor if we accept.} fxe4 $2 19. Nc7 Qe5 {We don’t really mind losing a rook for a knight, given that we’ve captured so many pawns. But white has a nasty surprise left.} 20. Nxa8 Rxa8 21. Qg4 $1 {The only move that doesn’t lose for White – but it’s a winning one! Bh6 and Raf2 is incoming with a powerful attack, and the attempt to push White back with} Nf6 {is met by} 22. Rxf6 $1 Qxf6 23. Qxe4 {and White wins the c4 -knight with a check.}) 12. Ng3 O-O-O 13. Qe2 {White managed to defend the c4 -pawn, but it remains a long-term problem.} Nd7 {Now we try to get the knight to e5 !} 14. f4 g6 {A very good move preventing Nf5 in some variations, and preparing h5 - h4 to kick White’s knight back.} 15. Be3 h5 16. Rae1 ({White centralizes all their pieces, but Black makes their presence felt too.} 16. e5 {is an intriguing pawn sacrifice to showcase the energy of White’s pieces in the center, but Black has an amazing response!} dxe5 17. dxe6 h4 $3 {Black sacrifices the knight with check but will have a double-attack afterwards. This way you avoid 17... Qxe6 18. f5 which gives White good attacking chances.} 18. exd7+ Qxd7 19. Rad1 hxg3 {The position is still crazy complicated, but this time it’s Black who has the attacking possibilities.}) 16... h4 17. Nh1 f5 {Unclear. It’s a fantastic position with lots of tension in the center. Personally, I like Black because of the constant pressure on c4 , plus White’s dark-squared bishop struggles to find a purpose as most diagonals are blocked – either by black’s pawns ( c5, b6 ) or even White’s own pawns ( f4, c3 ) .} *

