1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. e4 {is a case of too many pawn moves in the opening. Black can blast open the center and create an attack against the uncastled king.} cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 {When White faces an unpleasant choice going forward.} 10. e5 {Tries to keep the position closed, but we're not such inclined.} dxc4 11. Bxc4 Qxd4 {Simply stealing a pawn in the center.} 12. Qxd4 Nxd4 13. exf6 Nc2+ {White gives up the rook in the vague hope of trapping the knight afterwards, but Black's rooks will get involved on the open queenside files quickly enough to evacuate the corner knight.} 14. Ke2 Nxa1 15. fxg7 Rd8 (15... Kxg7 $4 16. Bb2+ {would turn the tables on Black.}) 16. Nf3 Bd7 17. Bg5 Nc2 {Yeah, so we had to give back the rook on d8 .} 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 {White's pawns on a3 and g7 are impossible to defend, and Black will get out of the trickery with some pawns up.} *

