1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. e4 {is a case of too many pawn moves in the opening. Black can blast open the center and create an attack against the uncastled king.} cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 {When White faces an unpleasant choice going forward.} 10. cxd5 exd5 {The exchange in the center has opened up for Black's bishop to join the party, and the knight is about to jump forward too.} 11. e5 Ne4 12. Ne2 {So far White has kept everything defended, but the next move shatters white's illusion of White's king escaping unscathed.} Bg4 {Renews the threat to the d4 -pawn.} 13. Be3 ({Defends d4,  but now Black gets favorable exchanges. If} 13. f3 {the bishop sacrifices itself with} Bxf3 {, eliminating the pawns around White's king his majesty is defenseless to Black's queen and knight.} 14. gxf3 $4 Qh4+) 13... Nc3 {We're exchanging away White's bishop pair, and the resulting position will leave White with a bishop that's blocked by its own central pawns.} 14. Qc2 Nxe2 ({Avoid} 14... Bxe2 $2 15. Bxh7+ $1 Kh8 16. Qxc3 Kxh7 17. Qc2+ Kg8 18. Qxe2 {when White emerges a clean pawn up.}) 15. Bxe2 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Qa5+ 17. Qd2 Rac8 {Black has control of the c-file, and the knight is headed to c4 . Black has good chances. Keep in mind the move f5 , which may be useful to hinder White in advancing the kingside pawn majority.} *

