1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 {We're going after the c4 -pawn. The bishop needs access to a6 .} 9. e4 {White has developed the bishop and knight. It's time to move forward in the center.} Ne8 {This is a key move in this line. It may look funny, but it's absolutely crucial to prevent Bg5 with a nasty pin. Sometimes this knight also participates in the pressure on the c4 -pawn by going to d6 .} 10. O-O Ba6 {Target acquired.} 11. Ng3 {This is white's all-out attack attempt. No attention is given to the pawn on c4 , instead White prepares f4 - f5 . The knight is crucial to control f5 , which prevents Black from blocking the f-pawn's advance like in the main line.} Na5 12. f4 Bxc4 {We take the challenge and the free pawn!} 13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. f5 cxd4 {It's best to capture here now, as the black knight on c4 may need a rook on the c-file for protection.} 15. cxd4 f6 ({It's important to block White's f-pawn from advancing even further. For example,} 15... Rc8 $2 16. f6 $3 Nxf6 $2 17. Bg5 {unleashes all of the potential in White's pieces and leads to a devastating attack.}) 16. Rf4 {Having given up a pawn, white desperately tries to generate an attack.} b5 {A great, dual-purpose move! Black both protects the loose knight on c4 , while simultaneously opening up the b6 -square for the queen.} 17. Rh4 Qb6 {White's attack is delayed due to the pressure on the diagonal towards White's king.} 18. Kh1 Rc8 {Black is doing a great job of including all the pieces, while not being intimidated by white's intentions on the other side.} 19. Rb1 (19. Qh5 {may seem threatening, but it turns out we just capture the center pawn with} Qxd4 {and after} 20. Qxh7+ Kf7 {Black's king escapes while white's rook does not.}) 19... e5 {We need to have our counterplay ready in response to White's attack.} 20. Qh5 Qxd4 21. Qxh7+ Kf7 22. Bh6 {Black runs away...} Ke7 23. Bxg7 Rf7 {And Black wins with white's pieces stuck on the kingside.} *

