1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 {We're going after the c4 -pawn. The bishop needs access to a6 .} 9. e4 {White has developed the bishop and knight. It's time to move forward in the center.} Ne8 {This is a key move in this line. It may look funny, but it's absolutely crucial to prevent Bg5 with a nasty pin. Sometimes this knight also participates in the pressure on the c4 -pawn by going to d6 .} 10. O-O Ba6 {Target acquired.} 11. f4 {White pushes forward to create an attack, but Black is ready to block.} f5 {No further! We grab space and prevent white from marching forward with the f-pawn.} 12. Ng3 {Now it's all about the f5 -pawn.} ({Getting all the captures done immediately with} 12. exf5 exf5 13. dxc5 bxc5 {leads to the same position we study in the 12. Ng3 line after} 14. Be3 d6 15. Ng3 g6 {.}) (12. Be3 $2 {puts pressure on c5 , but after} fxe4 13. Bxe4 Nd6 {black's knight will go from a dim position on the rim to an amazing one on c4 in no time. Black is much better.}) 12... g6 {It feels risky putting all the pawns on light squares when we've given up our dark-squared bishop, but here it's all about blockading. White's bishops are unable to prove their worth in a closed position.} 13. Be3 {Now that White's knight already on g3 , this move to pressure c5 is a respectable one, as the knight is ready to join the action should Black capture on e4 .} cxd4 14. cxd4 d5 {Black undoubled White's pawns, but gets amazing light-squared control in the center in return. It's not about what you exchange off, it's about what remains on the board.} 15. cxd5 Bxd3 {As part of this trade we also got rid of White's bishop pair.} 16. Qxd3 fxe4 {A crucial in-between capture before we're ready to take on d5 .} 17. Nxe4 {may seem logical to kick black's queen off of d5 .} Qxd5 18. Nc3 Qf5 {Black cleverly prevents White's intention of exchanging the central pawns with d5 next.} 19. Qxf5 exf5 {is very clever -- White is left with an isolated pawn on d4 , and lost the ability to exchange it for Black's e6 -pawn. Black will play Na5 - c4 , Rd8 and Nd6 , with very well-placed pieces.} *

