1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 {We're going after the c4 -pawn. The bishop needs access to a6 .} 9. e4 {White has developed the bishop and knight. It's time to move forward in the center.} Ne8 {This is a key move in this line. It may look funny, but it's absolutely crucial to prevent Bg5 with a nasty pin. Sometimes this knight also participates in the pressure on the c4 -pawn by going to d6 .} 10. O-O Ba6 {Target acquired.} 11. f4 {White pushes forward to create an attack, but Black is ready to block.} f5 {No further! We grab space and prevent white from marching forward with the f-pawn.} 12. Ng3 {Now it's all about the f5 -pawn.} ({Getting all the captures done immediately with} 12. exf5 exf5 13. dxc5 bxc5 {leads to the same position we study in the 12. Ng3 line after} 14. Be3 d6 15. Ng3 g6 {.}) (12. Be3 $2 {puts pressure on c5 , but after} fxe4 13. Bxe4 Nd6 {black's knight will go from a dim position on the rim to an amazing one on c4 in no time. Black is much better.}) 12... g6 {It feels risky putting all the pawns on light squares when we've given up our dark-squared bishop, but here it's all about blockading. White's bishops are unable to prove their worth in a closed position.} 13. dxc5 {White tries to exchange off the central pawns, which were getting in the way of the bishops.} bxc5 14. exf5 exf5 15. Be3 d6 {The threat to c5 is easily parried by Black. This is actually a pawn sacrifice, but white would be ill-advised to take it.} 16. Bxf5 {This wins a pawn and was for a long time the main line of this variation -- but in fact it's simply a mistake, as Black gets a devastating attack with an unopposed light-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} gxf5 17. Qd5+ Rf7 {This is key, as we need the b7 -square protected for the bishop.} 18. Qxc6 Bb7 19. Qa4 h5 {Black immediately starts an attack. The pawn will chase away White's knight so that Black can use the open g-file to mount an attack.} 20. Rab1 (20. Nxh5 $2 {doesn't work as Black launches an attack. First} Qh4 {to chase the knight back, and then after} 21. Ng3 Rh7 {There's no way to protect h2 , and white is about to fall victim to the rook and queen combining beautifully with the b7 -bishop.}) 20... Ng7 {Protects both f5 and h5 , while getting ready to continue pushing the h-pawn.} ({Black should not rush with} 20... h4 {since it allows} 21. Nxf5 {when white is very much still in the game.}) 21. Rfd1 h4 22. Nf1 Be4 {Black's light-squared bishop is an amazing piece. It's impossible to chase away and will cause trouble around white's king for the rest of the game. Black would like to follow up with something like Qf6 and Nh5 and then get the rooks pointing down towards White's king on the g-file.} *

