1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... Nc6 {This is the old main line, and it has stood the test of time. Black simply develops the pieces.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 {We're going after the c4 -pawn. The bishop needs access to a6 .} 9. e4 {White has developed the bishop and knight. It's time to move forward in the center.} Ne8 {This is a key move in this line. It may look funny, but it's absolutely crucial to prevent Bg5 with a nasty pin. Sometimes this knight also participates in the pressure on the c4 -pawn by going to d6 .} 10. O-O Ba6 {Target acquired.} 11. f4 {White pushes forward to create an attack, but Black is ready to block.} f5 {No further! We grab space and prevent white from marching forward with the f-pawn.} 12. Ng3 {Now it's all about the f5 -pawn.} ({Getting all the captures done immediately with} 12. exf5 exf5 13. dxc5 bxc5 {leads to the same position we study in the 12. Ng3 line after} 14. Be3 d6 15. Ng3 g6 {.}) (12. Be3 $2 {puts pressure on c5 , but after} fxe4 13. Bxe4 Nd6 {black's knight will go from a dim position on the rim to an amazing one on c4 in no time. Black is much better.}) 12... g6 {It feels risky putting all the pawns on light squares when we've given up our dark-squared bishop, but here it's all about blockading. White's bishops are unable to prove their worth in a closed position.} 13. dxc5 {White tries to exchange off the central pawns, which were getting in the way of the bishops.} bxc5 14. exf5 exf5 15. Be3 d6 {The threat to c5 is easily parried by Black. This is actually a pawn sacrifice, but white would be ill-advised to take it.} 16. Re1 {This maneuvering scheme was played by Magnus Carlsen, but it doesn't do anything to stop Black's main plan.} Nf6 {It's time for the knight to return to the center.} 17. Bf2 {White hopes to find a home for the bishop on h4 , where it won't be shut out of play by pawns.} Na5 {We've been so focused on the stuff going on in the middle, it's easy to forget the target on c4 is still there for the taking.} 18. Nf1 {White sacrifices a pawn to get the bishop to h4 , thinking something dangerous is bound to happen. Spoiler alert: It's not that dangerous.} ({Defending the pawn with} 18. Qa4 {doesn't put any pressure on Black's position, who can maneuver the bishop back to the great long diagonal with} Bb7 {when the g3 -knight is stuck trying to defend against Ne4 , which in turn means the f2 -bishop continues its struggle to find a purpose. Black is more than fine.}) 18... Bxc4 {Why not take a nice pawn and get rid of white's bishop pair?} 19. Bxc4+ Nxc4 20. Bh4 {White intends Re6 , and also has some ideas of Qd5 in the future.} Nb6 {Retreating the knight keeps it safe.} 21. Re6 {White ups the pressure.} Rf7 {This is a brilliant defensive move! We give back the pawn we won to organize our pieces. The queen needed the f8 -square, so the rook makes way.} 22. Rxd6 Qf8 {Moving the queen allows for Ne4 next move, while also getting ready for Re8 . Everything is protected and Black is fine.} *

