1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... b6 {This rarely played move is an attempt at improving upon our main line. Black wants to get the bishop to b7 early, thereby delaying white's advance in the center. But on the other hand it gives white an option to go very aggressive with e4 immediately.   I feel it's too unexplored to give as a main line -- especially seeing as how the decades old main line holds up very well for Black. But for adventurous players this can be worth a try.} 7. Bd3 {If white tries to develop akin to the main line, Black gets a small nuance...} Bb7 {when the threat on the diagonal forces the inclusion of f3 .} 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. e4 Ne8 {Black continues tradionally with the knight and castling, including this very thematic knight retreat to prevent Bg5 from White. The only difference between this and the old-school main line is the inclusion of f3 and Bb7 , but that works in Black's favor.} 11. O-O Na5 {Black eyes the pawn on c4 , and if White launches an attack.} 12. f4 f5 {As is customary in this line, Black is very well placed to answer f4 with ... f5 when the bishop's placement on b7 works out beautifully, as the diagonal is about to open.} 13. e5 d6 {Black has good pressure on White's pawns and will go after the c4 -pawn with Rc8 and Ba6 coming up.} *

