[ECO "E26"]
[PlyCount "22"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {With this move white immediately puts pressure on the bishop and forces it to make up its mind. It's called the Sämisch Variation , and frankly, if it was good, there would be no such thing as the Nimzo-Indian.   The a3 -move does nothing to help white's development, while encouraging Black to give White doubled pawns -- which means with the right plan, Black gets a nice game.} Bxc3+ {It's not time for retreat -- It's time to give white doubled pawns.} 5. bxc3 c5 {We immediately put pressure on White's center. We're rarely going to capture on d4 (as that would allow White to undouble the c-pawns), but it's useful stake a claim to the middle of the board.} 6. e3 {This is the main line. White goes for quick development first, then flooding the center with pawns.} (6. Qc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the 6.Nf3-line .}) 6... b6 {This rarely played move is an attempt at improving upon our main line. Black wants to get the bishop to b7 early, thereby delaying white's advance in the center. But on the other hand it gives white an option to go very aggressive with e4 immediately.   I feel it's too unexplored to give as a main line -- especially seeing as how the decades old main line holds up very well for Black. But for adventurous players this can be worth a try.} 7. e4 {This is a very interesting extra option White gets in this line. Without the pawn on b6 , Black would have Qa5 with threats on both c3 and e4 . On this occasion, however, the only way to punish White is taking the pawn immediately.} Nxe4 8. Qg4 {The double-attack on g7 and e4 guarantees White to get the pawn back next. The resulting position is very unclear. White has the bishop pair, but also the doubled c-pawns. It may be objectively balanced, but both sides can go for the win.} f5 {protecting the central knight is one way to go.} 9. Qxg7 {Black has to go for the queen exchange.} Qf6 10. Qxf6 Nxf6 11. d5 Ba6 {Black does best to avoid capturing the free pawn immediately. It’s a tremendously complex position where the engines say 0.00, but it’s anyone's game.} *

