1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 6. cxd5 {This prevents our mainline with 6... dxc4 , but it also allows Black to strike early in the center.} exd5 7. e4 {Pushing forward in the center is how White justifies the f3 -plan.} dxe4 {We're opening up in the center, trying to exploit our superior development.} 8. fxe4 {White has very nice-looking pawns, but for how long?} O-O {We're getting the king to safety before pushing c5 to counter White's strong center.} 9. Nf3 c5 {This is the moment to pounce!} 10. d5 {White needs to keep the center as closed as possible in order to get castled, but this has caused a major weakening of the dark squares, and e5 in particular.} Bg4 {The fight for control of the e5 -square begins, and strangely it's a light-squared bishop doing the job, despite e5 being a dark square. We're removing the white knight defending e5 .} 11. Be2 Bd6 ({Avoid} 11... Nbd7 $4 {because of} 12. d6 $1 {+- trapping the bishop on e7 .}) 12. O-O Nbd7 {Black has harmonious development and great control of the e5 -square.} *

