1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Be3 {This is a very clever move, trying to stop black's main idea of c5 : However, there are interesting tactics in the position based on black's development advantage.} b5 {An amazing move! Black simply gives away the b-pawn to get the pieces quickly into play.} 8. a4 {tries to avoid the white knight jumping around grabbing pawns.} b4 {It turns out the knight has to move again anyway. Black gets excellent play.} 9. Nb1 c5 {Striking in the center.} 10. dxc5 Nfd7 {Surrounds the c5 -pawn, and black is better in the ensuing middlegame.} 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. Nh3 Bxc5 {White has poor control of the dark squares, and the bishop on c4 struggles to find a good role. Black has a clear plan of completing development with Nc6 , Bb7 and Rc8 . In the future, a black knight may find a great home on the d4 -square, which has been left in the rear-view mirror by white's pawns.} *

