1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Be3 {This is a very clever move, trying to stop black's main idea of c5 : However, there are interesting tactics in the position based on black's development advantage.} b5 {An amazing move! Black simply gives away the b-pawn to get the pieces quickly into play.} 8. Nxb5 {This is the critical test of Black's idea.} Ba6 {It turns out the Black bishop is indirectly protecting the pawn on c4 , which means b5 was more of a pawn trade than a sacrifice.} 9. Nc3 {Returning to c3 doesn't exert pressure on Black's position, which in turn leaves white in trouble figuring out how to develop the kingside pieces.} O-O 10. Nh3 {This straight-forward attempt at getting the pieces out leads to trouble, as Black strikes against White's pawn center with} (10. Qa4 Nfd7 {transposes to 10.Nc3 in the main line .}) 10... c5 11. dxc5 Nfd7 12. Be2 Nxc5 13. O-O Nc6 {White did manage to get the king to safety, but Black's pieces are incredibly active, and Black has nice ideas of Rb8 and Nd3 to increase the pressure on White: in particular, the backward pawn on b2 .} *

