 point of this check is to leave the d8 -square available for Black's rook, with good pressure towards White's queen, as illustrated by the following continuation.} 12. Nc3 c5 13. d5 exd5 14. exd5 Rd8 {The position is opening up -- White's massive pawn center has been eviscerated, yet the king is still stuck in the middle. White needs to be prompt about getting the king away, but that leads to a nice position for Black.} 15. Bxc4 Qb4 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. O-O Nc7 {Black will regain the pawn on d5 and have well-placed pieces in the center.} *

