lack's pawn break.} c5 {is still an option as a temporary pawn sacrifice.} 12. dxc5 Qc7 {There's no way to stay a pawn up for White.} 13. Bxc4 Bxc5 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. Qb4 {Seemingly, white has managed to escape with a pawn up, but Black has one last trick up their sleeve.} Nxe4 {This discovered attack on the bishop wins back the pawn for Black, and ends up with an equal position.} 16. Nxe4 Qxc4 17. Qxc4 Bxc4 {At first glance I feel like this position looks better for black, with the powerful bishop in the center and White lacking development. However, the bishop will often point into nothingness, while White might actually benefit from not having castled yet as the king can be kept in the center for the ensuing endgame. With correct play, a draw will certainly happen, but there are enough imbalances for either side to hope for a win.} *

