e second time, especially given the state of White's development, but the attack on the c7 -pawn makes it worthwhile.} (10. Bxc4 $4 {loses because of} Nb6 $1 {A fantastic move, opening up for white to make a double-check on Black's king. However, white is left with too many hanging pieces afterwards.} 11. Nxc7+ Kf8 {Black simply moves the king away, and now white's queen on a4 , knight on c7 and bishop on c4 are all under attack. Black wins.}) 10... e5 {a pawn sacrifice designed to disrupt White's coordination.} (10... O-O {!? is an interesting alternative, which leads to immense complications after} 11. Nxc7 e5 12. Nxa8 exf4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. Qxa7 Bxa8 15. Qxa8 Qb6 {initially the computers hate Black's position, but the longer they think, the more optimistic they are on Black's behalf. I've always been one for solidity over complications though, and prefer the main line with 10... e5 .}) 11. dxe5 Nc5 {is a no-go for white. The queen is chased away, and with it the protection of the b5 -knight.} 12. Nxc7+ (12. Qxc4 c6 {is a decisive pin.}) (12. Qa5 Nc6 {transposes to the main line after} 13. Nxc7+ Kf8) 12... Kf8 {leaves white unable to defend the knight.} 13. Qa5 Nc6 *

