1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Be3 {This is a very clever move, trying to stop black's main idea of c5 : However, there are interesting tactics in the position based on black's development advantage.} b5 {An amazing move! Black simply gives away the b-pawn to get the pieces quickly into play.} 8. Nxb5 {This is the critical test of Black's idea.} Ba6 {It turns out the Black bishop is indirectly protecting the pawn on c4 , which means b5 was more of a pawn trade than a sacrifice.} 9. Qa4 {This is the critical move: White is protecting the knight, eyeing the Black king and attacking the c4 -pawn all at once.} Nfd7 {With his move, it turns out the pawn on c4 stays alive!} 10. Bf4 {It's weird moving the bishop for the second time, especially given the state of White's development, but the attack on the c7 -pawn makes it worthwhile.} (10. Bxc4 $4 {loses because of} Nb6 $1 {A fantastic move, opening up for white to make a double-check on Black's king. However, white is left with too many hanging pieces afterwards.} 11. Nxc7+ Kf8 {Black simply moves the king away, and now white's queen on a4 , knight on c7 and bishop on c4 are all under attack. Black wins.}) 10... e5 {a pawn sacrifice designed to disrupt White's coordination.} (10... O-O {!? is an interesting alternative, which leads to immense complications after} 11. Nxc7 e5 12. Nxa8 exf4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. Qxa7 Bxa8 15. Qxa8 Qb6 {initially the computers hate Black's position, but the longer they think, the more optimistic they are on Black's behalf. I've always been one for solidity over complications though, and prefer the main line with 10... e5 .}) 11. Bxe5 O-O {This was the big point! Now the lines with Nxc7 doesn't work for white.} 12. Rd1 {This is a sensible way for White, anticipating that black will play Nxe5 at some point, White readies the rook to put pressure on the d-file.} Nb6 {Black takes the opportunity to bully the queen around for a while.} 13. Qa5 Bxb5 14. Qxb5 a6 15. Qa5 Nc6 16. Qc3 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qb8 {Black is down a pawn, but White's development is still an important factor in the game. In addition, Black is trying to use the doubled c-pawns to their advantage: Doubled pawns mean open files, and that's precisely what Black is trying to exploit with the queen on the b-file.} 18. Qc2 {A necessity to stop the Na4 -threat, but that's the 5th queen move in the last six moves. Black can use the time gained to get compensation for the pawn.} Rd8 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. Bxc4 Nxc4 21. Qxc4 Rb8 {Black is two pawns down, but with the rook and queen working together, Black will get them back.} 22. Qc3 c6 {This move is very clever. It enables Qb6 , where the queen both attacks b2 while also preventing White's king from castling.} 23. Ne2 Qb6 24. f4 {White realizes that the b2 -pawn cannot be saved, and makes the f3 -square available for the king.} Qxb2 25. Qxb2 Rxb2 26. Kf2 Bc5+ 27. Kf3 {Proves white needed the f3 -square.} Rb3+ 28. Kg4 Rb2 29. Kf3 {The only way to keep everything protected.} Rb3+ {Secures a draw.} *

