e second time, especially given the state of White's development, but the attack on the c7 -pawn makes it worthwhile.} (10. Bxc4 $4 {loses because of} Nb6 $1 {A fantastic move, opening up for white to make a double-check on Black's king. However, white is left with too many hanging pieces afterwards.} 11. Nxc7+ Kf8 {Black simply moves the king away, and now white's queen on a4 , knight on c7 and bishop on c4 are all under attack. Black wins.}) 10... e5 {a pawn sacrifice designed to disrupt White's coordination.} (10... O-O {!? is an interesting alternative, which leads to immense complications after} 11. Nxc7 e5 12. Nxa8 exf4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. Qxa7 Bxa8 15. Qxa8 Qb6 {initially the computers hate Black's position, but the longer they think, the more optimistic they are on Black's behalf. I've always been one for solidity over complications though, and prefer the main line with 10... e5 .}) 11. Bxe5 O-O {This was the big point! Now the lines with Nxc7 doesn't work for white.} 12. Bxc7 {is greedy. Yes, White is up two pawns, with a third on c4 in trouble. But White's king remains uncastled and that is the most important factor in the position.} Qc8 13. Ba5 (13. Bg3 $4 Nb6 14. Qa5 Nc6 {loses the knight on b5 .}) (13. Bxb8 $2 Rxb8 14. Bxc4 Nb6 {wins a piece.}) 13... Nc6 14. Nc7 {It seems as though White has managed to get the pieces working together, only to be struck down by the fantastic rook sacrifice...} Nxd4 {which leaves Black with a winning attack...} 15. Nxa6 {The bishop is an important contributor to Black's attack, so it's actually the more important piece to capture at this point, but it's not enough to stop our attack if we continue correctly.} Qxa6 16. Bxc4 {White is up two pawns, so we need to strike immediately.} Qg6 {The threat on g2 keeps White occupied.} 17. Qxd7 {Grabbing material may be considered the best option in practical play, because now there's only one move to win for Black.} Nc2+ 18. Kf1 (18. Kd2 Nxa1 {First one rook.} 19. Qxe7 Qxg2+ {And then 