e second time, especially given the state of White's development, but the attack on the c7 -pawn makes it worthwhile.} (10. Bxc4 $4 {loses because of} Nb6 $1 {A fantastic move, opening up for white to make a double-check on Black's king. However, white is left with too many hanging pieces afterwards.} 11. Nxc7+ Kf8 {Black simply moves the king away, and now white's queen on a4 , knight on c7 and bishop on c4 are all under attack. Black wins.}) 10... e5 {a pawn sacrifice designed to disrupt White's coordination.} (10... O-O {!? is an interesting alternative, which leads to immense complications after} 11. Nxc7 e5 12. Nxa8 exf4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. Qxa7 Bxa8 15. Qxa8 Qb6 {initially the computers hate Black's position, but the longer they think, the more optimistic they are on Black's behalf. I've always been one for solidity over complications though, and prefer the main line with 10... e5 .}) 11. Bxe5 O-O {This was the big point! Now the lines with Nxc7 doesn't work for white.} 12. Nc3 {the knight gets away from trouble, but Black's initiative persists.} (12. Nxc7 $4 {was good without e5 inserted, but here Black wins after} Nxe5 $1 13. Nxa8 Qxd4 {Qxb2, Qe3 +, Nd3 +, Bh4 + are all on the agenda. Black has a winning attack.}) 12... Nb6 13. Qa5 {White keeps the queen poking at Black's bishop. It makes Black's life trickier, but also exposes the queen to huge danger.} Qc8 {Protecting the bishop to enable Nc6 , trapping White's queen.} 14. d5 {White prevents the queen from getting trapped, but allows Black to redirect focus to the e5 -bishop which is now undefended.} N8d7 15. Bd4 (15. Bg3 $4 {loses to} Nc5 {.}) 15... c5 16. dxc6 (16. Bf2 $2 Bd8 {is yet another illustration of how close Black is to trapping White's queen.}) 16... Nb8 {The knight returns to start, but it's not planning to stay there very long. The c6 -square is available and the knight is redirected there to bother White's queen.} 17. Nd5 {White tries to create counterthreats while at the same time giving more room to the queen. The resulting lines become very tactical.} Bh4+ {It's important to get the bishop away from White's knight. We're not afraid of g3 .} 18. g3 Nxc6 19. gxh4 {This is a sweet trick, since taking the queen leads to a fork on e7 . However, Black has a counter trick.} Nxd5 {Brilliant! Getting rid of the knight fork, while luring White's queen to an unfortunate square.} ({Not} 19... Nxa5 $4 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxc8 {when white is winning with a pawn up and the bishop pair.}) 20. Qxd5 Rd8 {Black wins back the piece on d4 with a huge attack.} *

