e second time, especially given the state of White's development, but the attack on the c7 -pawn makes it worthwhile.} (10. Bxc4 $4 {loses because of} Nb6 $1 {A fantastic move, opening up for white to make a double-check on Black's king. However, white is left with too many hanging pieces afterwards.} 11. Nxc7+ Kf8 {Black simply moves the king away, and now white's queen on a4 , knight on c7 and bishop on c4 are all under attack. Black wins.}) 10... e5 {a pawn sacrifice designed to disrupt White's coordination.} (10... O-O {!? is an interesting alternative, which leads to immense complications after} 11. Nxc7 e5 12. Nxa8 exf4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. Qxa7 Bxa8 15. Qxa8 Qb6 {initially the computers hate Black's position, but the longer they think, the more optimistic they are on Black's behalf. I've always been one for solidity over complications though, and prefer the main line with 10... e5 .}) 11. Bxe5 O-O {This was the big point! Now the lines with Nxc7 doesn't work for white.} 12. Nc3 {the knight gets away from trouble, but Black's initiative persists.} (12. Nxc7 $4 {was good without e5 inserted, but here Black wins after} Nxe5 $1 13. Nxa8 Qxd4 {Qxb2, Qe3 +, Nd3 +, Bh4 + are all on the agenda. Black has a winning attack.}) 12... Nb6 13. Qa5 {White keeps the queen poking at Black's bishop. It makes Black's life trickier, but also exposes the queen to huge danger.} Qc8 {Protecting the bishop to enable Nc6 , trapping White's queen.} 14. d5 {White prevents the queen from getting trapped, but allows Black to redirect focus to the e5 -bishop which is now undefended.} N8d7 15. Bd4 (15. Bg3 $4 {loses to} Nc5 {.}) 15... c5 16. dxc6 (16. Bf2 $2 Bd8 {is yet another illustration of how close Black is to trapping White's queen.}) 16... Nb8 {The knight returns to start, but it's not planning to stay there very long. The c6 -square is available and the knight is redirected there to bother White's queen.} 17. Nd5 {White tries to create counterthreats while at the same time giving more room to the queen. The resulting lines become very tactical.} Bh4+ {It's important to get the bishop away from White's knight. We're not afraid of g3 .} 18. Bf2 {A clever version compared to g3 , as now the bishop is not undefended on d4 . This means the line with Nxc6 no longer works out for Black.} Bxf2+ ({Not} 18... Nxc6 $6 19. Bxh4 Nxa5 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxc8 {when white got the queens off the board while still having a pawn up.}) 19. Kxf2 Nxc6 20. Qc5 {Black is still a pawn down, but it's time to cash in on the superior development.} Nxd5 21. exd5 Qb7 22. Re1 {A very difficult defensive move to find! It's crucial to prevent Ne7 .} (22. b4 $2 {protects the b2 -pawn through clever tactics, but leaves the d5 -pawn in trouble} Ne7 {Black is about to get the knight to d5 and include both rooks in the attack with Rac8 and Rfd8 . White's king is unlikely to survive.}) 22... Qxb2+ 23. Re2 Qd4+ 24. Qxd4 Nxd4 25. Re4 {White is very happy to have gotten the queens off the board, and is seemingly winning a pawn -- but Black still has resources.} Nb3 26. Bxc4 f5 {The rook is in trouble! It turns out the c4 -pawn wouldn't go down without a fight.} 27. Rf4 g5 {The rook is trapped, and White will have to go for a position an exchange down.} 28. Bxa6 gxf4 29. Nh3 Nc5 30. Bc4 Rac8 ({This is an extremely interesting position. The engines slightly prefer Black, but there are definitely chances for both sides. White will try to use the passed pawn in the center, while Black will chase White's bishop with the rook, and try to win the a3 -pawn. It's important to note that Nxf4 immediately is not good, because of} 30... Ne4+ {.}) 31. Rd1 ({Black should involve the king, leading to a highly unclear endgame after} 31. Nxf4 $2 Ne4+ 32. fxe4 Rxc4 33. Ne6 $6 Rb8 {which leaves the Black rooks coordinating dangerously against White's king. So White should rather play 31.Rd1}) 31... Kg7 32. Nxf4 Kf6 {with chances for both sides.} *

