1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. dxc5 {This was actually Garry Kasparov's choice, in the only top-tier outing this variation has ever had. The early queen trade should give Black a nice game.} Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 {is way less threatening, as White loses out on the Nb5 -possibilities.} Bxc5 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Nxe3 Nc6 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 {White tries to claim that black's bishop can't accomplish much with white's e4 - f3 - g2 pawn chain blocking its potential, but Black can live with a bad bishop as long as the rest of the pieces are doing well. The optimal plan for Black can be seen in this line:} 14. Ne2 Ke7 15. Nd4 Rac8 16. Ke2 Rhd8 17. Rhd1 Be8 {The bishop gets out of the way of the rooks and Black has a harmonious position.} *

