1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. dxc5 {This was actually Garry Kasparov's choice, in the only top-tier outing this variation has ever had. The early queen trade should give Black a nice game.} Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 10. b4 {This has been tested at the top level in recent games. White simply claims to have an advantage in the endgame due to all the extra space.} Bb6 11. Nge2 a6 {This stops the plan of Na4 followed by Be3 since a7 is available as a retreat square.} 12. Kc2 (12. e5 {Pushing forward is the logical attempt to punish black for not playing Nc6 , but Black is fine as long as we push back quickly in the center.} Nfd7 13. f4 Nc6 14. Kc2 f6 $1 {counterplay An important move! We open up the position before White gets all their pieces into optimal positions. Black is fine.}) 12... Nc6 {Now we need to rush development!} 13. Rd1 Bd7 14. Kb2 {Very patient play. The king needs to get out of the c-file anyway, so it’s best to do it immediately, and seeing what plan Black goes for before deciding how to continue next.} O-O {Black wants a rook to the c-file, and using the h8 one would be optimal.} 15. Bf4 Rfc8 {The d7 -bishop is loose, but luckily the tactics work out for Black thanks to the counterplay down the c-file.} 16. e5 {The critical test of Black’s concept.} (16. Bb3 {Getting the bishop away is not without danger for Black. White’s king is much closer to the action than Black’s, so accuracy is needed.} Be8 {This is the optimal solution for the pieces. We’ll go ... Nd7 - e5 next if allowed.} 17. Bd6 $1 {White gets ready for f4 to completely cramp Black.} Bc7 $1 {This move is needed to stop White from going e5 followed by f4 .} 18. Bxc7 Rxc7 19. f4 {White is very close to suffocating Black, but luckily there’s one move to save us} Ng4 $1 {Counterplay The knight saves the day with threats like Ne3 and Nxh2 . White can’t protect all the kingside pawns without allowing Black’s pieces to find good squares. For instance ... Ne3 and ... Rd8 .}) 16... Nh5 {We lose our bishop, but that’s not the end of the story.} 17. Rxd7 Nxf4 18. Nxf4 Nxe5 {A double attack!} 19. Bxe6 {A brilliant resource! The bishop was lost anyway, so White gets a pawn and creates weaknesses in Black’s pawn structure.} fxe6 20. Rxb7 a5 {The bishop on b6 doesn’t require protection because of the fork on c4 . Instead, we’re actually starting a bit of an attack on White’s king. Don’t underestimate the power of the black rooks.} 21. b5 {White is smart to keep as many files as possible closed.} Bd4 {It’s time to move the bishop away.} 22. Nfe2 Bxc3+ 23. Nxc3 a4 {Taking away the b3 -square from White’s king. Black is down a pawn, but the attack forces White to give it back. The undefended knight on c3 is key to many variations.} 24. b6 {White gets ready to play Rc7 to exchange off the pressure towards the c3 -knight.} Nc4+ 25. Kc2 Ra6 {The pawn is surrounded.} 26. Rc7 Rxc7 27. bxc7 Rc6 {It’s been a roller-coaster, but Black came out alive! White can’t grab the a4 -pawn without also losing the a3 -pawn, while the c7 -pawn is being captured next. The endgame is equal despite White’s active king.} *

