1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. d5 {White secures an imbalance in the pawn structure, but Black is ready to challenge for control of the d5 -square.} exd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Nd7 11. Ne2 Nb6 {White's bishop got a great outpost on d5 , but we're not letting it sit there undisturbed.} 12. Nc3 (12. Ba2 {lets black get pieces into play too easily.} Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 f5 {A good challenge in the center!} 14. Ng3 fxe4 15. Nxe4 (15. Re1 {Doesn't disrupt Black's plan, as} Bd7 $1 16. Rxe4 Bc6 $1 17. Re1 O-O-O+ {= means Black castles with check, solving the issue of the pin on the e7 -bishop.}) 15... Bf5 {Black is ready for queenside castling and Rhe8 , after which all the pieces will have active positions.}) 12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 O-O (13... Be6 $2 {should be avoided, as} 14. Qa4+ {disrupts Black's coordination.}) 14. Bf4 Be6 15. Nxe7+ {Doesn't win an exchange for White, because Black launches a venomous counterattack.} Qxe7 16. Bd6 Qh4+ 17. g3 Qh3 18. Bxf8 Qg2 {When White's rook on h1 finds itself in grave danger.} 19. Rf1 Bc4 20. Rf2 Qg1+ {Wins for Black.} *

