1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. e5 {An early lunge in the center -- but Black is well-placed to deal with the aggression.} Nfd7 9. f4 (9. dxc5 $2 {is bad, as black responds with} Nxe5 {attacking c4 and c5 at the same time. Black gets a solid advantage. For instance} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Be2 Bxc5 {with a clear pawn up.}) 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 {This has the benefit of not losing a pawn, but also leads to Black getting very easy development.} Nc6 11. Qd1 (11. Qf2 Na5 12. Ba2 $2 Nc5 {is big trouble for White.}) 11... a6 12. Nf3 b5 13. Ba2 Bb7 {A great diagonal for Black's bishop.} 14. O-O b4 15. axb4 Nxb4 {Black has great piece activity and access to lots of squares where there are no white pawns to chase them away, such as c5 , d5 and d3 .} *

