1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. e5 {An early lunge in the center -- but Black is well-placed to deal with the aggression.} Nfd7 9. f4 (9. dxc5 $2 {is bad, as black responds with} Nxe5 {attacking c4 and c5 at the same time. Black gets a solid advantage. For instance} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Be2 Bxc5 {with a clear pawn up.}) 9... cxd4 10. Ne4 {In my opinion, playing it as a gambit is the best way for White. The Black pawn on d4 will sometimes stand in the way of Black's pieces. Such as a bishop on c5 , a knight on c6 and a rook on d8 .} b5 {I think there's quite a bit of venom in White's setup, so I believe Black should aim to trade off White's bishop as soon as possible.} ({Here's a sample line of what can happen if we don't take the potential in White's position seriously.} 10... O-O 11. h4 $5 b6 12. Nf3 Bb7 $6 13. Neg5 Nc6 $2 14. Nxh7 {White gets a very dangerous attack.}) 11. Bd3 (11. Bxb5 $4 {The pawn is immune due to} Qa5+ {winning White's bishop.}) 11... b4 12. Nf3 (12. axb4 $2 {is a mistake because it allows Black's knight to come chasing after the bishop.} Nc6 $1 13. b5 Nb4 {Black's bishop on b7 will be a monster if we manage to eliminate white's counterpart on d3 . And here the bishop can't escape as} 14. Bb1 $2 d3 {is huge for black. If} 15. Bxd3 $2 {then} Nxe5 {.}) 12... Ba6 {With the exchange of the light-squared bishop, White's attacking potential is much lower, and Black can safely castle next.} *

