1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. Nge2 {By far white's most logical move.} (8. Be3 $6 {This is a bad way to defend the pawn, as it allows Black to develop with a threat after} cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 {and White will have to move the bishop again without putting pressure on Black's development.}) 8... O-O {We want to castle before playing Nc6 to avoid funky lines with d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. Bb5 {was played in the only previous outing of this line. Shabalov managed to get a quick with the White pieces against Barsov, but Black's play could be improved upon. I recommend} Qb6 {when there's a cross-roads.} 11. dxc5 {is more of a positional try.} Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 {Normally I hate disrupting my pawn structure like this, but I've been convinced this is Black's best bet. By keeping the queen on c5 , we're preventing castling for the time being -- but the most important factor is the b-file. We're gonna use the opened file to exert pressure on the b2 -pawn, and it's difficult for white to deal with it. If White's pawn had been on a2 , white could create a pawn chain protection with a2 - b3 . However, in order to do the same thing now, white would need to go a3 - b4 , after which Black can challenge the front pawn easily with a5 , fixing Black's pawn structure in the process.} 14. Qd4 Qa5 {We had to let white castle to avoid the queen exchange, but White's queen will be a target on d4 .} 15. O-O (15. b4 {We were actually trying to provoke b4 ! Now} Qc7 16. O-O Rd8 17. Qe3 a5 {straightens out Black's pawn structure.}) 15... c5 16. Qe3 Nd7 {A weird, multi-purpose move. We may want Ne5 at some point, but for now the important part is that Rb8 will be possible next move without nasty tactics -- and then Black is fine.} (16... Rb8 $2 {It's very important to note that this move immediately would be a mistake! White strikes with} 17. b4 $1 cxb4 18. axb4 Qxb4 $4 19. Rab1 Qd6 20. e5 {winning material.}) 17. Rfd1 Rb8 {We got the rook to the open file. Ne5 - c4 may be coming up next. Black is doing well.} *

