1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. Nge2 {By far white's most logical move.} (8. Be3 $6 {This is a bad way to defend the pawn, as it allows Black to develop with a threat after} cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 {and White will have to move the bishop again without putting pressure on Black's development.}) 8... O-O {We want to castle before playing Nc6 to avoid funky lines with d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. Bb5 {was played in the only previous outing of this line. Shabalov managed to get a quick with the White pieces against Barsov, but Black's play could be improved upon. I recommend} Qb6 {when there's a cross-roads.} 11. Bxc6 {Initiates tactics, where moveorders are important.} cxd4 {The bishop on c6 isn't running anywhere, so there's time to start capturing all over the place.} 12. Nxd4 (12. Qxd4 Qxc6 {leaves Black with a nice pawn structure intact, and with the bishop pair.}) (12. Bxb7 {is trying to be sneaky, but Black can be reasonably happy about opening the b-file. After} Qxb7 13. Bxd4 a5 {Black will remain a pawn down, but the white b-pawn will be a long-term weakness. In the meantime, Black will try to use the bishop pair, especially the one on c8 , which will rule the light-squares. Black is likely to follow up with something like Rd8 , Qb8 and Ba6 . All-in-all, Black is doing well.}) 12... Qxb2 {We're not at all in a hurry to take the bishop! The threat on White's c3 -knight means we'll get another stab at the bishop next move.} 13. Nce2 bxc6 {Finally it's time!} 14. Nxc6 Bxa3 {A brave move, but it's justified. Removing the last of the queenside pawns guarantees White won't win this game.} 15. Bd4 (15. Rb1 Qa2 16. O-O Qc4 {The queen escapes, with a fine position for Black.}) 15... Qb7 {The crucial resource. Black loses the bishop on a3 , but grabs the knight.} 16. Rxa3 Qxc6 17. Qa1 Rd8 18. Bxf6 (18. O-O Ne8 {Black defends the long diagonal and white can't do much more than capturing on a7 with a guaranteed draw.}) 18... gxf6 19. Qxf6 Ba6 {Both kings are in trouble!} 20. Ra5 Qb6 21. Rg5+ Kf8 22. Rg7 {Just as it looks like Black is getting checkmated, the computer comes up with a very cool defence.} Rd1+ 23. Kxd1 Qd8+ 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8+ 25. Kc2 Kxg7 {Both kings got out of trouble, and a very slightly better endgame for Black remains.} *

