ith d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. dxc5 {As we will see, this is actually a risky move. But it's definitely also the most testing one for Black's concept.} (10. O-O {gives Black very easy play after} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {when White will have to trade away any hope of an advantage.}) 10... Ne5 11. Ba2 Nd3+ 12. Kf1 {It's a big concession for White to move the king, but White is hoping it doesn't matter in an endgame. However, Black doesn't have to acquiesce to White's plan.} b6 {This is the key move! Black has no intention to cashing in on the pawn just yet. Instead, the bishop gets a route to a6 , from where it will point down towards White's king.} (12... Bxc5 $2 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. e5 {would play straight into White's hands, when the uncastled White king would not be a major feature in the position as Black has no pieces in attacking positions.}) 13. c6 {keeps a thorn deep inside Black's position.} Bc5 {Black keeps good counterplay.} 14. Bxc5 bxc5 {is a very nice change of pawn structure for Black. By getting the pawn to c5 , Black prevents white's b4 - b5 pawn advance, which would block the c8 -bishop's planned diagonal from a6 .} 15. Bc4 {Stops Ba6 , but allows Black to get the pawn back.} Nxb2 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Bb5 a6 18. Ba4 Ra7 {The black rook keeps White's c-pawn under control, and with Rc7 coming next it's likely Black will capture the dangerous pawn in the very near future.} *

