ith d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. dxc5 {As we will see, this is actually a risky move. But it's definitely also the most testing one for Black's concept.} (10. O-O {gives Black very easy play after} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {when White will have to trade away any hope of an advantage.}) 10... Ne5 11. Ba2 Nd3+ 12. Kf1 {It's a big concession for White to move the king, but White is hoping it doesn't matter in an endgame. However, Black doesn't have to acquiesce to White's plan.} b6 {This is the key move! Black has no intention to cashing in on the pawn just yet. Instead, the bishop gets a route to a6 , from where it will point down towards White's king.} (12... Bxc5 $2 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. e5 {would play straight into White's hands, when the uncastled White king would not be a major feature in the position as Black has no pieces in attacking positions.}) 13. c6 {keeps a thorn deep inside Black's position.} Bc5 {Black keeps good counterplay.} 14. Qd2 {Allows a sweet tactic.} Nxb2 {This wins back the pawn for Black, and leads to an unorthodox position.} 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Rb1 {White goes knight hunting, but Black can be happy with where the knight ends up.} (17. c7 $5 {is a tricky move. It's important to know that} Rd7 $4 {loses to} 18. Rb1 Nd3 19. Rb8 {so it's important to play Rf8= instead. But then Black is doing fine, with ... Ba6 and ... Rc8 coming up.}) 17... Nd3 18. Bc4 (18. Rb5 a6 19. Rb6 Ra7 {is similar to the main line. The white pawn on c6 remains a long-term target.}) 18... Ne5 19. Bb5 a6 20. Ba4 {white's weird bishop maneuver hasn't been in vain, because the c6 -pawn is better protected than normal in these lines. Even so, it remains a long-term weakness, and Black has some very interesting ideas too.} Ra7 {Planning Rc7 to pressure the c6 -pawn.} 21. f4 {White wants to kick the knight away from its pressure on the c6 -pawn, but all pawn moves leave weaknesses, and this one is no exception.} Nd3 22. h3 c4 {Black's knight has been kicked around a lot, but it's very close to finding a permanent home now.} 23. g4 {White is gaining space, and finding room for the king to get off the first rank, to enable the rook to join the game, but Black isn't just gonna sit still and watch White gradually push forward.} h6 24. Kg2 g5 {A great counterstrike on the kingside! Black has well-placed pieces and good chances in this very complicated queenless middlegame.} *

