1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. Nge2 {By far white's most logical move.} (8. Be3 $6 {This is a bad way to defend the pawn, as it allows Black to develop with a threat after} cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 {and White will have to move the bishop again without putting pressure on Black's development.}) 8... O-O {We want to castle before playing Nc6 to avoid funky lines with d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. dxc5 {As we will see, this is actually a risky move. But it's definitely also the most testing one for Black's concept.} (10. O-O {gives Black very easy play after} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {when White will have to trade away any hope of an advantage.}) 10... Ne5 11. Ba2 Nd3+ 12. Kf1 {It's a big concession for White to move the king, but White is hoping it doesn't matter in an endgame. However, Black doesn't have to acquiesce to White's plan.} b6 {This is the key move! Black has no intention to cashing in on the pawn just yet. Instead, the bishop gets a route to a6 , from where it will point down towards White's king.} (12... Bxc5 $2 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. e5 {would play straight into White's hands, when the uncastled White king would not be a major feature in the position as Black has no pieces in attacking positions.}) 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Rb1 {is the simple way of protecting the b2 -pawn.} Ba6 {Black continues the plan, but as does White.} 15. b4 {If White is allowed to play b5 , Black's counterplay may get shut down, so it's important to have a plan B. In Black's case: Getting the rook to the d-file.} Ra7 16. b5 Bb7 17. a4 {This is natural given the threat on a3 , but then Black strikes!} Bxe4 {Magnificent! Black is willing to give a full piece to get the rook involved quickly, and remove one of the few pawns defending White's king. White has a choice, but both are very scary.} 18. fxe4 Rd7 19. h3 {To stop Ng4 -ideas.} Bc5 {This is such a stunning move. Instead of trying some sort of discovered attack, Black exchanges off the best defensive piece around White's king.} 20. Bxc5 Nxc5 21. Qe1 Nfxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 {Black is down a bishop for a pawn, but look how useless White's bishop is. It's blocked by the Black pawns, locked in behind White's own queenside pawns and unable to find a clear safe haven. In addition, White has big trouble getting the h1 -rook into the game, without making white's precarious king position even worse. The computers tell us Black has a very promising future.} *

