ith d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. dxc5 {As we will see, this is actually a risky move. But it's definitely also the most testing one for Black's concept.} (10. O-O {gives Black very easy play after} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {when White will have to trade away any hope of an advantage.}) 10... Ne5 11. Ba2 Nd3+ 12. Kf1 {It's a big concession for White to move the king, but White is hoping it doesn't matter in an endgame. However, Black doesn't have to acquiesce to White's plan.} b6 {This is the key move! Black has no intention to cashing in on the pawn just yet. Instead, the bishop gets a route to a6 , from where it will point down towards White's king.} (12... Bxc5 $2 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. e5 {would play straight into White's hands, when the uncastled White king would not be a major feature in the position as Black has no pieces in attacking positions.}) 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Qc2 {is not the best way to defend the b2 -pawn...} Bc5 15. Bxc5 bxc5 {we have a repeating pattern from earlier, where the pawn on c5 does an excellent job of stopping White's b2 - b4 - b5 -idea.} 16. Bc4 {Therefore, to stop the Black bishop from getting to a6 , White plays this, but the resulting position is very reminiscent of the Benko gambit:} Ne5 17. Bb5 Qb6 18. a4 Ba6 {Black has given a queenside pawn, but that means the Black rooks has great pressure down the open files there. White's main problem though is the king. With Black's queen looming on the b6 - g1 -diagonal, White can't get the king to safety. All in all, Black has an initiative worth a pawn and then some.} *

