1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {The f3-Nimzo is the most aggressive of all White's options on move 4. It's not a very subtle move: White wants to take complete control in the center with e4 next, at the cost of delaying development. It's especially worth noting that White's knight on g1 is robbed of its best square, which means Black's development advantage can become very significant.  However, after investigating numerous complicated lines where Black tries to show the advantages of quick development over central control, I came to the conclusion that White gets what they want: Yes, there are numerous alternatives for Black to get interesting positions, but all of them involve going into complicated, unexplored territory, which frankly is precisely what an 4. f3 player is after.  This line attracts a very specific kind of player, who thrives in unexplored openings with rich complications -- so I decided to go for a solid, unknown line that seeks to get the white player out of their style.} d5 5. a3 Be7 {This is not the most common move, but I like keeping the bishop pair for later.} 6. e4 dxc4 {Here's the surprise! This move is extremely rare, but very solid. We're ready to strike in the center next move with c5 .} (6... e5 {transposes to 7.Bxc4 lines after Nfd7 Bxc4} 7. c5 {.}) 7. Bxc4 {By far the most natural move, white just recaptures the pawn. Now it's important for Black to make their presence felt in the center.} c5 {White has three main ways of dealing with the threat against d4 : Exchange, move forward or protect. The latter is the most logical, as it also helps white's development -- but we'll study all options.} 8. Nge2 {By far white's most logical move.} (8. Be3 $6 {This is a bad way to defend the pawn, as it allows Black to develop with a threat after} cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 {and White will have to move the bishop again without putting pressure on Black's development.}) 8... O-O {We want to castle before playing Nc6 to avoid funky lines with d5 and Bb5 +, which could cause some trouble.} 9. Be3 Nc6 {This is the key move! We're playing a pawn sacrifice.} 10. dxc5 {As we will see, this is actually a risky move. But it's definitely also the most testing one for Black's concept.} (10. O-O {gives Black very easy play after} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 {when White will have to trade away any hope of an advantage.}) 10... Ne5 11. Ba2 Nd3+ 12. Kf1 {It's a big concession for White to move the king, but White is hoping it doesn't matter in an endgame. However, Black doesn't have to acquiesce to White's plan.} b6 {This is the key move! Black has no intention to cashing in on the pawn just yet. Instead, the bishop gets a route to a6 , from where it will point down towards White's king.} (12... Bxc5 $2 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. e5 {would play straight into White's hands, when the uncastled White king would not be a major feature in the position as Black has no pieces in attacking positions.}) 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Qd2 Ba6 15. b4 {It's crucial for White to prevent the bishop's influence on the a6 - f1 diagonal by pushing the b-pawn forward.} Ra7 16. b5 {White manages to stop Black's annoying bishop, but there's new trouble to deal with as Black's rook is joining the game via d7 .} Bc8 17. Nd4 {White is looking for Nc6 while also intercepting the Black queen's defence of the d3 -knight, forcing a retreat.} Ne5 18. f4 {If the knight moves white will have Nc6 -- so this is when the fun begins.} Nfg4 {A piece sacrifice!} 19. fxe5 Nxe3+ 20. Qxe3 Bc5 21. Rd1 (21. Nce2 $2 Rxa3 22. Qd2 Bb7 {wins for black. There's a pin both on the d-file and on the a-file, while White's kingside rook is still nowhere near joining the game.}) 21... Rd7 22. Nce2 Qc7 {With White properly tied up in the center, it's time to harvest the spoils. This is a tremendously complicated position, but I think it's fair to say it's easier to be Black than White. For instance:} 23. Qc1 Qxe5 24. Nf3 Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Qxe4 {Leaves White with a piece for a pawn. Excellent, you'd think -- but White's pieces are in shambles. The bishop on c5 is a monster, the other bishop will become a monster on b7 , all the while White's king is still struggling and the rook stuck in the corner. Black has interesting prospects for the piece.} *

