1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 5. Nf3 {The knight defends the pawn, but it will have to work for its oats now as we develop pieces while attacking it.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 {A developing move which also posts a question what to do with White’s knight. There are three main options.} 7. Nc2 {The knight comes all the way over to the queenside to chase Black’s bishop back.} ({I.} 7. a3 {transposes to other lines, depending on what White does next.} Be7 8. Nxc6 (8. e3 {is studied in the 7. e3 -line. After O-O We’re back in the mainline there.}) 8... dxc6 {is studied in the 7. Nxc6 line.}) ({II.} 7. e3 {Defending the knight is sensible, but not exciting by any measure. Black just continues developing sensibly.} O-O 8. a3 Be7 9. Be2 d5 {Our standard strike in the center} 10. cxd5 Nxd4 $1 {A clever intermezzo, giving White an isolated d-pawn} 11. exd4 Nxd5 {If anyone’s a little better, it’s Black.}) 7... Bxc3 {We’re only giving White the bishop pair temporarily.} 8. Bxc3 Ne4 ({We’re not going to let White’s dark-squared bishop roam around uncontested. Bxg7? Doesn’t work because of} 8... Qa5 {}) 9. Qd3 {The only way to avoid doubled pawns!} Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Qa5 {White is unable to pose problems in the endgame.} 11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. e4 b6 {Yes, we let White have a big center, but there are no problems getting Black’s pieces activated. The king can stay in the center, we’ll put a rook on the c-file and White won’t win when we have no weaknesses.} *

