1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 5. Nf3 {The knight defends the pawn, but it will have to work for its oats now as we develop pieces while attacking it.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Nxc6 {The exchange is not as innocent as it looks. Black needs to know how to recapture.} dxc6 {It’s unusual to capture away from the center, but it keeps the symmetry of the position, and we’ll get e5 to activate the light-squared bishop soon.} ({You should avoid} 7... bxc6 {because after} 8. a3 Be7 9. e4 {White has a nice central structure. The c8 -bishop struggles to get into play.}) 8. a3 Be7 9. Qc2 {This allows e5 , but stops Bf5 in the future. The attempt to stop e5 immediately is ill-advised.} (9. Bf4 Nd7 $1 {We insist on getting our e5 -plan!} 10. Qc2 e5 11. Bg3 {White succeeded in developing the bishop outside the pawns, but that’s not always a good thing.} O-O 12. e3 f5 $1 {It turns out the g3 -bishop spent two moves only to land itself in big trouble. Black has a serious initiative.}) 9... e5 10. e3 O-O 11. Bd3 Qd6 {This is a clever move, preparing ... Rd8 to bother White’s bishops lined up on the d-file. Black is perfectly fine.} *

