1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 {We strike immediately!} 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishops, but it's a short-lived pleasure.} Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4 {I'll be taking out that bishop pair, thank you very much.} 7. Rc1 Qh4 {Very direct play, but the threats along the fourth rank makes it worthwhile.} 8. g3 Nxc3 {White wants to play Rxc3 , but needs to keep the d4 -pawn protected. So instead White is left with doubled pawns, either on the c-file or the h-file.} 9. gxh4 {This is the better option, as White can use the rook on the g-file.} Nxd1 10. Rxd1 cxd4 {Keeping White's damaged pawn structure in mind, we have no problem going for an endgame.} 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Ke7 {Black has a comfortable position. g6 will shut down any threats down the g-file, and we'll play d6 and e5 to take dark-squared control and get the bishop out.} *

