1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 {We strike immediately!} 5. d5 {When playing c5 you always have to ask yourself what you'll do if White just continues forward and grabs space in the center. In this instance it's a risky endeavor from White.} exd5 6. cxd5 {We have the so-called Benoni pawn structure. It's a very nice pawn structure for Black, but it can get very cramped -- which is why the general rule of thumb is to trade pieces when you can.} O-O 7. a3 {This plays into Black's hands, as we can trade without letting White have the bishop pair:} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 {Two minor pieces got traded off, and Black can be very happy about the resulting position. Get a rook on the e-file and a knight to e5 , when Black is doing very well.} *

