1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 {We strike immediately!} 5. dxc5 {When playing minimalistic openings, you have to appreciate the small things in life. In this case: White gives up the central pawn to make Black's bishop move for a second time.} Bxc5 6. g3 {Going for the fianchetto is the only way to make independent of the lines where White played e3 on move four.} O-O 7. Bg2 d5 {I don't make a habit out of giving myself an isolated queen's pawn (IQP), so when I do, you know it's good. Play becomes very reminiscent of the Tarrasch opening, but there's a major difference: White's knight on c3 is a bigger target than normal because White has captured on c5 early, which enables d4 from Black.} 8. Nf3 {This leaves White wondering how to get the pawn back after dxc4 .} dxc4 9. O-O Nbd7 {It's possible to use the queen to get the pawn back.} 10. Qa4 a6 11. Qxc4 b5 {Black has been able to develop the biggest problem piece in the position -- the bishop on c8 .} 12. Qh4 Bb7 {Black has perfect coordination.} *

