1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {Going Bd2 immediately poses fewer problems for Black, because a3 (the critical test of Black's c5 -response) is much less effective here than without e3 and O-O included first.} c5 {We strike immediately!} 5. dxc5 {When playing minimalistic openings, you have to appreciate the small things in life. In this case: White gives up the central pawn to make Black's bishop move for a second time.} Bxc5 6. g3 {Going for the fianchetto is the only way to make independent of the lines where White played e3 on move four.} O-O 7. Bg2 d5 {I don't make a habit out of giving myself an isolated queen's pawn (IQP), so when I do, you know it's good. Play becomes very reminiscent of the Tarrasch opening, but there's a major difference: White's knight on c3 is a bigger target than normal because White has captured on c5 early, which enables d4 from Black.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Na4 {I think this is an accurate move order from White, since the bishop is forced back where it will block Black's rook.} Be7 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. O-O d4 {Even though White's knight isn't on c3 , we're still pushing our pawn forward in the middle. We're taking out the knight's retreat square.} 12. Rc1 Re8 {We're expecting the bishop to move soon, when the rook will be very useful pointing down on e2 .} 13. Ne1 {This is a typical maneuver in this opening, getting the knight to a nice square while opening up for the fianchettoed bishop.} Bf5 14. Nd3 Be4 {Black gets rid of the bishop with the great pressure down the board, while White grows more and more concerned about Black's space advantage in the center. The pawn on d4 is doing a great job restricting White's pieces.} *

