1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This chapter is about lines where White plays Bd2 , but the best version of those lines for White is to start with e3 first. It's a finesse which allows an important Ne2 in many variations.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd2 {This innocent bishop move has become high-fashion at the top level. In some ways this is a waiting move just like Black's last: White doesn't want to commit their kingside pieces until Black reveals which central break -- c5 or d5 -- is on the menu.} c5 {I prefer this move. It puts immediate pressure on White's center and with it also White's concept.} 6. dxc5 {Doesn't pose any danger for Black. We simply recapture and then develop.} Bxc5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. a3 {Taking control of the b4 -square is very useful, and it also allows the b4 -advance in the future.} a6 {I like this move! We're giving the bishop a retreat square on a7 should white play b4 to push Black's bishop back. This way we get to keep our control of the very important square d4 .} 9. Qc2 d5 10. cxd5 {The only way to cause trouble is by giving Black an isolated queen's pawn (known as an IQP) in the center, but in this instance, the IQP is actually a strength.} exd5 11. Be2 d4 {The IQP strikes before White got the king to safety!} 12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. O-O Qc7 {Black is very slightly better because of the strong bishop in the center.} *

