1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This chapter is about lines where White plays Bd2 , but the best version of those lines for White is to start with e3 first. It's a finesse which allows an important Ne2 in many variations.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd2 {This innocent bishop move has become high-fashion at the top level. In some ways this is a waiting move just like Black's last: White doesn't want to commit their kingside pieces until Black reveals which central break -- c5 or d5 -- is on the menu.} c5 {I prefer this move. It puts immediate pressure on White's center and with it also White's concept.} 6. Nf3 {This is a combination of plans that doesn't work well together. In the Bd2 -lines we often want the knight on e2 .} cxd4 7. exd4 d5 {Black strikes in the center.} 8. c5 {The only way to avoid dxc4 , which would give White an isolated pawn, but this allows Black to target White's queenside.} b6 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 {White got the bishop pair and a queenside majority -- but keeping the queenside pawns in place without allowing an attack on the uncastled king will be a challenge.} Ne4 11. Rc1 a5 {A great move, preparing Ba6 which exchanges the bishop that traditionally gets locked-in by the d5 - e6 central pawn formation while simultaneously eliminating White's bishop pair.} 12. Bb5 Ba6 13. a4 {This is white's best chance of keeping control on the light squares, but at the same time it loses the ability to play b4 and support White's double-edged pawn on c5 .} Qe7 {Black is trying to force the c5 -pawn's hand by pointing all the pieces towards it.} 14. O-O Rc8 {The pawn will be captured on c5 next unless it moves.} 15. cxb6 Qb7 {Black will regain the pawn with a nice position. Black's pieces are no longer being restricted by the space-grabbing pawn on c5 .} 16. Bxa5 Bxb5 17. axb5 Rxa5 {Wins for Black.} *

