1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This chapter is about lines where White plays Bd2 , but the best version of those lines for White is to start with e3 first. It's a finesse which allows an important Ne2 in many variations.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd2 {This innocent bishop move has become high-fashion at the top level. In some ways this is a waiting move just like Black's last: White doesn't want to commit their kingside pieces until Black reveals which central break -- c5 or d5 -- is on the menu.} c5 {I prefer this move. It puts immediate pressure on White's center and with it also White's concept.} 6. Bd3 {This is also a mix of two different plans. If White wanted to play with the bishop to d3 early on, it would be better to do so on the previous move.} d5 7. cxd5 cxd4 {I like inserting this capture in the center because it gives Black an option to retreat the bishop if prodded by a3 , while also securing a very stable central pawn formation.} 8. exd4 exd5 {This is very similar to other lines we're investigating within the 4. e3 line. However, here White has committed the bishop to d2 , which is not a very challenging line to deal with for Black. We're usually more nervous when white puts the bishop on g5 .} 9. Nge2 h6 {Since white spent a move on Bd2 , we even have time to spend a move preventing Bg5 !} 10. O-O Nc6 {Black has free development and no problems.} 11. Kh1 {This is actually a typical attacking plan for this position. But with nice centralized pieces, there's no need to panic.} Re8 {Rook on the open file!} 12. f3 Bd6 {We weren't going to exchange the bishop for the knight, so rerouting it to point towards White's king is best.} 13. g4 {The point of White's play! It's a kingside attack. White plans Rg1 and g5 to create trouble for Black's king.} Nh7 {This is Black's best solution. The g5 -advance is looking very difficult to make happen, while there's no need to fear the d5 -pawn being captured...} 14. Nxd5 Bxh2 {Winning back the pawn while removing an important defender.} 15. Kxh2 Qxd5 {White's king will be uncomfortable as long as the queens remain on the board.} *

