1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This chapter is about lines where White plays Bd2 , but the best version of those lines for White is to start with e3 first. It's a finesse which allows an important Ne2 in many variations.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd2 {This innocent bishop move has become high-fashion at the top level. In some ways this is a waiting move just like Black's last: White doesn't want to commit their kingside pieces until Black reveals which central break -- c5 or d5 -- is on the menu.} c5 {I prefer this move. It puts immediate pressure on White's center and with it also White's concept.} 6. a3 {This is White's best move. Our bishop has no retreat, so we'll have to give up the bishop pair.} Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {We don't want to play against White's two bishops, so we're immediately moving to take out the c3 -bishop.} 8. Ne2 {As is typical for the 4. e3 line, White's knight finds a useful square on e2 , lending support to the piece on c3 . If Black just trades white will be up on both central control and development, so it's better to delay the capture and exploit that white struggles to continue development since the f1 -bishop is being blocked by the e2 -knight.} b6 {This is Black's main move. We combine development with reinforcing the annoying knight on e4 . If White tries to attack the knight we're ready with Bb7 to defend it.} 9. Qc2 {Threatens the knight.} Bb7 {When white still has trouble getting the f1 -bishop into play.} 10. f3 {If White has to play this move to force the knight away, it may have been better doing it earlier.} Nxc3 11. Nxc3 cxd4 {Opening up the center to create weaknesses to attack and exploit superior development.} 12. exd4 Nc6 {First Black goes after the d4 -pawn, but the c4 -pawn could also end up in trouble with Rc8 and Na5 just around the corner.} *

