1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This chapter is about lines where White plays Bd2 , but the best version of those lines for White is to start with e3 first. It's a finesse which allows an important Ne2 in many variations.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd2 {This innocent bishop move has become high-fashion at the top level. In some ways this is a waiting move just like Black's last: White doesn't want to commit their kingside pieces until Black reveals which central break -- c5 or d5 -- is on the menu.} c5 {I prefer this move. It puts immediate pressure on White's center and with it also White's concept.} 6. a3 {This is White's best move. Our bishop has no retreat, so we'll have to give up the bishop pair.} Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {We don't want to play against White's two bishops, so we're immediately moving to take out the c3 -bishop.} 8. Ne2 {As is typical for the 4. e3 line, White's knight finds a useful square on e2 , lending support to the piece on c3 . If Black just trades white will be up on both central control and development, so it's better to delay the capture and exploit that white struggles to continue development since the f1 -bishop is being blocked by the e2 -knight.} b6 {This is Black's main move. We combine development with reinforcing the annoying knight on e4 . If White tries to attack the knight we're ready with Bb7 to defend it.} 9. d5 {This is White's best plan, grabbing space in the center and preemptively blocking the b7 - e4 -diagonal, claiming Black's bishop will be ineffective. But b7 wasn't the only square we could move the bishop to.} Ba6 10. Qd3 {White both defends the c4 -pawn and attacks the knight.} exd5 {Seemingly this walks into a double-attack, but there's more to the story.} 11. Qxd5 Qe7 {This is key -- We can give up the rook since White's queen will be trapped afterward.} 12. Qd3 {The queen retreats to protect the bishop on c3 , thereby enabling Nf4 next move, which would take dominating control of the d5 -square.} d5 ({A fantastic sacrifice! The queen is invited back to d5 to act as a punching ball as all Black's pieces get involved.} 12... Nc6 {would play into White's plans.} 13. Nf4 {when White has a great grip on the important d5 -square.}) 13. Qxd5 Nd7 {This stops any queen trade with Qe5 . In order to complete development white must once again return to d3 to free the knight of its responsibility defending the c3 -bishop.} 14. Qd3 Bb7 {Stunningly calm play! Black gives extra protection to the e4 -knight and d5 -square.} 15. Nf4 {Without the d7 -pawn, white's grip on the d5 -square is a completely different story, since the rooks can get involved on the open file.} Ne5 16. Bxe5 Rad8 {Not even recapturing the bishop, black is just getting every piece involved.} 17. Nd5 Qxe5 {Black is about to win back the pawn on d5 with a very active position.} *

