fends the c4 -pawn and attacks the knight.} exd5 {Seemingly this walks into a double-attack, but there's more to the story.} 11. Qxd5 Qe7 {This is key -- We can give up the rook since White's queen will be trapped afterward.} 12. g3 {This is the only move previously played in this position, by the German grandmaster Blübaum.} Nc6 13. Bg2 {It's time to say goodbye to our knight.} Nxc3 14. Nxc3 {White has fantastic control of the d5 -square, but an accurate sacrifice by Black will turn the tables.} Na5 {Targeting the c4 -pawn, and there's no way for White to defend it.} 15. Qd1 {Ah, but there is a counter threat. The bishop attacks the rook on a8 while the queen eyes the b3 -square, to protect the c4 -pawn with b3 next.} Bxc4 {A brilliant sacrifice! Black captures a pawn, grabs control of the d5 -square and prevents White from castling, all at once.} 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 {Black has a bishop, a pawn and amazing light-squared control in return for the rook.} 17. Qf3 Re8 18. O-O-O {White got the king out of the center, but his majesty is not safe on the queenside either.} b5 {Black has good attacking chances.} *

