s to use pawns in an attempt to keep Black's bishop locked away on the queenside, but we're having none of it.} b5 {An absolutely necessary move. We need to weaken White's pawns to keep our bishop in play.} 11. Qd3 {White finally gets the knight off the e4 -square. But there are some nuances between putting the queen on d3 or c2 .} Nxc3 (11... exd5 12. cxb5 $1 {is an additional option for White.} Bb7 13. Ng3 {We end up with a weird central pawn structure the engine says favors White.}) 12. Nxc3 bxc4 13. bxc4 exd5 {This is a good moment to open up the position. Yes, White gets a great square on d5 , but Black will in return cause some trouble for the uncastled king.} 14. Qxd5 {Becomes similar to the main line.} Qa5 {forces White back into defence.} 15. Qd2 Nc6 16. Be2 Rab8 {Taking control of the open file, before targeting the c4 -pawn.} 17. O-O Ne5 {Black got all the pieces working together. There's no way to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's threat of capturing the d7 -pawn in return means it's an equal position.} *

