s to use pawns in an attempt to keep Black's bishop locked away on the queenside, but we're having none of it.} b5 {An absolutely necessary move. We need to weaken White's pawns to keep our bishop in play.} 11. Qd3 {White finally gets the knight off the e4 -square. But there are some nuances between putting the queen on d3 or c2 .} Nxc3 (11... exd5 12. cxb5 $1 {is an additional option for White.} Bb7 13. Ng3 {We end up with a weird central pawn structure the engine says favors White.}) 12. Nxc3 bxc4 13. bxc4 exd5 {This is a good moment to open up the position. Yes, White gets a great square on d5 , but Black will in return cause some trouble for the uncastled king.} 14. Nxd5 Nc6 15. Be2 {This prepares to get the king to safety as soon as possible.} Qa5+ {The castling interruption comes just at the right moment.} 16. Qc3 Rab8 {There's no rush for Black to exchange. First we take control of the open file.} 17. O-O Qxc3 18. Nxc3 Na5 {The c4 -pawn is surrounded.} 19. Ne4 {Luckily for White, this counterattack keeps the material balance.} Bxc4 20. Bxc4 Nxc4 21. Nxc5 Rfc8 {Black has extremely active pieces, but a draw is the most likely result still.} 22. Nxd7 {If White goes for another pawn, it's tricky to see how the knight gets out.} Rb7 23. Rfd1 f6 {The engine says White's knight can be saved with correct play, but it's definitely white sweating here.} *

