1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This chapter is about lines where White plays Bd2 , but the best version of those lines for White is to start with e3 first. It's a finesse which allows an important Ne2 in many variations.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd2 {This innocent bishop move has become high-fashion at the top level. In some ways this is a waiting move just like Black's last: White doesn't want to commit their kingside pieces until Black reveals which central break -- c5 or d5 -- is on the menu.} c5 {I prefer this move. It puts immediate pressure on White's center and with it also White's concept.} 6. a3 {This is White's best move. Our bishop has no retreat, so we'll have to give up the bishop pair.} Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {We don't want to play against White's two bishops, so we're immediately moving to take out the c3 -bishop.} 8. Ne2 {As is typical for the 4. e3 line, White's knight finds a useful square on e2 , lending support to the piece on c3 . If Black just trades white will be up on both central control and development, so it's better to delay the capture and exploit that white struggles to continue development since the f1 -bishop is being blocked by the e2 -knight.} b6 {This is Black's main move. We combine development with reinforcing the annoying knight on e4 . If White tries to attack the knight we're ready with Bb7 to defend it.} 9. d5 {This is White's best plan, grabbing space in the center and preemptively blocking the b7 - e4 -diagonal, claiming Black's bishop will be ineffective. But b7 wasn't the only square we could move the bishop to.} Ba6 10. b3 {White continues to use pawns in an attempt to keep Black's bishop locked away on the queenside, but we're having none of it.} b5 {An absolutely necessary move. We need to weaken White's pawns to keep our bishop in play.} 11. Qc2 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 {The main benefit of this move is that it prevents Black from playing b4 , which may leave the bishop on a6 out of play.} d6 14. Ng3 Nd7 {The knight is making its way to f6 , to put pressure on the d5 -pawn.} 15. Be2 Nf6 16. e4 {Using the pawn as a protector looks natural, but it falls victim to clever tactics:} b4 {Black gets the bishop into play while simultaneously creating a dangerous attack.} 17. axb4 Bxe2 18. Kxe2 {Capturing with the knight would lose the e4 -pawn immediately, so White's king is going on an adventure.} Re8 {Black has tremendous compensation for the pawn. White will count themselves lucky to survive the opening.} *

