s to use pawns in an attempt to keep Black's bishop locked away on the queenside, but we're having none of it.} b5 {An absolutely necessary move. We need to weaken White's pawns to keep our bishop in play.} 11. Qc2 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 {The main benefit of this move is that it prevents Black from playing b4 , which may leave the bishop on a6 out of play.} d6 14. Ng3 Nd7 {The knight is making its way to f6 , to put pressure on the d5 -pawn.} 15. Be2 Nf6 16. Qd2 Re8 17. O-O Rb8 {Black's big problem in this position is the bishop on a6 . Rb8 tries to help the bishop find a better position by taking over the defensive task of protecting the b5 -pawn. In a dream world Black would like to follow up with Bc8 and a5 , staking a claim to the queenside.} 18. a4 {White increases the pressure on b5 to prevent the bishop from backing up, but Black has a stunning sacrifice.} h5 {It turns out the knight can't feel safe on g3 .} 19. Nxh5 {White is happy to capture what is seemingly a free pawn.} Nxh5 20. Bxh5 bxa4 {The discovered attack on f1 may look devastating at first, but thanks to the a1 -rook pointing down towards the a6 -bishop, things are not so clear...} 21. Rfc1 Bb5 {I have no words for this move, recommended by the engines. Black is willing to go into a position with a pawn down, as long as White's rooks are blocked out of play, by White's a4 -pawn and Black's c5 -pawn respectively.} 22. bxa4 Bd7 {Black will try to establish a rook on b4 , where it will be dominating procedures. Black has good play for the pawn.} *

