[Black "Rubinstein with 4.e3 / 5.Nge2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E46"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Ng3 {White gets the knight out of the way while protecting the pawn on c4 .} dxc4 {This is the right moment to strike in the center. Yes, we allow white to develop the bishop in one move, but we also get good pressure against the d4 -pawn next.} 8. Bxc4 c5 {The pressure on the d4 -pawn forces White to make a big decision: trade off all pawns (and queens) in the center, or allow Black to create an isolated queen's pawn structure.} 9. O-O {An uncomprimising move, rejecting the queen trade. But at the same time, White now has to deal with a long-term target in the position: the isolated pawn on d4 .} cxd4 10. exd4 Nbd7 {This is an important move to prevent white's pawn from moving forward in the center. The knight is headed for b6 , where it will both attack white's bishop, but more importantly control the d5 -square.} 11. Bb3 {The bishop pre-emptively moves away, but that doesn't stop our plan.} Nb6 {Any pawn break with d5 is under control.} 12. Bf4 Bd7 {In these structures, finding a placement for the light-squared bishop is often the biggest problem. Had White's knight been on f3 , it would jump up to e5 and ruin Black's pawn structure by capturing on c6 once the Black bishop reached its desired destination. Here however, with the knight on g3 , Black's bishop finds a great outpost on c6 .} 13. Be5 Bc6 {Black has succeeded in developing the pieces to good positions, while White still has a long-term issue protecting the isolated pawn in the center. The position may be equal, but I would definitely prefer Black in practical play. Plans moving forward include Rc8 , Nfd5 , Qd7 and Rfd8 .} *

