1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Ng3 {White gets the knight out of the way while protecting the pawn on c4 .} dxc4 {This is the right moment to strike in the center. Yes, we allow white to develop the bishop in one move, but we also get good pressure against the d4 -pawn next.} 8. Bxc4 c5 {The pressure on the d4 -pawn forces White to make a big decision: trade off all pawns (and queens) in the center, or allow Black to create an isolated queen's pawn structure.} 9. d5 {White tries to avoid the queen trade while also avoiding the isolated pawn in the center.} exd5 {This is Black's simplest solution.} 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Qb6 {Our queen protects the e6 -square, so we can offer a trade of bishops without splitting up our kingside pawns.} 12. O-O Be6 13. e4 {Pushing the e-pawn opens up for White's bishop, but it also gives Black access to the d4 -square.} Nc6 {Our concerns about having to use our pawn to recapture on e6 expired when the d4 -square opened up for our pieces. A trade now would just make it easier for us to get a rook on the d-file to further our control of the d4 -square.} 14. Be3 a5 {One last cautionary move: We stop any thought White had of playing b4 . Next up is a rook to the d-file and eventually getting the knight to d4 . Black's position is very straightforward.} *

