1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Ng3 {White gets the knight out of the way while protecting the pawn on c4 .} dxc4 {This is the right moment to strike in the center. Yes, we allow white to develop the bishop in one move, but we also get good pressure against the d4 -pawn next.} 8. Bxc4 c5 {The pressure on the d4 -pawn forces White to make a big decision: trade off all pawns (and queens) in the center, or allow Black to create an isolated queen's pawn structure.} 9. d5 {White tries to avoid the queen trade while also avoiding the isolated pawn in the center.} b5 {Adventurous players may enjoy the tricky pawn structure arising here when White's bishop is forced to give up protection of the d5 -pawn.} 10. Bxb5 exd5 11. O-O Be6 {Black holds a nice center with the so-called 'hanging pawns' pawn formation, but White is not without plans to break it down.} 12. Nce2 {The knight is re-routed to f4 .} Nbd7 13. Nf4 Qb6 {Black has pressure down the queenside and good control in the center, but White's pawn breaks (in particular e4 at the right moment) and attacking potential on the kingside should not be underestimated. It's a very unclear situation.} *

