1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Ng3 {White gets the knight out of the way while protecting the pawn on c4 .} dxc4 {This is the right moment to strike in the center. Yes, we allow white to develop the bishop in one move, but we also get good pressure against the d4 -pawn next.} 8. Bxc4 c5 {The pressure on the d4 -pawn forces White to make a big decision: trade off all pawns (and queens) in the center, or allow Black to create an isolated queen's pawn structure.} 9. dxc5 {Taking the pawn is definitely the safer option, but it's not the way to put pressure on Black's position.} Qxd1+ {The queen trade should be made when White doesn't have the option to capture back on d1 with a rook. Now White will have to spend extra time reorganizing the pieces.} 10. Kxd1 Bxc5 11. Ke2 Bd7 {I like this move because it disrupts White's optimal setup with a knight on e4 .} 12. Nge4 {White tries to go for a well-placed knight, but it will be dislodged in no time.} Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Be7 14. Bd2 Bc6 {The knight is threatened, but retreating it will lead to the loss of the g2 -pawn.} 15. f3 Bxe4 16. fxe4 Bf6 {Black is better because of White's broken pawns and the fantastic outpost for a knight on e5 .} *

