[PlyCount "28"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Nf4 {This is an aggressive placement for the knight, but Black is still able to strike back in the center.} c6 {With White's knight on f4 , we can change our plan of pawn breaks in the center. In this c6 -line, we're planning e5 instead of c5 to attack White's center.} 8. Bd3 (8. cxd5 exd5 {pretty much solves all of Black's opening problems by giving us a Carlsbad structure where it's not clear how useful Nf4 is.}) 8... dxc4 {We force White to move the bishop for a second time in a row.} 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Our knight makes us ready for the e5 -break next.} 10. Bxe6 {White can try to strike before Black gets the central advance, but it comes at a cost.} fxe6 11. Nxe6 Qe8 12. Nc7 {This wins a rook without losing the knight immediately, but it also allows a devastating counter-attack.} Qg6 {The queen's infiltration on g2 will decide the game.} 13. Nxa8 Qxg2 14. Rf1 Ng4 {All black's pieces participate in the attack. It's a question of time before White must resign.} *

