1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Nf4 {This is an aggressive placement for the knight, but Black is still able to strike back in the center.} dxc4 {Just like after 7. Ng3 , this is a possible move. However, White's increased control of d5 thanks to the f4 -knight makes this a less effective line compared to when the knight was on g3 .} 8. Bxc4 c5 9. d5 {This feels natural...} e5 10. Nh5 Ne8 {Black's knight is rerouted to d6 , where it will be very effective in assisting Black's pawn advances b5 and f5 .} 11. e4 Nd6 12. Be2 Nd7 {Black plans c4 , b5 , g6 and f5 , gaining important control of both sides of the board. In the meantime White's d5 -pawn is going nowhere.} *

