1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. Nf4 {This is an aggressive placement for the knight, but Black is still able to strike back in the center.} dxc4 {Just like after 7. Ng3 , this is a possible move. However, White's increased control of d5 thanks to the f4 -knight makes this a less effective line compared to when the knight was on g3 .} 8. Bxc4 c5 9. O-O {I think going for the isolani is White's best option, as black is unable to create a blockade on the d5 -square.} cxd4 10. exd4 Nbd7 11. d5 {This is the extra option White has compared to when the f4 -knight is on g3 .} Nb6 12. Ba2 exd5 13. Nfxd5 Nfxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 {After the mass trade in the center, White is left with the slightly more active pieces, leaving Black to find some accurate moves for a draw.} *

