1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. c5 {This is frankly one of the reasons I chose to put the bishop on e7 . If we had retreated the bishop to d6 instead this move would come with an attack on the bishop and White would try to build a dominating force of pawns on the queenside. Now however, black is ready to start immediate counterplay against White's aggressive pawn play.} b6 {First we challenge the pawns.} 8. b4 {Now we get another chance to put pressure.} a5 9. Bd2 {The rook on a1 needed protection, so white's bishop steps out of the way to let the queen defend the corner rook.} c6 {This is generally a useful move for black. It takes control of the b5 -square, which means black can now go Ba6 without getting hit by White playing b5 , blocking the bishop out of play.} 10. Ng3 {White needed to move the knight to get the f1 -bishop involved, but it can't find a safe home anywhere.} h5 {Intending to push White's knight around. The pawn on h5 is immune because of the pressure against White's queenside pawns.} 11. h4 {Stopping Black's advance is inadvisable.} g6 {Black has protected the pawn on h5 , while White's knight on g3 means it's very difficult for White to do the same for their pawn on h4 . White will either have to move the knight again, or live with the h4 -pawn being a big headache for the rest of the game. Either way black is much better.} *

