1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. cxd5 {This exchange is often considered unfavorable for white, as it opens up for Black's light-squared bishop. Even so, in this position it is the only way to fight for an opening advantage. The key is that White's development of the knight to e2 has prevented quick development, and White needs to buy some time to get castled before Black makes a breakthrough in the center. By making the trade, White prevents the standard plan of dxc4 followed by c5 to remove all the pawns from the middle. After the trade, however, if Black wants to go c5 now, they'll have to accept an isolated pawn in the center.} exd5 8. g3 {The fianchetto used to be White's most popular option, but there are limits to how effective the bishop can be on g2 , as it's pointing into a rock-solid black pawn chain.} c6 {The center is well-guarded.} 9. Bg2 Na6 {Next step is to find a role for this knight. It will find a great home on c7 where it supports the d5 -pawn which in turn will enable the c5 -break in the future.} 10. O-O Nc7 11. f3 {White's strategy is to build a big center. To prevent this, Black's strategy is often to go c5 immediately after f3 -- making the claim that the backward e3 -pawn is just as vulnerable as the isolated d5 -pawn.} Re8 {Now black is ready for c5 , as the bishop and rook will coordinate together against the e3 -pawn.} 12. e4 {Pushing forward is the only way to punish Black for delaying the c5 -push, but it turns out the c5 -move will be very good now as well.} dxe4 13. fxe4 c5 {It's absolutely necessary for Black to strike back before we get steamrolled in the center. Black wins amazing control of the dark squares, with some great squares for the pieces.} 14. d5 Ng4 {The knight is headed for e5 . White's g2 -bishop is being blocked in by the white pawns. Overall Black's position is much easier to play.} *

