1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. cxd5 {This exchange is often considered unfavorable for white, as it opens up for Black's light-squared bishop. Even so, in this position it is the only way to fight for an opening advantage. The key is that White's development of the knight to e2 has prevented quick development, and White needs to buy some time to get castled before Black makes a breakthrough in the center. By making the trade, White prevents the standard plan of dxc4 followed by c5 to remove all the pawns from the middle. After the trade, however, if Black wants to go c5 now, they'll have to accept an isolated pawn in the center.} exd5 8. Ng3 {The knight moves to let the f1 -bishop into the game, but it puts no pressure on Black's center.} c5 {We're ready to take on the isolated pawn in the center because there's a great likelihood we'll be able to push it forward and trade it off while White is busy getting castled.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Na4 {This temporarily succeeds in stopping d4 , but the knight is not well-placed on a4 .} Bd6 {This square is the best, as there are situations when we want to take out the g3 -knight -- usually in the event White goes e4 after Black's d4 -push.} 11. Be2 {Getting the king out of the center is White's top priority now.} Nc6 12. O-O d4 {I'm not sure this is the best move, but it's the most clear-cut way of demonstrating that Black is doing fine at minimum. Despite making a lot of effort, White wasn't able to stop d4 after all.} 13. exd4 Bxg3 14. hxg3 Nxd4 {White got the bishop pair, but Black has active pieces, in particular the knight on d4 . White will likely allow Nxe2 + next move, making the position completely equal.} *

