1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. cxd5 {This exchange is often considered unfavorable for white, as it opens up for Black's light-squared bishop. Even so, in this position it is the only way to fight for an opening advantage. The key is that White's development of the knight to e2 has prevented quick development, and White needs to buy some time to get castled before Black makes a breakthrough in the center. By making the trade, White prevents the standard plan of dxc4 followed by c5 to remove all the pawns from the middle. After the trade, however, if Black wants to go c5 now, they'll have to accept an isolated pawn in the center.} exd5 8. Ng3 {The knight moves to let the f1 -bishop into the game, but it puts no pressure on Black's center.} c5 {We're ready to take on the isolated pawn in the center because there's a great likelihood we'll be able to push it forward and trade it off while White is busy getting castled.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 {White tries to stop d4 by attacking the bishop and forcing it to step back. We are not deterred, however.} d4 {White isn't the only one who can push pawns to pressure pieces.} 11. bxc5 dxc3 {Black's c3 -pawn is deep into White territory, but White's c5 -pawn is in just as much trouble.} 12. Qb3 {Eliminating the pawn is White's top priority.} Qa5 13. Ne2 {An undeveloping move, but it's needed to take out the c3 -pawn.} Na6 {We want to take on c5 , but we want to get our pieces involved while doing it.} 14. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 15. Nxc3 Nxc5 {White has the bishop pair, but Black has great development.} 16. Bb2 {White needed to avoid Nb3 , which would have eliminated White's only advantage: the bishops.} Bf5 17. f3 Rfd8 {Black has excellent development and is ready to plant something on d3 next.} *

