1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Nge2 {By reinforcing the knight on c3 with its twin, White avoids doubled pawns and will succeed in pushing Black's bishop back with a3 next. The big drawback is interrupting White's development by blocking the f1 -bishop.} d5 {Black immediately fights for central control.} 6. a3 Be7 {We have no interest in giving up the bishop pair on this occasion. Now White needs to decide how to deal with the threat on the c4 -pawn.} 7. cxd5 {This exchange is often considered unfavorable for white, as it opens up for Black's light-squared bishop. Even so, in this position it is the only way to fight for an opening advantage. The key is that White's development of the knight to e2 has prevented quick development, and White needs to buy some time to get castled before Black makes a breakthrough in the center. By making the trade, White prevents the standard plan of dxc4 followed by c5 to remove all the pawns from the middle. After the trade, however, if Black wants to go c5 now, they'll have to accept an isolated pawn in the center.} exd5 8. Nf4 {The knight puts pressure towards d5 , which means c5 isn't viable for Black.} c6 {Solidifying the center, but surprisingly also getting the c7 -square ready for a different piece!} 9. Bd3 Na6 {Our knight is headed for c7 , where it will give extra protection to the d5 -pawn (which is needed if we want to go c5 later), or it can move further to e6 to make some trades.} 10. Bxa6 {Giving Black doubled pawns on the edge may be tempting, but when the majority of White's pawns are on dark squares it's not a good decision to give up the light-squared bishop.} bxa6 11. O-O a5 {The pawn moves up to discourage White from playing b4 , while also giving the bishop a nice placement on a6 .} 12. Bd2 Ba6 13. Re1 Rb8 {The advantage of having doubled pawns is that there's more open files for the rooks!} 14. Qc2 Bd6 {The bishop puts extra pressure towards the kingside, but mostly this move is about clearing the e-file for the rook to point down.} 15. Rac1 {The main danger for Black is the backward pawn on c6 , and White's ability to put pressure on it, but as we will see, that's easy to deal with.} Re8 {Simple moves: Just putting the pieces on better squares.} 16. Na4 {White tries to attack down the c-file, but it's easily parried.} Bc4 {The bishop finds a great outpost and blocks the c-file. Black is better thanks to all the well-placed pieces.} *

