eaded for c7 , where it will give extra protection to the d5 -pawn (which is needed if we want to go c5 later), or it can move further to e6 to make some trades.} 10. O-O Nc7 11. f3 {White's long-term objective is to take control with the pawns in the center. This is step one of that plan.} Re8 {I like this move because it's the most clear-cut plan. Once White goes f3 , Black wants to play c5 and argue the pawn on e3 is just as weak as its counterpart on d5 . We need this move in preparation of c5 to add pressure to e3 .} 12. Nce2 {White understands the c5 -break cannot be prevented, and gets ready for how to deal with it when it does happen.} c5 {We're not discouraged by a knight planning to land on d4 .} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd4 {This was White's idea. The knight prevents the c5 -bishop's pressure on e3 .} Ne6 {I like this move, as we change the pawn structure for the second move in a row. Our d5 -pawn doesn't have to be lonely anymore.} 15. Nfxe6 fxe6 {No more isolani on d5 . Black is ready to advance in the center and generally has well-placed pieces. The position is unbalanced, but with even chances.} *

