1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. a3 {Leads to a familiar position.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nc6 {We've transposed to the mainline in the 4. a3 chapter.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 4.e3 6th Move Sidelines (R"]
[Black "Rubinstein 6th Moves: 6.Nge2 "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E47"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. c5 {This is a very ambitious attempt from White and frankly I'm surprised it hasn't been played more often. White tries to advance a pawn mass on the queenside, so we need to strike quickly.} b6 {Immediately attacking the advancing pawns.} 9. a3 Bxc3+ {Unfortunately we have to give up our bishop pair, and we won't even double White's pawns!} 10. Nxc3 Nc6 {This is a key move. The pawn on d4 is temporarily undefended, and the time we gain attacking it will be used to advance our own pawns in the center.} 11. Bb5 {White manages to defend the pawn while creating an attack of their own, but the bishop moves for a second time, away from what was already a good position.} Bb7 12. O-O {White got the king to safety, and is ready to reinforce the queenside pawns with b4 next.} bxc5 {We accept the challenge. This allows White to get a supermajority on the queenside, but we get the same thing in the center.} 13. dxc5 d4 {A very interesting position arises. Black has play in the center, while White pushes forward on the queenside. I like Black's centralization, but you shouldn't underestimate White's long-term potential with outside pawns and the bishop pair. The engines say equal, but in practical play it's anyone's game.} *

