1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. O-O {Castling allows Black to enter a very nice IQP-position.} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bd6 {The bishop had done its job on b4 , and by retreating this early we're creating trouble for White in finding an aggressive placement for their dark-squared bishop currently on c1 .} 10. Bg5 {White falls for the trap!} Bxh2+ {luring White's king out in the open, and capturing a pawn while we're at it.} 11. Kxh2 Ng4+ {Can't take our queen because it's check!} 12. Kg1 Qxg5 {We won the bishop back, with interest. The extra pawn gives Black a winning position.} *

