1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. O-O {Castling allows Black to enter a very nice IQP-position.} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bd6 {The bishop had done its job on b4 , and by retreating this early we're creating trouble for White in finding an aggressive placement for their dark-squared bishop currently on c1 .} 10. h3 {This move is necessary to stop Black's knight from going to g4 .} h6 {I like this as it prevents Bg5 .} 11. Be3 {Black's play the last couple of moves have forced White's bishop to a more passive placement than what it was hoping for.} Nbd7 {The time has come to control the d5 -square. The knight is headed for b6 .} 12. Qd2 Nb6 13. Bb3 Bd7 {More pieces to control the d5 -square! The bishop will be great on c6 .} 14. Rad1 Bc6 {Black has placed the pieces brilliantly. The d4 -pawn is going nowhere, and will be a target long-term.} 15. Bxh6 {This is the only way to punish Black's play, but with accurate defence Black will come out on top. One wrong step though and White's attack crashes through, so it's important to study.} gxh6 16. Qxh6 Re8 {Black gets ready for Bf8 to kick White's queen away.} 17. Rd3 {The rook wants to join via g3 .} Nh7 {We can't move the bishop away from g3 now, so we need a different way to kick White's queen away. Retreating the knight opens up for Qf6 next.} 18. Bc2 f5 ({The only saving move, but also good enough to win the game. White's intended attack down the diagonal is prevented. Just don't go} 18... Qf6 $2 {since after} 19. Rg3+ $1 Bxg3 20. Bxh7+ {Two checks in a row eliminate the defender of Black's queen.} Kh8 21. Qxf6+ {and it's time for Black to resign.}) *

