1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. a3 {It's a recurring question in the Nimzo: 'What if a3 now?'. This is one of the worse versions.} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 {Capturing with the pawn improves the defense of the d4 -pawn, but still doesn't escape the fact that White's pawn structure has some problems when compared to Black's.} dxc4 {The exchange forces White's bishop to move a second time, and to a worse square.} 10. Bxc4 {White's bishop would rather be on d3 , pointing towards the kingside. That would also allow the c-pawn to take a step forward in the center.} b6 {b7 will make a great square for Black's bishop, as it looks out on the long diagonal.} 11. O-O Bb7 12. Bd3 {A sensible move, but it also makes it absolutely clear that Black made a good decision and won a lot of time for development by capturing on c4 .} Nc6 {The knight temporarily blocks the bishop, but it is headed for c4 via a5 .} 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 Na5 {Black is close to getting a dream setup, with a rook to c8 , a knight to c4 and the mighty queen on d5 .} 15. c4 {White tries to deny Black control of the light squares in the center, but this is a mistake, met by a devastating trick.} Rc8 16. Rc1 g5 {A fantastic move. The main idea is actually to take control of the f4 -square, so that White's knight cannot jump there.} 17. Bg3 Nxc4 {A killer blow.} 18. Bxc4 Rxc4 {Boom!} 19. Rxc4 Qd5 {The double attack on g2 and c4 means White will have to give back the rook, after which Black has a winning position up a pawn.} *

