1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. cxd5 exd5 {Initially, this was my recommendation, which immediately takes us into symmetrical territory, and is the sister variation of my recommendation in the main line (the only difference being White's knight is on e2 instead of f3 ). However, it turns out the placement of White's e2 -knight is more significant than I originally thought. Black misses out on Bg4 -pins, as that can be met by f3 , and there are lines where the knight will jump to f4 and put lots of pressure on Black's central pawn. Some of my concerns is illustrated by this line:} 9. O-O Nc6 (9... h6 {is no better as White plays} 10. a3 {(I want to go Nc6 before a3 .)} Bd6 11. Nb5 {when having the retreat to b8 would be very useful.}) 10. h3 Re8 11. a3 Bd6 {At this moment, the best square for the bishop.} 12. Bg5 {White's pin is annoying, but the bishop dance we're about to witness is really spectacular.} Be7 {The bishop moves again, to avert the pin.} 13. Be3 {White's bishop also moves again!} (13. Nf4 {would be a mistake since} h6 {provides Black counterplay.}) 13... Bd6 {The third move in a row for the bishop, because it's needed to deal with the Nf4 -threat.} 14. Nf4 {White goes ahead anyway!} Nxd4 {This is the trick Black depended on, but after} 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qxd4 {Black has the bishop pair, but is also stuck with an isolated pawn in the center.} Be5 17. Qd3+ Kg8 18. Nfe2 {White has excellent control of the d4 -square. Next move is Bd4 , and then getting the rooks involved. Black's light-squared bishop struggles to find a positioning where it will not be blocked by the d5 -pawn, and as such the bishop pair is not that useful.} *

