1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {One of the key points here is that White no longer has Bg5 available.} 9. O-O Nc6 {Black essentially treats the position as if the trade of knights has already happened and develops according to what would be good with a pawn on d5 instead of a knight.} 10. Nxd5 {If clarifying the pawn structure in the center is White's best, then Black was definitely right to capture with the knight on the last move. This was played recently by Carlsen, but I think it makes it easier for us to get our priorities straight.} exd5 11. Nf4 {White immediately targets the d5 -pawn. This is the advantage of making the exchange early.} Re8 {I like this move. It's important to take the open file as soon as possible. It's actually a pawn sacrifice though if White is greedy.} 12. Qh5 {This is a double attack, but it turns out we're not too concerned about losing the d5 -pawn.} g6 13. Qxd5 Bd6 {White's queen is in a surprising amount of danger. Bxf4 is actually a threat to win a piece, while moving the knight will be met by Bxh2 + and a discovered attack on the d5 -queen.} 14. Bc4 {This is best. It both defends the queen and makes a threat on f7 .} Qe7 {Black protects f7 and has a threat of taking on f4 .} 15. Be3 {Normal development would be a huge mistake, as Black has trickery to win the game.} Bxf4 16. Bxf4 Be6 {The bishop on c4 is not feeling safe.} 17. Qb5 Nxd4 18. Qa4 {This was the only square for the queen to keep the protection of the bishop, but it turns out to be insufficient.} Bxc4 {We make the trade, as it's the other bishop that's in trouble.} 19. Qxc4 Qe4 {The bishop on f4 is in trouble, but moving it doesn't solve anything.} 20. Be3 Nf3+ {Check! The queen is lost next move.} *

