ucture in the center is White's best, then Black was definitely right to capture with the knight on the last move. This was played recently by Carlsen, but I think it makes it easier for us to get our priorities straight.} exd5 11. Nf4 {White immediately targets the d5 -pawn. This is the advantage of making the exchange early.} Re8 {I like this move. It's important to take the open file as soon as possible. It's actually a pawn sacrifice though if White is greedy.} 12. Qh5 {This is a double attack, but it turns out we're not too concerned about losing the d5 -pawn.} g6 13. Qxd5 Bd6 {White's queen is in a surprising amount of danger. Bxf4 is actually a threat to win a piece, while moving the knight will be met by Bxh2 + and a discovered attack on the d5 -queen.} 14. Bc4 {This is best. It both defends the queen and makes a threat on f7 .} Qe7 {Black protects f7 and has a threat of taking on f4 .} 15. Bb3 {White backs up the bishop to keep it protected.} Bf5 {Simple development is the way! Be4 may come next. Black has excellent compensation for a pawn.} *

