1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {One of the key points here is that White no longer has Bg5 available.} 9. O-O Nc6 {Black essentially treats the position as if the trade of knights has already happened and develops according to what would be good with a pawn on d5 instead of a knight.} 10. Nxd5 {If clarifying the pawn structure in the center is White's best, then Black was definitely right to capture with the knight on the last move. This was played recently by Carlsen, but I think it makes it easier for us to get our priorities straight.} exd5 11. Nf4 {White immediately targets the d5 -pawn. This is the advantage of making the exchange early.} Re8 {I like this move. It's important to take the open file as soon as possible. It's actually a pawn sacrifice though if White is greedy.} 12. Be3 {White first reinforces the d4 -pawn, and then they're ready to after Black's d5 -pawn.} Bd6 {We're often willing to give away our bishop for the f4 -knight to stop the pressure towards d5 .} 13. Qf3 {White ups the pressure on the d5 -pawn.} Nb4 {I like this move as it disrupts White's coordination. It also provides temporary protection for the d5 -pawn, which is very useful.} 14. Bb1 {The bishop had to avoid being captured, but now it's blocking in White's rook. That means White needs to spend time on a3 and Bd3 back to complete development. Fortunately we're able to put that time to good use.} Qh4 {We're increasing the pressure on the f4 -knight, getting ready for mass exchanges.} 15. g3 {Trying to chase away the queen doesn't help, as the queen trade happens anyway, just like in the main line.} Qg4 {The queen is helping in the protection of the d5 -pawn by exchanging off one of the pieces (White's queen) attacking it.} 16. Qxg4 Bxg4 17. a3 Bxf4 {If Black's knight retreated we would have lost the d5 -pawn. But we're willing to trade off the bishop to stop it.} 18. Bxf4 Nc6 19. Be3 Na5 {An important maneuver. The knight is headed for c4 , and White doesn't have the standard b3 -move available since we provoked a3 earlier. As the knight reaches c4 , Black can be happy with their position.} *

