1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {One of the key points here is that White no longer has Bg5 available.} 9. O-O Nc6 {Black essentially treats the position as if the trade of knights has already happened and develops according to what would be good with a pawn on d5 instead of a knight.} 10. Bc2 {White prepares for a queen and bishop battery down towards Black's king.} Bd6 {Always one of our main moves.} 11. Qd3 {Checkmate threat.} Qh4 {Counter checkmate threat! In addition it also covers White's checkmate and provokes weaknesses around White's king.} 12. g3 Qh5 {Black's queen helps out defensively while also contributing to a potential attack.} 13. Nxd5 {The time has come for White to admit there's nothing better than trading.} exd5 {Black's bishop is immediately ready to get involved. Potentially all the way to the h3 -square, thanks to the weaknesses we provoked.} 14. Bf4 {Since White has placed almost all the pawns on dark squares, it would be strategically beneficial to exchange off the bishop which is prone to be blocked by its own pawns.} Be7 {Conversely, we are not interested in such an exchange.} 15. Bd2 {By retreating the bishop White gets ready for Nf4 (again).} Qg6 {The trade takes the sting out of the Nf4 -threat.} 16. Qb3 {White goes after the d5 -pawn.} Qd6 {We simply protect the pawn.} 17. Bf4 Qd8 {What a weird maneuver from the queen! But during her adventure, she did make White trade knights on d5 , and has disrupted the coordination, as White would much rather have a knight instead of a bishop on f4 .} 18. Be3 {Reinforcing d4 , to enable Nf4 next.} Na5 {Chasing the queen away from b3 and its pressure towards b7 and d5 .} 19. Qd3 {Once again a checkmate threat.} g6 {We both prevent the mate and get ready for Bf5 to exchange off our "problem bishop". Black is doing fine.} *

