1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nge2 {Many of the sidelines involve White placing the knight on e2 instead of f3 . Earlier in the chapter we saw White doing it before developing the bishop. Logic would suggest that avoiding the bishop getting trapped inside on f1 by the knight is better, but in the meantime Black has gotten important pressure on the center with c5 , which we didn't see in the 5. Ne2 lines. It has its pros and cons, and means these lines are significantly different to the previous one, as the central battle starts much sooner.} cxd4 ({I like this capture, as it clarifies the central situation and eliminates some sidelines.} 6... d5 {is not so good in view of} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {When Black's capture on d4 comes too late, as doing so now will only help undouble White's pawns.}) 7. exd4 d5 {We're fighting for central control!} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {One of the key points here is that White no longer has Bg5 available.} 9. O-O Nc6 {Black essentially treats the position as if the trade of knights has already happened and develops according to what would be good with a pawn on d5 instead of a knight.} 10. a3 {This doesn't really make much sense to me, as White forces the bishop to the d6 -square, where we want it to go anyway. However, it was played in 2021 by Caruana, so it deserves our attention. In general, White's concept is to avoid the trade of knights on d5 , which will make it difficult to get the c8 -bishop into play.} Bd6 {As always this is where we want our bishop.} 11. Ne4 {Continuing the chase after Black's bishop. This is actually the most commonly played move.} Bc7 {I like keeping the bishop on the diagonal where it's pointing towards White's king.} 12. Bc2 {White answers with the very same move, getting ready for Qd3 to make some threats towards the kingside.} Qh4 {I like getting the queen out. In addition to the obvious threat of checkmate, Black gets ready for the rook to take over the d8 -position, where it will put pressure on White's central pawn.} 13. h3 h6 {This is move is necessary to prevent Bg5 .} 14. Qd3 {The queen and bishop working together looks intimidating, but we don't scare easily.} Rd8 {We don't need to defend h7 just yet!} 15. Nd2 {It turns out the knight didn't have any more aggressive options. The retreat does create a big threat on h7 , but now it's easy for Black to deal with.} Nf6 {We wanted this retreat anyway, as it opens up for the rook against d4 .} 16. Nf3 Qh5 {This was all played by a Nimzo legend, Artur Jussupow, back in 1997. Even with modern engines, I see no reason to divert from his play. Black has stopped the threats on the c2 - h7 -diagonal and is creating some threats of their own down the d-file.} *

