h sense to me, as White forces the bishop to the d6 -square, where we want it to go anyway. However, it was played in 2021 by Caruana, so it deserves our attention. In general, White's concept is to avoid the trade of knights on d5 , which will make it difficult to get the c8 -bishop into play.} Bd6 {As always this is where we want our bishop.} 11. Re1 {White is simply improving their positioning while avoiding the trade on d5 .} Qh4 {At the time of writing this has never been played before, but it has become a standard move for us in this opening, and I think it works okay here too.} 12. g3 {Stopping the checkmate while gaining time on Black's queen.} Qh5 13. Nxd5 {Lacking a better plan, White finally captures on d5 . This does gives the c8 -bishop breathing space though, especially since we already provoked light-squared weaknesses with our queen.} exd5 14. Bf4 {With all White's pawns on dark squares, White naturally wants to exchange off the 'bad' bishop. But even more important is getting the knight to f4 , which is why the d6 -bishop must be chased or exchanged away.} Bxf4 {Black has a very difficult choice. This trade leads to a position where White is very comfortable, but where it will be difficult to win. The advantage with this choice is that the queens get traded off immediately. I'll show some of Black's alternatives, but what they both have in common is that Black's queen could end up in trouble on h5 with White's knight trying to make its way to f4 .} 15. Nxf4 Qxd1 16. Raxd1 Bg4 {Getting developed with a threat is always nice.} 17. Rd2 {The rook must stay on the d-file to provide indirect protection of the d4 -pawn.} Rad8 {We use the corner rook because we may need to retreat our bishop all the way back.} 18. h4 {White tries to prevent g5 , but it's not possible in the long run.} h6 {The g5 -threat has been renewed.} 19. h5 {This does stop g5 , but there are other considerations in play too.} Nxd4 {Oops, wasn't this pawn supposed to be indirectly defended?} 20. Bh7+ {White gives away the bishop to recapture the knight, but the crucial difference is that there's no pawn on h7 anymore, so it doesn't win a pawn in the process.} Kxh7 21. Rxd4 Rfe8 {White will regain the pawn on d5 , but that will only be enough to retain material equality, not end a pawn up which was the case previously. Black is doing well with the bishop on an open board.} *

