h sense to me, as White forces the bishop to the d6 -square, where we want it to go anyway. However, it was played in 2021 by Caruana, so it deserves our attention. In general, White's concept is to avoid the trade of knights on d5 , which will make it difficult to get the c8 -bishop into play.} Bd6 {As always this is where we want our bishop.} 11. Re1 {White is simply improving their positioning while avoiding the trade on d5 .} Qh4 {At the time of writing this has never been played before, but it has become a standard move for us in this opening, and I think it works okay here too.} 12. g3 {Stopping the checkmate while gaining time on Black's queen.} Qh5 13. Nxd5 {Lacking a better plan, White finally captures on d5 . This does gives the c8 -bishop breathing space though, especially since we already provoked light-squared weaknesses with our queen.} exd5 14. Bf4 {With all White's pawns on dark squares, White naturally wants to exchange off the 'bad' bishop. But even more important is getting the knight to f4 , which is why the d6 -bishop must be chased or exchanged away.} Rd8 {Seeing as how we're allowing the bishop trade anyway, this makes sense to get the trades without letting White's pieces get better positions. The problem is} 15. Qd2 {When the queen trade is avoided, and Nf4 will be more powerful when it does come. Black can revert to avoiding the bishop trade...} Bf8 16. Bc7 {is a very tricky move, both attacking the rook and clearing the f4 -square for the knight.} Rd7 {is best to attack the bishop, but it also blocks the development of the c8 -bishop.} 17. Ba5 {The threat of Nf4 is so strong.} g5 {Black should do this to stop it. We arrive at a very complicated position with chances for both sides, but the lack of queenside development made me seek a more clear-cut solution in the immediate queen trade.} *

