1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. d5 {Pushing forward in the center in the standard reply if you face c5 in the first couple of moves of the game, but here Black is well-placed to deal with it.} b5 {This move tries to punish White for their sloppy development.} 7. dxe6 {This is the most common move, but I would go as far as to call it a mistake! Black can sacrifice a pawn to gain full control of the center. White needs to play extremely accurately to survive.} bxc4 {We're ready for d5 next.} 8. exf7+ {White keeps capturing -- what other choice does the poor pawn have?} Kh8 {This is an important move. The point is actually that the rook remains on f8 to protect the queen on d8 . So when black follows up with d5 next, there's no pin on the d5 -pawn down the d-file.} 9. Bxc4 d5 {Black has complete control in the center, and the bishop pointing in towards White's king is about to create some trouble.} 10. Bd3 {In a bad position it's easy to make bad moves. The bishop becomes vulnerable on d3 when we study the 'go for the throat'-line.} d4 11. a3 {Trying to kick the bishop away, but we're still pointing in towards the king.} Ba5 12. exd4 cxd4 {The knight on c3 is lost, so White has to get as much material back as possible.} 13. b4 dxc3 14. bxa5 {White has done a good job of staying two pawns up, but in the process the center opened up, and White's king is not very happy about that.} Rxf7 {Did I say White was two pawns up? Make that one. And white has great troubles getting the king to safety still, as development is met by Rd7 .} 15. Ne2 {Trying to get the king ready for castling, but it loses.} Rd7 {I did say the bishop on d3 would regret its positioning. Black wins the piece and the game.} *

