1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. d5 {Pushing forward in the center in the standard reply if you face c5 in the first couple of moves of the game, but here Black is well-placed to deal with it.} b5 {This move tries to punish White for their sloppy development.} 7. dxe6 {This is the most common move, but I would go as far as to call it a mistake! Black can sacrifice a pawn to gain full control of the center. White needs to play extremely accurately to survive.} bxc4 {We're ready for d5 next.} 8. exf7+ {White keeps capturing -- what other choice does the poor pawn have?} Kh8 {This is an important move. The point is actually that the rook remains on f8 to protect the queen on d8 . So when black follows up with d5 next, there's no pin on the d5 -pawn down the d-file.} 9. Bxc4 d5 {Black has complete control in the center, and the bishop pointing in towards White's king is about to create some trouble.} 10. Be2 {White leaves the d-file opened, making the d4 -break less effective. But we have other attacking resources too!} Ne4 {The knight joins the action!} 11. Bd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 d4 {The d4 -push strikes again. This time it's actually a sacrifice, because while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Bxc6 {Accepting the knight leads to problems.} Qf6 {Another sacrifice! The queen attacks both c3 and c6 .} 15. Bxa8 {White's policy of capturing everything has been consistent, but will be punished.} dxc3 {White loses their queen if they recapture the pawn, but Black gets a second queen if they don't. Resigning might be the best option.} *

