ecause while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Qf6 {Black continues the all-out attack. This move forces White to find some very difficult defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Bxc6 {White can try capturing the knight again. It's important to note this time there's a different method compared to last move for Black to capitalize.} dxc3 {The extra pawn exchange has made this capture extra good, because White will be unable to find any safe haven for their king.} 17. bxc3 Qxc6 18. cxb4 Qxg2 {Well, I guess castling kingside is out of the question for White now.} 19. Rg1 Qb7 {Castling queenside doesn't look very enticing -- yet it's actually White's best move! White's king will live in fear until the end. Black has amazing prospects despite being a pawn down.} *

