ecause while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Qf6 {Black continues the all-out attack. This move forces White to find some very difficult defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {White's greed is the only thing that can save them!} Nxd4 {A necessary sacrifice to keep the attack rolling.} 17. Bxa8 Ba6 {Black prevents castling and threatens Rxa8 as well as the surprising Ne2 !} 18. Be4 {This is the only saving move! White needs the bishop on d3 to exchange off some of Black's attacking pieces.} Ne2 {A cheeky knight move. In addition to attacking c3 it also eliminates the option of Rc1 by controlling that square as well.} 19. Bd3 {White manages to get the bishop ready to defend!} Nxc3 20. O-O {When White gets the king out of danger. Black can follow up with} Qd4 {to create problems for the d3 -bishop, but this is elegantly solved.} 21. bxc3 Bxc3 22. Qxc3 {A queen sacrifice to eliminate Black's pesky bishops!} Qxc3 23. Bxa6 {A bishop, pawn and rook is good compensation for a queen. If anyone is better I would say White, but a draw is by far the most likely result.} *

