ecause while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Qf6 {Black continues the all-out attack. This move forces White to find some very difficult defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {White's greed is the only thing that can save them!} Nxd4 {A necessary sacrifice to keep the attack rolling.} 17. Bxa8 Ba6 {Black prevents castling and threatens Rxa8 as well as the surprising Ne2 !} 18. Be4 {This is the only saving move! White needs the bishop on d3 to exchange off some of Black's attacking pieces.} Ne2 {A cheeky knight move. In addition to attacking c3 it also eliminates the option of Rc1 by controlling that square as well.} 19. Bd3 {White manages to get the bishop ready to defend!} Bxd3 {I think this is Black's most testing move.} 20. Qxd3 Nf4 {White's queen has a lot of threats to deal with. The g2 -pawn doesn't make it to the top of priorities, but that could be tricky for a human to understand.} 21. Qc4 {For some reason this is the only saving move. Which is a bit weird, as it leaves the g2 -pawn hanging with check.} Bxc3+ 22. Qxc3 Qe6+ {forces the king out in the open.} 23. Kf1 Qa6+ {There's a smothered mate brewing.} *

