ecause while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Qf6 {Black continues the all-out attack. This move forces White to find some very difficult defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {White's greed is the only thing that can save them!} Nxd4 {A necessary sacrifice to keep the attack rolling.} 17. Bxa8 Ba6 {Black prevents castling and threatens Rxa8 as well as the surprising Ne2 !} 18. Be4 {This is the only saving move! White needs the bishop on d3 to exchange off some of Black's attacking pieces.} Ne2 {A cheeky knight move. In addition to attacking c3 it also eliminates the option of Rc1 by controlling that square as well.} 19. Bd3 {White manages to get the bishop ready to defend!} Bxd3 {I think this is Black's most testing move.} 20. Qxd3 Nf4 {White's queen has a lot of threats to deal with. The g2 -pawn doesn't make it to the top of priorities, but that could be tricky for a human to understand.} 21. Qc4 {For some reason this is the only saving move. Which is a bit weird, as it leaves the g2 -pawn hanging with check.} Bxc3+ 22. bxc3 Nxg2+ 23. Ke2 {This makes logical sense, defending the f2 -pawn, but that pawn is a lost cause.} Rxf7 {A renewed threat on f2 means White must play defensive moves rather than getting the pieces into the game (at long last).} 24. Rhf1 Nf4+ {The king is about to be chased around the board.} 25. Kd1 Rd7+ 26. Kc1 Ne2+ 27. Qxe2 {Taking the knight this way is ill-advised as Black decides the game...} Qxc3+ {Checkmate is coming up.} *

