ecause while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Qf6 {Black continues the all-out attack. This move forces White to find some very difficult defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {White's greed is the only thing that can save them!} Nxd4 {A necessary sacrifice to keep the attack rolling.} 17. Bxa8 Ba6 {Black prevents castling and threatens Rxa8 as well as the surprising Ne2 !} 18. Be4 {This is the only saving move! White needs the bishop on d3 to exchange off some of Black's attacking pieces.} Ne2 {A cheeky knight move. In addition to attacking c3 it also eliminates the option of Rc1 by controlling that square as well.} 19. Bd3 {White manages to get the bishop ready to defend!} Bxd3 {I think this is Black's most testing move.} 20. Qxd3 Nf4 {White's queen has a lot of threats to deal with. The g2 -pawn doesn't make it to the top of priorities, but that could be tricky for a human to understand.} 21. Qc4 {For some reason this is the only saving move. Which is a bit weird, as it leaves the g2 -pawn hanging with check.} Bxc3+ 22. bxc3 Nxg2+ 23. Kd1 {Running away is the best defense.} Qxf2 24. Kc1 {Keep running away from Black's pieces!} Rb8 {A threat on b2 , but it's easily parried.} 25. Rb1 Qe3+ {The time has come to congratulate White on an amazing defensive effort. The number of tricky decisions have been astounding, and I'll be very surprised if anyone manages to get this far in practical play. But finally Black must take into account White's massive material advantage and go for a repetition.} 26. Kc2 Qf2+ {The white king isn't getting away, but it's not getting checkmated either. Draw.} *

