1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. d5 {Pushing forward in the center in the standard reply if you face c5 in the first couple of moves of the game, but here Black is well-placed to deal with it.} b5 {This move tries to punish White for their sloppy development.} 7. dxe6 {This is the most common move, but I would go as far as to call it a mistake! Black can sacrifice a pawn to gain full control of the center. White needs to play extremely accurately to survive.} bxc4 {We're ready for d5 next.} 8. exf7+ {White keeps capturing -- what other choice does the poor pawn have?} Kh8 {This is an important move. The point is actually that the rook remains on f8 to protect the queen on d8 . So when black follows up with d5 next, there's no pin on the d5 -pawn down the d-file.} 9. Bxc4 d5 {Black has complete control in the center, and the bishop pointing in towards White's king is about to create some trouble.} 10. Be2 {White leaves the d-file opened, making the d4 -break less effective. But we have other attacking resources too!} Ne4 {The knight joins the action!} 11. Bd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 d4 {The d4 -push strikes again. This time it's actually a sacrifice, because while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Bb7 {This is a worthy alternative -- maybe even objectively better. But also leads to an endgame rather than a massive attack, so it may not be everyone's style. My main problem with it is that it feels easier for White to find the right defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {White tries to exploit the f3 -bishop's pin on the c6 -knight, but there are other tactical motifs in the air as well.} Nxd4 {Black allows the trades which generally would be bad for the attacking side, but as we're about to see, White's king won't be happy at the end.} 17. Bxb7 Qe7+ {The double-attack takes out White's bishop AND forces the king to move. The only problem is that it leaves the knight alone in the center.} 18. Kf1 Qxb7 19. Qxd4 {White succeeds in trading off some of the most scary Black pieces and remains three pawns up. But somehow the position is winning for Black! What kind of witch craft is this? It's all about White's king and the kingside rook's inability to join the game.} Ba5 {A very accurate move. Black opens threats against b2 while the bishop is maneuvered to b6 where it will point down towards White's king. In addition it's just a matter of time before the f7 -pawn is captured, giving Black even more pressure on the kingside. I'm fascinated by this position, because to me it looks very unclear -- but the engines say Black is winning with correct play. What a difference active pieces make!} *

