ecause while it goes after White's knight, it also opens the diagonal down towards the rook in the corner.} 13. Bf3 {Trying to grab the rook is the only way to survive.} Nc6 {A shocker! Can't White just capture the knight?} 14. Nge2 {I feel like this is the kind of tricky move you can't find over the board -- you just have to know it. But if you knew this line, you'd never walk into it as White!} Bb7 {This is a worthy alternative -- maybe even objectively better. But also leads to an endgame rather than a massive attack, so it may not be everyone's style. My main problem with it is that it feels easier for White to find the right defensive moves.} 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Bxc6 {This exchange enables White to get rid of the d4 -pawn once and for all.} Bxc6 17. Qxd4 {The d4 -pawn has been eliminated! White breathes a sigh of relief, while Black surprisingly ventures into an endgame despite being three pawns down at this moment.} Qxd4 {Let's see how much damage the bishops can do on an open board.} 18. Nxd4 Bxg2 {That's one less pawn to worry about.} 19. Rg1 Bb7 20. O-O-O Rxf7 {Another one bites the dust. Black has great compensation for a pawn, thanks to the amazing bishop pair and the pressure down on the f2 -pawn. Is it enough to win the game? The engines actually prefer Black's position, but it's not a winning advantage yet. There's no doubt Black's position is easier to play though.} *

