1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. d5 {Pushing forward in the center in the standard reply if you face c5 in the first couple of moves of the game, but here Black is well-placed to deal with it.} exd5 {is also possible.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bxh7+ {This was White's point to avoid losing a pawn.} Kxh7 9. Qxd5 Bxc3+ {We want to break up White's pawn formation. The c4 -square becomes a major weakness in White's position now.} 10. bxc3 d6 11. Nf3 Kg8 {The king steps back to avoid potential danger with Qh5 and Ng5 . The plan moving forward is Nc6 , Be6 and f6 (to avoid Ng5 ) in that order. Black has a fine position and doesn't need to learn many lines at all. In my recommended line Black tries to go for an advantage, but it requires more study.} *

