1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. cxd5 {This is actually a pawn sacrifice -- a sacrifice I believe Black should not accept.} cxd4 {is the attempt to punish White.} 10. O-O dxe3 11. d6 {It is in fact White who looks to be the punishing party. Black's entire army remain in their barracks on the queenside, while there is a great deal of white pieces pointed toward the kingside, where Black's king resides.} exf2+ 12. Rxf2 Qc5 {Pinning the rook seems like a good idea to stop White's brewing attack, but it's not enough.} 13. Rb1 {The rook is headed for b5 , chasing back Black's queen and swooping over to the kingside.} Ng4 {This is the attempt to punish White's play, but even losing a rook won't stop White's attack from marching on.} 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. Rbb2 {Despite Black's significant material advantage, this position is terrifying and should be avoided.} *

