1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. cxd5 {This is actually a pawn sacrifice -- a sacrifice I believe Black should not accept.} exd5 {Simplicity! The bishop is ready to enter the game via g4 .} 10. Nd2 {By stepping away from f3 , White avoids the pin.} Bg4 {Pin or no pin, we still want to get our bishop into the game!} 11. f3 Bh5 {We're headed for g6 , to fight for control of e4 and trade off the bishops.} 12. O-O Re8 {First order of business: Put pressure on the e3 -pawn.} 13. Re1 Bg6 {Second order of business: Trade off White's bishop pair.} 14. Bxg6 hxg6 {As long as Black can prevent e4 , we have an excellent position.} 15. e4 {White tries, but Black is ready for it here.} cxd4 16. cxd4 Qc3 {It's a simple double attack.} 17. Nb3 {The knight protects both threats, but leaves the e4 -pawn undefended.} dxe4 {Black wins a pawn, and likely the game.} *

