1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. cxd5 {This is actually a pawn sacrifice -- a sacrifice I believe Black should not accept.} exd5 {Simplicity! The bishop is ready to enter the game via g4 .} 10. O-O {White's king gets out of the center, but at the same time this allows an annoying pin on White's knight.} Bg4 {White faces a tough decision. Do you move the queen, allowing Black to double the pawns and open up in front of White's king? Do you push the pawns forward in front of the king to kick Black's bishop out? Or do you retreat your own bishop to stop the pin?} 11. Be2 {This feels like a dreadfully passive move.} c4 {Closing down the center is a risky decision, as it lessens the pressure on d4 . If White can manage to play e4 in the future, they will have dominating pawns in the center. That's why we're only playing this after White's bishop left its post watching the e4 -square. On the plus side, White's bishop will be ineffective in the closed position.} 12. Nd2 {White is now all-in on managing to get the e4 -break in the center.} Bf5 {With the position closed down, we're not dependent on exchanging off White's bishop pair. It's more important to control the e4 -square.} 13. g4 {White needs to create threats immediately, before Black gets the e4 -break completely blocked with the rooks coming in to the e-file.} Bg6 14. f4 Bd3 {A brilliant concept! The bishop needed to get away, but we waited until White had committed their pawns further than what's advisable. A trade will open up the c-file, in addition to the d3 -pawn being incredibly difficult to capture despite surrounded by white pawns. Black has a massive positional advantage.} *

