1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. cxd5 {This is actually a pawn sacrifice -- a sacrifice I believe Black should not accept.} exd5 {Simplicity! The bishop is ready to enter the game via g4 .} 10. O-O {White's king gets out of the center, but at the same time this allows an annoying pin on White's knight.} Bg4 {White faces a tough decision. Do you move the queen, allowing Black to double the pawns and open up in front of White's king? Do you push the pawns forward in front of the king to kick Black's bishop out? Or do you retreat your own bishop to stop the pin?} 11. Qe1 {This is the right way to handle the situation for White. The queen gets out of the pin, judging the doubled pawns to be the lesser evil, and not without its advantages.} Bxf3 {The debate is on! Will the doubled pawns be good or bad?} 12. gxf3 Nc6 {Simply continuing development.} 13. Kh1 {One advantage of the doubled pawns is that White can use the g-file for a rook pointing down on Black's king.} Rfe8 {Rooks belong on (half-) open files!} 14. Rg1 g6 {This is a very solid defensive formation for Black. The g6 -pawn is protected by two pawns, creating a barricade White's rook will struggle to break through.} 15. Qf1 {The queen gets out of the e-file to avoid the pressure of Black's rook pointing down.} Na5 {If this knight can take White's bishop pair, that would be a massive success. The position is very imbalanced, but I like Black's chances.} *

