1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. Qc2 {White's most common move, but it's not especially good.} b6 {We would love to get the bishop out on a6 and maybe trade off White's bishop pair.} 10. O-O {This loses a pawn (at minimum).} dxc4 11. Bxc4 {The bishop will not feel safe on c4 , with the Black queen looking in its direction.} cxd4 12. cxd4 Ba6 {The double-pin secures material gain.} 13. Bd3 {The bishop had to retreat to avoid capture, but now there's a different piece in trouble.} Qxc2 14. Bxc2 Bxf1 {Black has a winning material advantage.} *

