1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. Qc2 {White's most common move, but it's not especially good.} b6 {We would love to get the bishop out on a6 and maybe trade off White's bishop pair.} 10. cxd5 {This capture is designed to take the sting out of both dxc4 and Ba6 , but it's met by a very surprising third plan.} c4 {Black aborts the Ba6 -idea and instead grabs a space advantage.} 11. Be2 {Retreating feels sensible, but Black's control of e4 is a major issue.} exd5 {If given time, Black has great squares for the pieces, so White should try to stake their claim immediately.} 12. Ne5 {In a dream world, the knight will work as the shield for White's upcoming pawn offensive.} Nc6 {Putting pressure on the knight immediately.} 13. f4 {This is a mistake, but a logical one. White tries to keep the knight's forward position, but it also creates a devastating weakness on the e4 -square.} Ne7 {The knight takes control of f5 , intending to get the bishop there.} 14. g4 {Allowing the bishop to f5 would be bad news, so White tries to create an attack while preventing Black's plan.} Ne4 {e4 is a nice placement for the knight, but this move is mostly about getting ready for f6 to kick White's only good piece back. When that's done, it's the right moment to start punishing White for their overly aggressive pawn pushes.} *

