1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. Qc2 {White's most common move, but it's not especially good.} b6 {We would love to get the bishop out on a6 and maybe trade off White's bishop pair.} 10. cxd5 {This capture is designed to take the sting out of both dxc4 and Ba6 , but it's met by a very surprising third plan.} c4 {Black aborts the Ba6 -idea and instead grabs a space advantage.} 11. d6 {White responds in kind with trickery! But Black is doing well after all the captures.} cxd3 12. dxc7 dxc2 13. cxb8=Q Rxb8 {It's time to sum up the sequence. Black lost a pawn on d5 , but won a pawn back when we captured White's promoted pawn on b8 . Black captured a bishop, while White captured a knight. So we're equal on material. However, the pawn on c2 would appear to be in tons of trouble, with so many white pieces surrounding it. So why is this still okay for Black? It's all about the light-squared control.} 14. Bb2 {White realizes the pawn on c2 isn't going anywhere, so instead they concentrate on preventing Black's plans: Initially by protecting the c3 -pawn we're going to target.} Bd7 {If the bishop gets to a4 , White won't even manage to get rid of the c2 -pawn.} 15. a4 {A necessary move to stop Ba4 .} Rfc8 {Black is ready for Ne4 next, to get the c3 -pawn.} 16. Ne5 {Putting pressure on Black's bishop, but more importantly getting ready to play f3 .} Be8 17. f3 {Ne4 has been prevented.} b5 {Seeing as how White has done a good job of preventing our main plans, we have to open another route of attack to make sure we have counterplay when the c2 -pawn is lost.} 18. Kd2 {There's no need for White to actively allow Black's rook into the game.} bxa4 {Yes, we give ourselves pretty useless doubled pawns on the a-file, but the key here is to open up for the rooks to secure counterplay. Black has good chances here, as capturing the pawn with Kxc2 is a mistake.} 19. Kxc2 {Despite preparing for over five moves, White is still not ready to capture.} Nd5 {Black attacks both e3 and c3 .} 20. Rhe1 Nxc3 {A simple trick to win a pawn and open up for the rooks.} 21. Bxc3 Rb3 {Turns out that a4 -pawn became useful after all. Black will get the piece back on c3 with a winning position.} *

