1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. Nd2 {The knight's protection of c4 stops the immediate danger posed by pawn captures in the center.} dxc4 {We take on c4 to make it more difficult for White to trade off the vulnerable pawns (and now pieces) along the c-file.} 10. Bxc4 {Taking with the bishop avoids moving the knight for a third time, but it doesn't control the important e5 -square.} e5 {It's time to strike in the center!} 11. Bb2 Nc6 {The pressure on d4 is significant, and White will have to move the d4 -pawn or allow trades which result in an isolated d4 -pawn.} 12. d5 {Moving forward is actually a mistake.} Na5 13. Ba2 c4 {White's bishops are not having a good time. One is blocked by the black pawn; the other by White's own pawn. White will have to go for e4 to protect d5 , but then the f5 -pawn break may be good some time in the future.} *

