. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 {White's pawn weakness on c3 is immediately attacked.} 14. Qc2 c4 {An amazing move! Black wants to strike quickly before White gets the bishop pair working together, and a pawn sacrifice is the way to do it.} 15. Bxc4 Bf5 {Suddenly White's development becomes a problem, while Black's rooks are ready. Getting rid of the c-pawn helped give the rooks targets down the c-file.} 16. Qe2 {The queen moves to protect the bishop and look towards the kingside. White hopes Black will capture on c3 , which would win the pawn back under very poor circumstances when White responds Bb2 . Instead we should just increase the pressure.} Rac8 17. Bb2 Ng4 {When the bishop moves left, our knight moves right. The checkmate threat on h2 forces White to weaken the light squares even more.} 18. g3 Qc5 {The queen moves to open up the e5 -square for the knight.} 19. Ba2 {Keeping the bishop pair has never been worse, as Black's bishop causes loads of trouble, and therefore should have been exchanged off with Bd3 instead.} Ne5 {There's a big threat on d3 .} 20. e4 {This is also a mistake, as it opens up for Black's queen on the c5 - g1 -diagonal. As a result, White won't be able to play f3 to protect the light squares.} Bg4 {Attacking the queen and getting ready for Nf3 +.} 21. Qe3 Nf3+ 22. Kg2 Qh5 {There's no chance we're exchanging queens. We're attacking!} 23. h4 Rc6 {The rook joins the attack. White won't survive much longer without big material losses.} *

