1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O {Castling is actually a waiting move of sorts. Black is undecided whether to go for c5 or d5 and wants to see how White plans to continue development -- and in particular where White places the g1 -knight. Putting pressure in the center with c5 is good against Bd3 , but not against Ne2 . So we castle and wait to see White's plan before we choose whether to strike first with c5 or with d5 in the center.} 5. Bd3 {White develops the bishop while keeping flexibility for the kingside knight -- will it go to e2 or will it go to f3 ?} c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. a3 {For once playing a3 leads to something other than a transposition! It differs from the lines studied in the 4. a3  chapter because Black has already committed to d5 .} Bxc3+ {We're not in the retreating business. The bishop pair is lost, but Black aims to exploit their superior development.} 8. bxc3 Qc7 {The queen eyes several white weaknesses on the c-file.} 9. Nd2 {The knight's protection of c4 stops the immediate danger posed by pawn captures in the center.} dxc4 {We take on c4 to make it more difficult for White to trade off the vulnerable pawns (and now pieces) along the c-file.} 10. Nxc4 {The knight moves again, but does an important job guarding against Black's e5 -pawn break.} Nc6 {Strengthening Black's control of e5 to enable the pawn push next move.} 11. O-O e5 {In a way it's illogical to open up the position when the opponent has the bishop pair, but we're also trying to highlight the weaknesses in White's pawn structure. White has to capture in the center to prevent being saddled with an isolated pawn on d4 , so that will also help in getting our queen to the powerful e5 -square.} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 {White's pawn weakness on c3 is immediately attacked.} 14. Qc2 c4 {An amazing move! Black wants to strike quickly before White gets the bishop pair working together, and a pawn sacrifice is the way to do it.} 15. Bxc4 Bf5 {Suddenly White's development becomes a problem, while Black's rooks are ready. Getting rid of the c-pawn helped give the rooks targets down the c-file.} 16. Bd3 {A very logical move, as it both gets the bishop off the c-file and offers to trade off Black's (currently) most annoying piece.} Ng4 {This is an important piece of the pawn sacrifice. Black is looking at the White c-pawn and White's kingside at the same time.} 17. g3 {This stops checkmate, but weakens the light squares around White's king. Which in conjunction with the pending exchange of light-squared bishops spells trouble.} Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Qh5 {Another checkmate threat.} 19. h4 {This was the only way to stop the checkmate, but it hasn't made White's king feel any safer.} Ne5 20. Qe4 {is a logical, centralizing move...} Rac8 {There's no good way of preventing Rc4 next, which will allow even more black pieces to join the attack.} *

