1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. dxc5 {This capture makes Black's life easy. We can go into an endgame where White will suffer due to a poor pawn structure.} dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bxc3+ {We'll do this trade voluntarily as White has given up hopes of a big center when they took on c5 .} 9. bxc3 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ne4 11. Ke1 {This is the best square, as it protects the f2 -pawn without allowing c3 to be captured with a check.} Bd7 ({There's no need for impatience with} 11... Nxc5 $6 {when after} 12. Ba3 {White gets uncomfortable pressure down the diagonal. The c5 -pawn isn't running anywhere, so we can take our time in recapturing it.}) 12. Ba3 Rc8 {Black will capture on c5 next and have good pressure down the c-file towards White's isolated pawn. Black is better.} *

