1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. Nxd4 {allows Black to get very easy play.} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 e5 {Forcing the knight back before we get her majesty involved.} 10. Nb3 Qxd5 11. O-O Rd8 12. Be2 Nc6 {Black has very nice development and a superior pawn structure in exchange for White's bishop pair.} *

