1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. O-O {Getting the king to safety comes at a cost: Black gets an extremely annoying pin...} Bg4 {There's three ways out of this for white. One: to play h3 and g4 , which massively hurts White's king safety. Two: Move the queen and allow a broken pawn structure in front of the king. Three: Move the bishop back to e2 to defend. I will not cover the third, as it's a passive move which allows Black to seize the initiative. But that leaves two options where White's king gets in trouble as the kingside pawns go crazy. We're in for an exciting game.} 10. Qb3 {Gets out of the pin, but there's still plenty of problems to deal with.} Bxc3 11. Qxb7 {Being greedy like this doesn't work out...} Ba5 12. Qxa8 Qb6 {when White's queen is in big trouble.} 13. Ne5 Qxd4 14. Nxg4 Nxg4 {Black gets a huge attack while White's queen is stuck in the corner.} 15. Bf5 Nxf2 16. Rxf2 Bb6 {and Black wins.} *

