1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. O-O {Getting the king to safety comes at a cost: Black gets an extremely annoying pin...} Bg4 {There's three ways out of this for white. One: to play h3 and g4 , which massively hurts White's king safety. Two: Move the queen and allow a broken pawn structure in front of the king. Three: Move the bishop back to e2 to defend. I will not cover the third, as it's a passive move which allows Black to seize the initiative. But that leaves two options where White's king gets in trouble as the kingside pawns go crazy. We're in for an exciting game.} 10. Qb3 {Gets out of the pin, but there's still plenty of problems to deal with.} Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 {This is the critical pawn structure for this line. It looks very broken for White, but there are advantages to it too -- The g-file is one such advantage, where White can place a rook and in cooperation with White's bishops point dangerously towards Black's king. In this version, White placed their queen away from an onslaught against Black's king, which makes it less dangerous.} Qd7 13. Kh1 Nc6 14. Rg1 g6 {I think this is Black's best defensive plan. It weakens the dark squares, but it's difficult for White to exploit that fact. In return we have a very solid point on g6 , defended by two pawns, which halts the intentions of White's g-file rook.} 15. Rb1 Na5 {This is actually a pawn sacrifice, but I think it's an excellent illustration of how Black can be willing to give up a pawn to eliminate White's bishop pair in this line.} 16. Qb5 Qxb5 17. Rxb5 b6 18. Bg5 {White gets the knight, which was the only defender of the d5 -pawn.} Kg7 19. Bxf6+ Kxf6 20. Rxd5 Rfd8 {Exchanging off White's most active piece.} 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 {This is a very interesting position. Black is down a pawn, but White's lack of dark-squared control makes the weakened pawn structure much more apparent (and easier for us to attack). Even if we don't manage to take any White pawns, we're likely to create a dark-squared blockade. The engines evaluate this as 0.0, despite Black being a pawn down.} *

