1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. O-O {Getting the king to safety comes at a cost: Black gets an extremely annoying pin...} Bg4 {There's three ways out of this for white. One: to play h3 and g4 , which massively hurts White's king safety. Two: Move the queen and allow a broken pawn structure in front of the king. Three: Move the bishop back to e2 to defend. I will not cover the third, as it's a passive move which allows Black to seize the initiative. But that leaves two options where White's king gets in trouble as the kingside pawns go crazy. We're in for an exciting game.} 10. Bg5 {Since Nbd7 is met by Nxd5 , Black has to give up the bishop before continuing development.} Bxc3 ({The natural} 10... Nbd7 $4 {doesn't work once White has castled because of} 11. Nxd5 {.}) 11. bxc3 Nbd7 {Black got the knights working well together: the knight on d7 defends its buddy on f6 , which in turn defends the d5 -pawn.} 12. Qb3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 {This is the critical pawn structure for this line. It looks very broken for White, but there are advantages to it too -- The g-file is one such advantage, where White can place a rook and in cooperation with White's bishops point dangerously towards Black's king. In this version, White placed their queen away from an onslaught against Black's king, which makes it less dangerous.} Rc8 14. Rae1 {In this version of the pawn structure White's best plan is to get the rooks quickly involved on the e-file.} h6 15. Bh4 Qb6 {Getting rid of the queens would remove any concern about Black's king safety. In addition we're trying to eliminate the defender of the c3 -pawn.} 16. Re3 Rfe8 {Fighting for control of the e-file, but it's also about freeing the f8 -square which Black's knight would like to use in its maneuvering.} ({Don't fall for} 16... Qxb3 $6 17. axb3 Rxc3 $4 {when White wins after} 18. Bh7+ {.}) 17. Rfe1 Rxe3 18. Rxe3 Qxb3 {Uniting White's pawns is odd, but plenty of pawn weaknesses for Black to put pressure on remains.} 19. axb3 Nf8 {Black intends Ne6 , and we're not afraid of getting our own pawn structure shattered with Bxf6  gxf6 because that would lose all dark-square control for White, including the very juicy f4 -square Black's knight is headed for.} 20. f4 (20. Bxf6 gxf6) 20... Nh5 {Threatens the f4 -pawn, and if it pushes forward with f5 Black is free to capture the c3 -pawn with Rxc3 since there's no Bh7 + tactics anymore.} 21. Bg3 (21. f5 Rxc3) 21... g6 {Taking control of the f5 -square, but just as importantly: Stopping any funny business with Bh7 +. Now Rxc3 is a threat.} 22. c4 dxc4 23. bxc4 Rd8 {We're provoking White's pawns forward, to give our knight good squares in their wake.} 24. d5 Nxg3 25. hxg3 Nd7 {Black's knight is about to land on c5 , from where it cannot be chased away. Suffering awaits White.} *

