1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. O-O {Getting the king to safety comes at a cost: Black gets an extremely annoying pin...} Bg4 {There's three ways out of this for white. One: to play h3 and g4 , which massively hurts White's king safety. Two: Move the queen and allow a broken pawn structure in front of the king. Three: Move the bishop back to e2 to defend. I will not cover the third, as it's a passive move which allows Black to seize the initiative. But that leaves two options where White's king gets in trouble as the kingside pawns go crazy. We're in for an exciting game.} 10. Bg5 {Since Nbd7 is met by Nxd5 , Black has to give up the bishop before continuing development.} Bxc3 ({The natural} 10... Nbd7 $4 {doesn't work once White has castled because of} 11. Nxd5 {.}) 11. bxc3 Nbd7 {Black got the knights working well together: the knight on d7 defends its buddy on f6 , which in turn defends the d5 -pawn.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. c4 {This has been the most popular plan for White the last decade. It opens up the board for White's bishops, but at the same time the d4 -pawn becomes an easy target for Black's pieces.} dxc4 14. Bxc4 h6 {An important move! We want White's bishop on h4 , for reasons that will become apparent.} 15. Bh4 Nb6 16. Bb3 a5 {Once again we're adding a useful move before executing our main plan.} 17. a4 {White would like to prevent a4 , pushing the bishop back.} ({It's important to be aware of} 17. g4 a4 $1 18. gxh5 $6 axb3 19. Qxb3 Nbd5 {when White won't brag about being a pawn up given the huge trouble around their king.}) 17... Bxf3 {Now is the right time!} 18. Qxf3 Qxd4 {This is why we wanted the bishop on h4 ! We capture a pawn in the center while attacking the bishop at the same time.} 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Qxb7 Rab8 {This is why we moved the a-pawn: White's queen can't capture it now.} 21. Qa6 Nd7 {Getting rid of that pesky white queen.} 22. Qxf6 Nxf6 {Black is good.} *

