1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. O-O {Getting the king to safety comes at a cost: Black gets an extremely annoying pin...} Bg4 {There's three ways out of this for white. One: to play h3 and g4 , which massively hurts White's king safety. Two: Move the queen and allow a broken pawn structure in front of the king. Three: Move the bishop back to e2 to defend. I will not cover the third, as it's a passive move which allows Black to seize the initiative. But that leaves two options where White's king gets in trouble as the kingside pawns go crazy. We're in for an exciting game.} 10. Bg5 {Since Nbd7 is met by Nxd5 , Black has to give up the bishop before continuing development.} Bxc3 ({The natural} 10... Nbd7 $4 {doesn't work once White has castled because of} 11. Nxd5 {.}) 11. bxc3 Nbd7 {Black got the knights working well together: the knight on d7 defends its buddy on f6 , which in turn defends the d5 -pawn.} 12. Qd2 {I think this is the best move, as it keeps white's queen involved with the kingside action. It's also historically the most common, although it hasn't been seen in a grandmaster game since the 90's.} Bxf3 13. gxf3 {This is the critical pawn structure for this line. It looks very broken for White, but there are advantages to it too -- The g-file is one such advantage, where White can place a rook and in cooperation with White's bishops point dangerously towards Black's king.} Qc7 {The best place for black's queen is d6 , where it looks towards the kingside and f4 -square at the same time. Unfortunately, she has to take a detour to get there.} (13... h6 $4 {must be avoided. White strikes with} 14. Bxh6 gxh6 $2 15. Qxh6 {with a winning attack. Kh1 and a rook to the g-file will checkmate Black's king.}) 14. Kh1 Nh5 15. Rg1 Qd6 16. Rg4 {White prepares to bring all the pieces into the attack by opening the g1 -square for the last rook.} g6 {I think this is Black's best defensive plan. It weakens the dark squares, but it's difficult for White to exploit that fact. In return we have a very solid point on g6 , defended by two pawns, which halts the intentions of White's g-file rooks.} 17. Rh4 {prepares Rxh5 to open files towards Black's king, so we retreat to keep the pawn structure intact.} Ng7 18. Bh6 {White's new threat is Bxg7 followed by a queen landing on h6 .} Qf6 {Thankfully we get the queen involved while simultaneously putting pressure on White's rook.} 19. Rh3 Rfe8 {Black continues as if nothing is happening, just improving the pieces. That is the correct strategy, as White struggles find any breakthrough and has some weirdly-placed pieces (in particular the rook on h3 ). Black should proceed with caution, but is objectively fine in a chaotic situation.} *

