1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. Ne5 {I think this knight lunge is critical. White wants to hinder black's development. Ne5 does that by preventing Bg4 for black.} Nc6 10. Nxc6 {I think inflicting Black with this backward c-pawn is generally the correct plan, but here black as an accurate method of equalizing.} bxc6 11. O-O Bxc3 {Black recreates the pawn symmetry at the cost of the bishop pair.} 12. bxc3 Qa5 {This is the key to Black's plan. We're looking at the c3 -pawn, but that's not our main priority. Taking the c-pawn would allow White to use the c-file to put pressure on black's c6 -pawn, while also getting the pieces into play quickly. Instead we want to play Ba6 next, exchanging off white's bishop pair.} 13. Re1 {moves the rook away from the a6 - f1 -diagonal, so that White has the option of avoiding the bishop exchange.} Ba6 14. Bf5 (14. Bc2 {is similar to the main line: Black doesn't take the c3 -pawn, and instead concentrates on getting control of the e-file.} Rfe8 15. Bf4 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Re8 {Black's control of the e-file guarantees a good game.}) 14... Rfe8 {We choose to ignore the c3 -pawn and instead focus on getting our pieces into play. Black's development advantage is going to guarantee us control of the open file.} 15. Bf4 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Re8 {Black's pieces have found great positions, all putting pressure on white.} 17. Be5 {The last hope of causing trouble, but black has an excellent response.} Ne4 18. f3 ({trying to kick the knight back would be excellent for white, if not for} 18. Bxe4 {Being greedy doesn't work out.} dxe4 19. Qxe4 $2 Qxc3 {What more can you ask from a move? Black captures a pawn on c3 , protects the c6 -pawn and creates the threat of f6 , exploiting the pin on the e-file.}) 18... Rxe5 19. fxe4 (19. dxe5 $4 {fails to} Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Nf2+ 21. Kg1 Nd3+ {winning white's queen.}) 19... Re8 20. e5 c5 {After an unorthodox series of exchanges white got an extra pawn in the center, but black's pressure against said center gives black an equal game.} *

