1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. Ne5 {I think this knight lunge is critical. White wants to hinder black's development. Ne5 does that by preventing Bg4 for black.} Nc6 10. Nxc6 {I think inflicting Black with this backward c-pawn is generally the correct plan, but here black as an accurate method of equalizing.} bxc6 11. O-O Bxc3 {Black recreates the pawn symmetry at the cost of the bishop pair.} 12. bxc3 Qa5 {This is the key to Black's plan. We're looking at the c3 -pawn, but that's not our main priority. Taking the c-pawn would allow White to use the c-file to put pressure on black's c6 -pawn, while also getting the pieces into play quickly. Instead we want to play Ba6 next, exchanging off white's bishop pair.} 13. Bg5 {has been White's main choice in practice.} Ne4 14. Be7 Re8 15. Bb4 Qd8 {It turns out the bishop isn't particularly well-placed on b4 . Yes, White managed to force the queen back, but now black has the pawn of a5 and Ba6 .} 16. f3 ({Trying to force the knight back is well met by} 16. Re1 {does nothing to stop black's idea. After} a5 17. Ba3 Ba6 {We will get the bishop exchange and an even position.}) 16... a5 {when tactics ensue.} 17. fxe4 axb4 18. exd5 bxc3 {Mass pawn exchanges in the center only increases the likelihood of a peaceful result.} 19. Rxf7 (19. Bxh7+ {results in an instant draw after} Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Qxf7+ Kh8 22. Qh5+ {.}) 19... Qxd5 {Avoiding the danger while sweeping up White's central pawns.} ({Avoid} 19... Kxf7 $4 20. Qh5+ Ke7 21. Re1+ {with a powerful attack for white.}) 20. Rf2 Ba6 {Black exchanges off the dangerous bishop pointing towards our king, with a likely draw.} *

