1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation and is the most traditional way to play against the Nimzo-Indian. White simply prepares quick development, getting ready to develop the bishop to d3 . An added benefit of this move is the option of going Ne2 next, which avoids doubling of the c-pawns.} O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {White captures on d5 early, anticipating that this will be the only opportunity to do so before Black plays dxc4 . The goal is to create an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. It's a pawn that cannot be guarded by other pawns and is therefore considered a liability.} cxd4 {By capturing on d4 we're preventing White from saddling us with the IQP.} 8. exd4 exd5 {Black goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. This line is surprisingly rare, but very solid.} ({We actually have an opportunity to give White an IQP after} 8... Nxd5 $6 {but in this instance white gets very quick development and has good chances to build a nice initiative. Especially with the accurate} 9. O-O {! when there's no reason to fear} Nxc3 $2 10. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 {because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {with a winning attack for White.}) 9. Ne5 {I think this knight lunge is critical. White wants to hinder black's development. Ne5 does that by preventing Bg4 for black.} Nc6 10. O-O {White gets the king to safety and delays the decision on whether to corrupt Black's pawn structure by taking on c6 .} Nxd4 {A very direct move, and I think a good one. It avoids positional trouble we could land in if we allowed Nxc6 from White next.} 11. Bxh7+ {This is White's justification for leaving the d4 -pawn unprotected. White wins back the pawn.} Nxh7 {We don't want to have the king out in the open, so the knight has to take back the piece.} 12. Qxd4 {The double attack on d5 and b4 means Black has to give back the bishop pair. White's main plan is to claim the isolated pawn on d5 is more of a weakness than a strength.} Bxc3 13. Qxc3 (13. bxc3 {creates a pawn weakness on c3 , which counteracts Black's problems with the d5 -pawn. The two weaknesses cancel each other out, and Black is fine after} Re8 {With a plan of Bf5 and Nf8 for getting the pieces into play.}) 13... d4 {Since we had to give up our bishop, we use the pawn to take control of important dark squares in the center.} 14. Qg3 {Aiming at Black's king is the best option.} Re8 15. Rd1 {This feels natural, taking aim at the d4 -pawn, but on the other hand it leaves the knight on e5 vulnerable, which Black can exploit.} Nf6 16. Bg5 {Allows exchange tactics from Black.} Ne4 17. Bxd8 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Rxd8 {My first instinct is that White looks better because the d-pawn a clear target, the engines reassures me that the pawn is very slippery and won't go down without a fight.} 19. Rac1 Be6 {Putting pressure on the a2 -pawn.} 20. b3 Rac8 {Stops White's intentions on the c-file, with an equal position.} *

