ates a pawn weakness on c3 , which counteracts Black's problems with the d5 -pawn. The two weaknesses cancel each other out, and Black is fine after} Re8 {With a plan of Bf5 and Nf8 for getting the pieces into play.}) 13... d4 {Since we had to give up our bishop, we use the pawn to take control of important dark squares in the center.} 14. Qg3 {Aiming at Black's king is the best option.} Re8 15. Rd1 {This feels natural, taking aim at the d4 -pawn, but on the other hand it leaves the knight on e5 vulnerable, which Black can exploit.} Nf6 16. Nf3 {Retreats the vulnerable knight while attacking the d4 -pawn.} Nh5 {Once again Black can start exchanges to relieve the pressure.} 17. Qh4 {Isn't as effective.} Qxh4 18. Nxh4 b6 19. h3 Ba6 {Saves Black's d-pawn.} 20. Rxd4 Re1+ {Greed is punished.} 21. Kh2 Rc8 {Winning the bishop.} *

