[PlyCount "20"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 {Previously black usually played 8... cxd4 here, which left White with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 .   However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move 8... Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.} 9. Bd3 {This seems weird, as it just moves the bishop back where it came from, but White is waiting for Black to capture on d4 , and chooses piece placements with that exchange in mind. However, White is not the only one who can play a waiting game. Black has a clever little move.} h6 {When we permanently prevent Bg5 in the future, while keeping our options open depending on White's response.} 10. a3 {Black doesn't want to give up the bishop and strengthen White's center.} Ba5 {Which is actually the same position we study in the mainline beginning with 9.a3 .} *

