1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 {Previously black usually played 8... cxd4 here, which left White with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 .   However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move 8... Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.} 9. dxc5 {Doesn't raise any concerns...} Bxc5 {Leads to a completely symmetrical position. White can try to exploit the extra move by expanding on the queenside, but Black also has nice plans for the future.} 10. Qc2 b6 {The black bishop will be excellent on b7 .} 11. a3 Bb7 12. b4 Bd6 13. Rd1 Qe7 {Black has coordinated the pieces to point toward White's king, and is ready to move the rooks in next. Black has a good game.} *

