1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 {Previously black usually played 8... cxd4 here, which left White with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 .   However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move 8... Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.} 9. Qe2 {is a logical try, getting ready for Rd1 . But it leaves the d4 -pawn undefended for a move, which Black can exploit.} cxd4 10. Rd1 {White is getting the pawn back in the center, but there's an amazing sequence giving Black an edge.} (10. exd4 $2 {just leaves Black a pawn up after} Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 {when Black's queen has plenty of squares available should White try to push it around, for instance.} 12. Rd1 Qg4 {and Black can be happy with the extra pawn.}) 10... Bxc3 {Unexpected, but good.} 11. bxc3 Nd5 {Because of the Nc3 -threat, White is forced to capture the knight.} 12. Bxd5 exd5 13. cxd4 (13. Nxd4 {Causes no problems for Black with the opposite-colored bishops.}) 13... Bg4 {The pin on the knight is extremely annoying for White, who is also left with a bishop blocked by its own pawns. Yes, in theory White's pawn structure is superior, with targets on b7 and d5 , but chances are that situation will change when dealing with Black's bishop (for instance if White feels forced to play h3 and g4 , massively weakening the king's position).} *

