1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 {Previously black usually played 8... cxd4 here, which left White with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 .   However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move 8... Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.} 9. a3 {This is the main line, asking the bishop to declare its intentions.} (9. Bd3 {This seems weird, as it just moves the bishop back where it came from, but white is waiting for Black to capture on d4 , and chooses piece placements with that exchange in mind. However, White is not the only one who can play a waiting game. Black has a clever little move in} h6 $1 {when we permanently prevent Bg5 in the future, while keeping our options open depending on White's response. After} 10. a3 {Black doesn't want to give up the bishop and strengthen White's center, so we go} Ba5 {which is actually the same position we study in the mainline beginning with 9. a3 .}) 9... Ba5 {We don't want to give away the bishop pair AND reinforce White's center, so we retreat.} 10. Qd3 {This is the most common move, as White tries to involve the rook while keeping the d4 -pawn protected.} a6 {Black wants to expand on the queenside. The big question to consider is whether the weakening of the dark squares can be punished by taking the pawn on c5 .} ({Ba2 moves the bishop away ahead of time, but it's likely to transpose to one of the other variations.} 10... b5 11. Rd1 {Transposes to the 11.Rd1-line , And} Ne4 {is analyzed in the 11.Ne4 line .}) 11. Ne4 {Tries to open up the e4 -square for White's queen. We continue our plan.} b5 12. Ba2 {is too passive and allows Black to seize the initiative.} c4 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Qe4 Bb7 {All Black's pieces are finding good squares, while White's bishops look lost on the edge.} 15. Bb1 g6 16. Ne5 {White intends Nd7 to c5 while simultaneously threatening the knight on c6 .} Nd8 {Preventing White's idea.} 17. Qc2 Qe7 {When Nd7 has been stopped, and Black can get the d8 -knight back into play next move.} *

