of the other variations.} 10... b5 11. Rd1 {Transposes to the 11.Rd1-line , And} Ne4 {is analyzed in the 11.Ne4 line .}) 11. Ne4 {Tries to open up the e4 -square for White's queen. We continue our plan.} b5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Qe4 {This is White's big idea, but Black is happy to get the pieces quickly into play, even if it costs a pawn.} Bb7 14. Bd3 {The mate threat on h7 enables White to gobble a pawn on c5 next.} g6 15. dxc5 Nb4 {This is Black's excellent counter.} 16. Qe5 {This clever tactic allows White to stay a pawn up, but Black gets a monster in the light-squared bishop.} (16. Qxb7 {allows Black to get a fantastic knight in the heart of White's position after} Nxd3 {when there's no way to defend the pawn as} 17. b4 $4 {allows} Qxa1 ({and c6 self-traps the queen after} 17... Nxc5 {.})) 16... Qxe5 17. Nxe5 Nxd3 18. Nxd3 Rfd8 19. Ne5 Bc7 20. Nf3 {After we're done kicking the knight around, it's time to start our constricting game.} e5 21. b4 f6 22. Bb2 Kf7 {Black is a pawn down, but even so I think Black is better. The pawns on e5 and f6 are doing a fantastic job of shutting White's knight and out of the game. Black will get the king to the center and then expand on the kingside. There's also the light-squared bishop which features unopposed on a fantastic diagonal.} *

