of the other variations.} 10... b5 11. Rd1 {Transposes to the 11.Rd1-line , And} Ne4 {is analyzed in the 11.Ne4 line .}) 11. Rd1 {is the natural follow-up, but it allows Black to take tons of space on the queenside.} b5 12. Ba2 c4 {Closing down the center is always a big decision, but we claim White's center pawns aren't that intimidating.} 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. e4 {It looks like a great situation for White, who has taken control in the center and opened up for the traditionally bad bishop on c1 -- but Black has a plan to create counterthreats.} Ne7 {Black threatens Bxc3 followed by capturing the e4 -pawn, so White needs to make a decision. Do you want to push the pawn forward, or protect it?} 15. Bb1 {To me this makes more sense, keeping the central pawns next to each other, controlling both dark squares and light squares.} (15. e5 {Pushing forward opens up the diagonal for Black's b7 -bishop, while also giving the knight a magnificent square on d5 . Black can be happy after} Nfd5 16. Ne4 Ng6 {when we have an unbalanced position with chances for both sides. The computer prefers Black though.}) 15... Ng6 {At first sight, I would think this is a good position for White. But investigating further, it turns out White is struggling to find good squares for the pieces. Yes, the center looks impressive, but White can't push the pawns further forward without leaving weaknesses. The rook on a1 is stuck in the corner for the foreseeable future, while Black's rooks are close to getting involved on the d-file. All in all, it's an exciting position where I would prefer to be Black.} *

