of the other variations.} 10... b5 11. Rd1 {Transposes to the 11.Rd1-line , And} Ne4 {is analyzed in the 11.Ne4 line .}) 11. dxc5 {This is the only way for White to stop black's queenside expansion, but it comes at a cost to the pawn structure.} Qxd3 12. Bxd3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 {The big question here is whether Black can get the pawn back safely. It requires some accuracy.} Na5 {This is the move with the best score for Black. The threat of Nb3 forking the a1 -rook and c5 -pawn forces White to act.} 14. Rb1 Rd8 {sees Black continuously making threats against White's loose pieces.} 15. Rd1 {gets the rook involved, but it's vulnerable to threats, such as Ba4 .} ({Make sure to avoid Ne4?? since White wins after} 15. Rb4 $1 {Nxc5 Bxh7+ Kxh7 Rxd8+-}) 15... Bd7 16. Bc2 {White stops Ba4 , but Black has other good squares for that bishop too.} Bc6 17. Rd4 {White is begging to get the pawn structure fixed, but there's no way Black is taking the rook on d4 . Instead, there's a brilliant tactic.} Be4 {Which eliminates white's bishop pair and secures the e4 -square for Black's knight.} 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 {White can't capture on e4 due to the back-rank mate, so there's no way to defend the pawn on c5 . Black is much better.} *

