1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 {Previously black usually played 8... cxd4 here, which left White with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 .   However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move 8... Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.} 9. a3 {This is the main line, asking the bishop to declare its intentions.} (9. Bd3 {This seems weird, as it just moves the bishop back where it came from, but white is waiting for Black to capture on d4 , and chooses piece placements with that exchange in mind. However, White is not the only one who can play a waiting game. Black has a clever little move in} h6 $1 {when we permanently prevent Bg5 in the future, while keeping our options open depending on White's response. After} 10. a3 {Black doesn't want to give up the bishop and strengthen White's center, so we go} Ba5 {which is actually the same position we study in the mainline beginning with 9. a3 .}) 9... Ba5 {We don't want to give away the bishop pair AND reinforce White's center, so we retreat.} 10. Qd3 {This is the most common move, as White tries to involve the rook while keeping the d4 -pawn protected.} a6 {Black wants to expand on the queenside. The big question to consider is whether the weakening of the dark squares can be punished by taking the pawn on c5 .} ({Ba2 moves the bishop away ahead of time, but it's likely to transpose to one of the other variations.} 10... b5 11. Rd1 {Transposes to the 11.Rd1-line , And} Ne4 {is analyzed in the 11.Ne4 line .}) 11. dxc5 {This is the only way for White to stop black's queenside expansion, but it comes at a cost to the pawn structure.} Qxd3 12. Bxd3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 {The big question here is whether Black can get the pawn back safely. It requires some accuracy.} Na5 {This is the move with the best score for Black. The threat of Nb3 forking the a1 -rook and c5 -pawn forces White to act.} 14. Bc2 {This is White's best bet, as the bishop has to move away from the vulnerable d3 -square sooner or later.} Bd7 15. e4 {Getting ready for Be3 to defend the pawn.} Rfc8 {We use the f-rook to avoid any scenario where two black rooks on c5 and f8 are caught on the diagonal by White's dark-squared bishop.} 16. Be3 Nc4 17. Bd4 {For the time being, White has managed to keep the pawn. It's very important to get it back, so Black keeps making threats.} Bc6 {Attacking the pawn, but just as importantly: Clearing the d7 -square for the knight.} 18. Rfe1 Nd7 {The threat of e5 to push back White's bishop keeps the position equal.} 19. Reb1 {Initiating very fancy tactics, but it peters out to a draw.} (19. Bb3 $5 Na5 20. Ba2 {stops Black from getting the e5 -move, but doesn't save the pawn after} Bb5 {.}) 19... e5 20. Rb4 exd4 21. Rxc4 {Miraculously, White has managed to stay a pawn up, but Black's next secures the draw.} d3 22. Bxd3 Bb5 23. Rd4 Nxc5 {The threat of a rook fork with Nb3 is much more scary than you would normally think.} 24. Bxb5 {Leads to exciting exchanges.} Nb3 25. Bd7 Rxc3 26. Rdd1 Nxa1 27. Rxa1 {Normally we would consider a knight and a bishop superior to a rook, but this is an exception due to White's awkwardly placed bishop on d7 and back-rank threats.} Rd8 28. Ba4 b5 29. Bd1 Rxa3 {This illustrates the kind of trouble white can land in.} *

