1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {White keeps the tension in the center, waiting to see how Black develops before making a decision on which pawn, if any, to take.} dxc4 {Taking away White's option of cxd5 and forcing White's bishop to move again is my recommendation.} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 {Previously black usually played 8... cxd4 here, which left White with an isolated queen's pawn, known as an IQP. Practice has shown that white gets interesting chances, often thanks to the c1 -bishop causing trouble after getting to g5 .   However, recently this line surged in popularity as people realized there's no need to make the pawn exchange in the center. By delaying the exchange, Black is making sure the bishop on c1 sits there without much of a future. I think our move 8... Nc6 is bound to become the modern mainline of this important battleground.} 9. a3 {This is the main line, asking the bishop to declare its intentions.} (9. Bd3 {This seems weird, as it just moves the bishop back where it came from, but white is waiting for Black to capture on d4 , and chooses piece placements with that exchange in mind. However, White is not the only one who can play a waiting game. Black has a clever little move in} h6 $1 {when we permanently prevent Bg5 in the future, while keeping our options open depending on White's response. After} 10. a3 {Black doesn't want to give up the bishop and strengthen White's center, so we go} Ba5 {which is actually the same position we study in the mainline beginning with 9. a3 .}) 9... Ba5 {We don't want to give away the bishop pair AND reinforce White's center, so we retreat.} 10. Bd3 {This was Caruana's choice when faced this line twice in May 2020.} h6 {An excellent move! In anticipation of playing cxd4 some time in the future, we take out any Bg5 -possibility. Once again White needs to find a constructive move without knowing whether Black will capture on d4 next or not.} 11. Bc2 {Has been White's top choice, but it's not clear to me what White is planning if black keeps the c1 -bishop imprisoned by avoiding the central pawn exchange.} Qe7 {Getting ready for Rd8 and more pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 12. Ne4 {Has been White's top choice...} Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Rd8 {Black is coordinating the forces well. White gets out of the d-file trouble...} 14. Qa4 {But ends up with a symmetrical and equal position...} Bb6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 {Black is fine.} *

