[PlyCount "28"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. Bg5 {White puts the bishop in an aggressive position, but leaves the c4 -pawn undefended. That's not usually a big problem in similar positions, but here Black is able to reinforce the c4 -pawn with b5 next, making it a proper gambit.} dxc4 {We accept the challenge!} {Taking the center with e4?? doesn't work on account of Qxd4-+ .} 6. a3 {White hopes to grab the bishop pair and then winning back the c4 -pawn, but we're not planning on cooperating with White's plan.} Ba5 {We're not interested in giving away our bishop just yet. As a matter of fact, the inclusion of a3 and Ba5 has greatly benefitted Black, as we're ready to go b5 next move, when White can't put pressure on the b5 -pawn with a4 , as that will run into b4 , forcing the c3 -knight away -- a move Black normally doesn't have available because the b4 -bishop would stand in the way.} 7. Qa4+ {White has to prevent b5 , even if that means moving the queen for a second time.} Nc6 {We block the check and defend our bishop. Now the d4 -pawn is under attack.} 8. e3 {With the d4 -pawn defended, White is ready to take the c4 -pawn next. It would seem Black has no way to keep it protected, but look at this:} Qd5 {The queen attacks the g5 -bishop while also taking control of the b5 -square.} 9. Bxf6 Bxc3+ (9... b5 $4 {immediately would be a big mistake on account of} 10. Qxa5 $1 Nxa5 11. Nxd5 {and White has an extra piece.}) 10. bxc3 b5 {We're not in a rush to take back the bishop on f6 ! First we're kicking White's queen back while simultaneously protecting our c4 -pawn.} 11. Qc2 gxf6 {Black got away from the complications with an extra pawn!} 12. Be2 Rb8 {As White is about to take control of the long h1 - a8 -diagonal, we're preemptively evacuating it.} 13. Bf3 Qd6 14. Ne2 f5 {Black has two doubled pawns, but more importantly there's eight black pawns on the board versus White's seven. Contrary to what's normal in these gambit lines, Black has good control in the center, so I believe Black is better.} *

