1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. Bg5 {White puts the bishop in an aggressive position, but leaves the c4 -pawn undefended. That's not usually a big problem in similar positions, but here Black is able to reinforce the c4 -pawn with b5 next, making it a proper gambit.} dxc4 {We accept the challenge!} {Taking the center with e4?? doesn't work on account of Qxd4-+ .} 6. e3 {White tries to regain the c4 -pawn immediately, while also protecting the d4 -pawn.} b5 {We're not giving the pawn back without a fight!} 7. a4 c6 {Everything stays protected.} 8. Bxf6 gxf6 ({It's important to accept the doubled pawns.} 8... Qxf6 $4 {would be a terrible mistake, as after} 9. axb5 cxb5 $2 10. Qe4 {the rook on a8 is trapped.}) 9. Be2 a6 {We're just solidifying our pawn structure to retain our extra pawn.} 10. Bf3 Ra7 {Black is moving the rook over to c7 , where it won't be bothered by pins in the a-file or on the diagonal. Black is up a pawn, with good central control and the bishop pair -- also known as an excellent position.} *

