1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. Bg5 {White puts the bishop in an aggressive position, but leaves the c4 -pawn undefended. That's not usually a big problem in similar positions, but here Black is able to reinforce the c4 -pawn with b5 next, making it a proper gambit.} dxc4 {We accept the challenge!} {Taking the center with e4?? doesn't work on account of Qxd4-+ .} 6. Nf3 {White aims to defend the d4 -pawn and then push in the center with e4 next.} Nbd7 (6... b5 {, holding on to the c4 -pawn, is certainly a viable move, but I prefer Nbd7 , as it prepares a central strike against White's e4 -plan.}) 7. e4 c5 {Instead of staying a pawn up by protecting the c4 -pawn, we annihilate White's once proud center and speed up our development. There's no need to fear e5 .} 8. dxc5 {is a more sensible approach.} Qa5 {Black is the one with early pressure on the center.} *

