1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. Nf3 {White is staying flexible -- not committing to either cxd5 or a3 just yet. The disadvantage of this strategy is that the pawn on c4 is unprotected, and I don't see any reason to let it live.} dxc4 {We're going to make an effort to keep this pawn, punishing White's nonchalance.} {Bg5 this transposes to the lines with 5.Bg5.} 6. e3 {White tries to regain the pawn as soon as possible. Spoiler alert: White will succeed in the end, but Black will achieve other advantages in the meantime.} b5 {White's first attempt at winning the c4 -pawn back has been denied.} 7. a4 c6 {For the time being, we're protecting our pawns easily.} 8. Bd2 {White unpins the knight, getting it ready to capture the b5 -pawn. We're going to have to give away our bishop.} Bxc3 9. Bxc3 {The pressure on b5 has been eliminated, but now there's a lot of weak dark squares.} a5 {We expand on the queenside and retake control of the dark squares.} 10. axb5 cxb5 {The trade has seemingly helped fix Black's pawn structure, but it's all part of White's plan of getting the pawn back.} 11. b3 {White's point: We can't protect both b5 and c4 . We will have to give the pawn back.} Bb7 {First we protect the rook, then we push the pawn forward.} ({Avoid} 11... b4 $4 {as White exploits the position of the rooks with} 12. Bxb4 {which hands White a big attack as Black can't castle anymore.}) 12. bxc4 b4 13. Bb2 {This is actually a very famous line from the Semi-Slav opening, but with one crucial difference: Usually White has the bishop on d3 instead of a queen on c2 . We can exploit that...} Be4 {Ruining White's coordination.} 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 a4 {When Black's pawns are dangerously far up the board. A very complicated struggle ensues, but one where Black has good chances.} *

