1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. Nf3 {White is staying flexible -- not committing to either cxd5 or a3 just yet. The disadvantage of this strategy is that the pawn on c4 is unprotected, and I don't see any reason to let it live.} dxc4 {We're going to make an effort to keep this pawn, punishing White's nonchalance.} {Bg5 this transposes to the lines with 5.Bg5.} 6. a3 {White is willing to give up hopes of getting the c4 -pawn, but wants the bishop pair in return.} Bxc3+ ({Retreating the bishop with} 6... Ba5 {will allow White to get the pawn back with} 7. Qa4+ {I'd rather try to hold on to the pawn.}) 7. bxc3 {White is ready to take full control in the center with e4 next, so we have to strike quickly.} (7. Qxc3 $6 {Has the benefit of attacking c4 , but that threat is easily dealt with by} b5 {when White has given up control of the e4 -square and missed out on a chance to strengthen central control by capturing with a pawn towards the center.}) 7... c5 {While White is busy trying to regain the c4 -pawn, we will use the time to put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 8. e3 {This does both protect the d4 -pawn and open an attack on the c4 -pawn, and White can get the pawn back. However, after} cxd4 9. cxd4 b5 10. a4 b4 {Black is happy to give back the c-pawn if it means getting an excellent queenside play.} 11. a5 {White stops ... a5 , but it's very time-consuming.} (11. Bxc4 $6 {is too cooperative, as Black is able to get a protected passed pawn on b4 after} a5 {Giving Black good long-term chances.}) 11... O-O 12. Bxc4 Ba6 {Black achieves the strategically beneficial trade of bishops, ridding White of the bishop pair. Afterwards it becomes a race for queenside control, and Black is doing well there, being the first to get a rook on the c -file.} *

