1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. a3 {Untraditionally for the Qc2 -Nimzo, White forces the exchange of bishop for knight at a moment when the pawn has to take back on c3 .} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 ({Not} 7. Qxc3 {as Black can immediately create trouble with} Ne4 8. Qc2 Qa5+ {.}) 7... b6 {I like this move as it prepares to get the light-squared bishops exchanged off after Ba6 .} 8. dxc5 Ba6 {A pawn sacrifice from Black to ensure the light-squared bishops are traded. And we even disrupt the king's castling rights in the process.} 9. cxb6 axb6 {It's important to take out White's pawn before it suddenly sits on b7 , trapping Black's rook.} 10. cxd5 Bxf1 11. Kxf1 Qxd5 {Black is down a pawn, but has well-placed pieces and good pressure for the rooks down the a- and c-files.} 12. c4 Qc5 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Nf3 Rc8 {Black is likely to win back the pawn, but we should be careful about going into an endgame where White might benefit from having their king in the center.} 15. Ke2 b5 {Regaining the pawn without committing to a queen exchange is the way to go. Black is fine.} *

