1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. Nf3 {Developing your pieces is rarely wrong, but we continue our strategy of pressure on White's center.} cxd4 7. exd4 O-O {By trading early on d4 we allow White to develop their bishop to an attacking position, but on the other hand the d4 -pawn can become a target for Black's pieces in the near future, in an isolated queen's pawn (IQP) position.   To avoid just being worse in the long-term, White plays very aggressively to justify the IQP.} 8. c5 {If White could establish an aggressive pawn chain on the queenside, this would be an excellent move -- but we can strike back before White consolidates their space advantage.} b6 {Trading away the c5 -pawn would be a massive concession, so White has to get rid of Black's bishop.} 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 bxc5 {We're giving White a big pawn majority on the queenside, while our pawns in the center look stuck -- or do they?} 11. dxc5 e5 {A brilliant move that gives Black an excellent position! Capturing on e5 would make White's king very unhappy, so White can't stop the further advance in the center, when Black takes over the dark squares with the pawns and uses the bishop to deal with the light squares. Perfect harmony!} *

