1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. Nf3 {Developing your pieces is rarely wrong, but we continue our strategy of pressure on White's center.} cxd4 7. exd4 O-O {By trading early on d4 we allow White to develop their bishop to an attacking position, but on the other hand the d4 -pawn can become a target for Black's pieces in the near future, in an isolated queen's pawn (IQP) position.   To avoid just being worse in the long-term, White plays very aggressively to justify the IQP.} 8. Bg5 {White neglects kingside development to put pressure on Black.} h6 {It's useful to insert h6 and Bh4 , because we might need to go g5 to push the bishop back at some point.} 9. Bh4 Nc6 10. Rd1 {This is a specialty of Mamedyarov. White keeps making useful moves, waiting for Black to capture on c4 so that the bishop can develop in one move. We don't want to be that cooperative, but that means taking some risks to kick White back.} g5 {This was Ding's move against Mamedyarov, and it requires a brave heart. Black's pieces become very powerful, but the king has to suffer the consequences. The question is whether we are in a position to give the king enough assistance, and I believe the answer is yes.} 11. Bg3 Ne4 {To resolve the pressure on White's position, Mamedyarov had prepared a piece sacrifice.} 12. Bd3 f5 13. O-O {White got the king to safety, but the bishop on g3 will be trapped.} Bxc3 {First we eliminate the pressure on the center, then trap the bishop.} 14. bxc3 f4 {The bishop is trapped, but in the process we've lost our grip on the center.} 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Qe7 {There's no rush to take the bishop -- it's not going anywhere. First we protect our king. Qg6 + can now be met by Qg7 .} 17. h4 {White simultaneously puts more pressure on the kingside, while forcing us to take the bishop before it runs away.} fxg3 {Taking the bishop is the critical test. But now the f-file is opened for White's rook too.} 18. hxg5 hxg5 19. fxg3 Bd7 {Black is about to get all the pieces involved in defence, while White struggles to find a clear way to infiltrate. Accurate defence has given Black good chances of winning.} *

