1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. dxc5 Ne4 {This is an extremely rare move, but I think it's a clever one. Black tries to create trouble for White's pawn structure.} ({If Black plays traditionally with} 6... Bxc5 {It's White who gets the advantage of the superior pawn structure after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White is ready to go Rd1 next and put pressure on Black's lone pawn in the center. Objectively it's okay for Black because of their active pieces, but I prefer to avoid such permanent pawn weaknesses.}) 7. cxd5 Qxd5 {Taking with the queen makes a crucial difference. With the bishop still on b4 , the pin on White's king remains, which means we can use the queen to recapture on d5 , thereby avoiding the isolated queen's pawn position.} 8. Nge2 Nc6 {Black calmly develops. The pawn on c5 isn't going anywhere.} 9. f3 Nxc3 10. Nxc3 Qxc5 {The pawn has been regained, with Black having nice, active pieces. It's equal.} *

