1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. dxc5 Ne4 {This is an extremely rare move, but I think it's a clever one. Black tries to create trouble for White's pawn structure.} ({If Black plays traditionally with} 6... Bxc5 {It's White who gets the advantage of the superior pawn structure after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White is ready to go Rd1 next and put pressure on Black's lone pawn in the center. Objectively it's okay for Black because of their active pieces, but I prefer to avoid such permanent pawn weaknesses.}) 7. Nge2 {White reinforces the c3 -knight, getting ready to kick Black's bishop back with a3 next. But we have a great trick:} Nc6 8. a3 Nxc5 {Brilliant! We take back the pawn, while simultaneously making the bishop poisoned.} 9. axb4 {Accepting Black's gift would be a grave mistake.} Nxb4 10. Qb1 Nbd3+ {White's king is forced out on the board.} 11. Kd2 Nxf2 12. Rg1 dxc4+ {Black has a winning attack.} *

