1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. dxc5 Ne4 {This is an extremely rare move, but I think it's a clever one. Black tries to create trouble for White's pawn structure.} ({If Black plays traditionally with} 6... Bxc5 {It's White who gets the advantage of the superior pawn structure after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White is ready to go Rd1 next and put pressure on Black's lone pawn in the center. Objectively it's okay for Black because of their active pieces, but I prefer to avoid such permanent pawn weaknesses.}) 7. Nge2 {White reinforces the c3 -knight, getting ready to kick Black's bishop back with a3 next. But we have a great trick:} Nc6 8. a3 Nxc5 {Brilliant! We take back the pawn, while simultaneously making the bishop poisoned.} 9. Nd4 {White is up to the task. The b4 -bishop is in jeopardy once again, and has to acquiesce to a trade. However, in this instance white is forced to take back with the queen, a piece which is very vulnerable to further probing from Black.} Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 O-O {Quick development is the way! This is effectively a pawn sacrifice, but one Black is happy to make to exploit the big advantage in development.} 11. Qc2 {White moves the queen yet again, but it's actually a clever prophylactic move aimed at taking the sting out of Black's Ne4 -plan.} a5 {A really good move. Black prevents white's b4 -expansion on the queenside while also taking control of the a6 -square with the rook. Why is that last part important you may ask?} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black is ready for Ba6 next, with excellent counterplay.} *

