1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. dxc5 Ne4 {This is an extremely rare move, but I think it's a clever one. Black tries to create trouble for White's pawn structure.} ({If Black plays traditionally with} 6... Bxc5 {It's White who gets the advantage of the superior pawn structure after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White is ready to go Rd1 next and put pressure on Black's lone pawn in the center. Objectively it's okay for Black because of their active pieces, but I prefer to avoid such permanent pawn weaknesses.}) 7. Nge2 {White reinforces the c3 -knight, getting ready to kick Black's bishop back with a3 next. But we have a great trick:} Nc6 8. a3 Nxc5 {Brilliant! We take back the pawn, while simultaneously making the bishop poisoned.} 9. Nd4 {White is up to the task. The b4 -bishop is in jeopardy once again, and has to acquiesce to a trade. However, in this instance white is forced to take back with the queen, a piece which is very vulnerable to further probing from Black.} Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 O-O {Quick development is the way! This is effectively a pawn sacrifice, but one Black is happy to make to exploit the big advantage in development.} 11. Nxc6 (11. cxd5 Ne4 {can only cause problems for White, as the position opens up with White's king still stuck in the center.}) 11... bxc6 12. cxd5 {White accepts the challenge!} Ne4 {Black has no patience for pawns. We're looking for attacking chances.} 13. Qxc6 {White is currently two pawns up, and the a8 -rook is under attack. And yet black can ignore it all and charge after White's king.} Qh4 14. Qc2 {White had to retreat to keep the king safe.} exd5 15. Bd3 Rb8 {Black is down a pawn. White also has the bishop pair, plus the superior pawn structure. So we must act quickly: The rook is transferred over to the kingside along the sixth rank.} 16. O-O Rb6 {White has to be very careful to stay alive.} 17. f3 Rh6 {White tries to chase away Black's attacking pieces, but it's not the time for retreat. On the contrary, it's time to strike!} 18. g3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Qxg3+ 20. Qg2 Qh4 {Black's attack is very scary. Plans include Bh3 and f5 (to intercept white's control of the g6 -square and let Black's rook use it to point down on White's king).} *

