1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. dxc5 Ne4 {This is an extremely rare move, but I think it's a clever one. Black tries to create trouble for White's pawn structure.} ({If Black plays traditionally with} 6... Bxc5 {It's White who gets the advantage of the superior pawn structure after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White is ready to go Rd1 next and put pressure on Black's lone pawn in the center. Objectively it's okay for Black because of their active pieces, but I prefer to avoid such permanent pawn weaknesses.}) 7. Nf3 {To me this is a shocking move, as it does nothing to address the threats Black have created against c3 -- yet it is White's best move. Sometimes you just have to get the pieces out quickly. It's based on an important trick though, to avoid doubled c-pawns.} (7. Bd2 {causes no troubles as Black gets a pleasant position with the bishop pair after} Nxd2 8. Qxd2 dxc4 {.}) 7... Nxc3 {Giving White doubled pawns was our main plan, so we follow through on the threat.} 8. a3 {White tries to chase the bishop away to allow Qxc3 next, but we're not that cooperative.} Ba5 {We trust we'll be able to regain the c5 -pawn in time. Right now it's more important to force a weakening of the pawn structure for White.} 9. bxc3 {White argues that the inclusion of a3 and Ba5 has made it more difficult for Black to regain the c5 -pawn.} (9. b4 {only helps Black, who gets a good position after} Ne4 10. cxd5 exd5 11. bxa5 Qxa5+ {We're winning a pawn on c5 .}) 9... O-O 10. cxd5 {White lures the queen out on the board, arguing that she will be prone to attacks from White's pieces.} Qxd5 11. Bd3 Qh5 {We protect the pawn on h7 while simultaneously getting the queen out of there. Next up we focus on getting the c5 -pawn.} 12. a4 Nd7 13. Ba3 Nxc5 {We've successfully regained the pawn, with an equal position.} *

