1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. e3 {White keeps the c4 -pawn protected while avoiding the forcing lines starting with cxd5 or a3 . It is not as innocent as it looks though.   In fact there are lots of tricky move orders to try to lure us away from our repertoire scheme, but I think the immediate strike in the center keeps us within our preferred setups.} c5 {Creating the early central tension is the best way to put pressure on White.} 6. dxc5 Ne4 {This is an extremely rare move, but I think it's a clever one. Black tries to create trouble for White's pawn structure.} ({If Black plays traditionally with} 6... Bxc5 {It's White who gets the advantage of the superior pawn structure after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {White is ready to go Rd1 next and put pressure on Black's lone pawn in the center. Objectively it's okay for Black because of their active pieces, but I prefer to avoid such permanent pawn weaknesses.}) 7. Nf3 {To me this is a shocking move, as it does nothing to address the threats Black have created against c3 -- yet it is White's best move. Sometimes you just have to get the pieces out quickly. It's based on an important trick though, to avoid doubled c-pawns.} (7. Bd2 {causes no troubles as Black gets a pleasant position with the bishop pair after} Nxd2 8. Qxd2 dxc4 {.}) 7... Nxc3 {Giving White doubled pawns was our main plan, so we follow through on the threat.} 8. Bd2 {A very clever way to keep the pawns next to each other! White wants to capture back on c3 with the bishop instead of the pawn, and the knight can't run away due to the b4 -bishop being unprotected behind.} Nxa2 {We can be clever in return! The knight would be lost anyway, so we give it in a way that starts a big fight about the b4 -square!   Without the a-pawn, White's ability to control b4 has become a big problem, and as a result the next couple of moves are pretty forced as White tries to regain queenside control.} 9. Rxa2 Bxd2+ {We're trading off the one white piece that was pointed towards b4 .} 10. Qxd2 (10. Nxd2 {gives up the fight for the b4 -square, and Black can claim a good position after} Nc6 {.}) 10... dxc4 {Oh, so your queen controls b4 , does she? We might have to do something about that. How about we have a trade on the d-file?} 11. Bxc4 Nc6 {There's no need for Black to initiate the trade, as that would allow White's king into the game too easily.} 12. Qc3 {By stepping out of the queen trade, White is now ready for b4 next.} Qf6 {Permission to play b4 denied. White can't avoid the trade anymore but claims to have accomplished something by doubling Black's pawns.} 13. Qxf6 gxf6 {Doubled pawns may not be the greatest, but at least these are helping control the center. In addition, Black hopes to use the g-file for a rook in the future.} 14. Kd2 {This is still the fight for the b4 -square. After the queen failed to help White's b-pawn forward, it's now the king who joins the party.} Ke7 15. Kc3 Bd7 {Black is simply developing. It's too early for White to go b4 now.} 16. Rha1 {White has managed to coordinate the pieces in a good way, and will get b4 next move. But White's pawn won't get further than b4 , because we go} (16. b4 $6 a5 $1 17. b5 $2 Nb4 18. Ra3 Rhc8 {when the c5 -pawn is surrounded.}) 16... a6 17. b4 Rac8 {When White's further advances on the queenside has been stopped, and the white rooks look silly as they're both pointed towards a pawn well-defended by another pawn.   There's no breaking through without allowing simplifications. I believe this position is equal. White's most dangerous plan is a maneuver of the knight to d6 , but by retreating the knight initially, White also allows Black to move their knight forward.} 18. Nd2 Ne5 19. Ne4 {This allows tactics for Black.} Nxc4 20. Kxc4 Bc6 {The bishop on c6 is a monster, both on offense and on defense.} 21. Nd6 {Black comes out on top...} Rcg8 22. g3 Bd5+ {Winning the exchange.} *

