ite piece that was pointed towards b4 .} 10. Qxd2 (10. Nxd2 {gives up the fight for the b4 -square, and Black can claim a good position after} Nc6 {.}) 10... dxc4 {Oh, so your queen controls b4 , does she? We might have to do something about that. How about we have a trade on the d-file?} 11. Bxc4 Nc6 {There's no need for Black to initiate the trade, as that would allow White's king into the game too easily.} 12. Qc3 {By stepping out of the queen trade, White is now ready for b4 next.} Qf6 {Permission to play b4 denied. White can't avoid the trade anymore but claims to have accomplished something by doubling Black's pawns.} 13. Qxf6 gxf6 {Doubled pawns may not be the greatest, but at least these are helping control the center. In addition, Black hopes to use the g-file for a rook in the future.} 14. Kd2 {This is still the fight for the b4 -square. After the queen failed to help White's b-pawn forward, it's now the king who joins the party.} Ke7 15. Kc3 Bd7 {Black is simply developing. It's too early for White to go b4 now.} 16. Rha1 {White has managed to coordinate the pieces in a good way, and will get b4 next move. But White's pawn won't get further than b4 , because we go} (16. b4 $6 a5 $1 17. b5 $2 Nb4 18. Ra3 Rhc8 {when the c5 -pawn is surrounded.}) 16... a6 17. b4 Rac8 {When White's further advances on the queenside has been stopped, and the white rooks look silly as they're both pointed towards a pawn well-defended by another pawn.   There's no breaking through without allowing simplifications. I believe this position is equal. White's most dangerous plan is a maneuver of the knight to d6 , but by retreating the knight initially, White also allows Black to move their knight forward.} 18. Nd2 Ne5 19. Be2 h5 {I think this is a very clever move. The point is to keep the knight in its great position on e5 , as} 20. Ne4 {White completes the knight invasion, but Black simply plays around it.} (20. f4 {can now be met with} Ng4 {when Black has good counterplay. If White instead tries h3 to prevent this Ng4 -plan, Black will be able to exert pressure on the g2 -pawn along the g-file -- a pawn that became more difficult to defend when White chose to push the h-pawn forward.}) 20... f5 {We're actively encouraging the knight in!} 21. Nd6 Rc7 {The b7 -pawn is defended (and may get more help from Rb8 if needed), and Black has a great knight in the center. The position is tense, but equal.} *

