1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. Nf3 {White calmly develops, but this doesn't cause any problems for Black as we try to regain the pawn on c5 with the queen.} Qa5+ ({With the knight on c6 , this check is now available because b4 will be met by ...Nxb4: b4??} 9... Nb4) 10. Nd2 {This move prevents Black's main plan of Qxc5 , but it allows black to continue moving the pieces into attacking positions. The position quickly becomes very dangerous for White.} Nd4 11. Qd3 {The queen is move exposed on d3 than d1 , but the threat on the d4 -knight gives White some extra time to figure out a defensive plan.} e5 {Protecting the knight and getting ready for Bf5 .} 12. b4 Qa4 {The threat of Nc2 means White still can't develop the kingside.} 13. Ra2 Nxd2 {After studying the alternative 13... Bf5 , I've concluded this is the most straightforward line for Black. The queen has to recapture to avoid getting hit by Bf5 next.} 14. Qxd2 a5 {Timing is everything and a5 is very well-timed here. We're trying to involve the a8 -rook without ever moving it.} 15. cxd5 (15. e3 {becomes the same thing as 15. cxd5 after} Nb3 16. Qc2 axb4 17. cxd5 {.}) 15... axb4 16. e3 {White gets rid of that annoying knight in the middle.} Nb3 {Just because we lost our central location doesn't mean we can't still create trouble. Once again White's queen has to move.} 17. Qc2 Nxc1 {Black eliminates White's bishop pair, removes the defender of the a3 -pawn and forces White's queen to move yet again -- all in one move.} 18. Qxc1 (18. Qxa4+ $2 {doesn't work for White because the rook is hanging on a2 in the line} Rxa4 19. Bb5+ $2 Ke7 20. Bxa4 Nxa2 {and Black has a piece up.}) 18... bxa3 19. Qc3 {This line is all about white's queen! It's her 9th move of 19 total, but once again it was necessary, as the king needed protection on the e1 - a5 -diagonal.} Qa5 {It has been a very exciting opening, but now it calms down as Black targets the c5 -pawn while White goes after the passer on a3 .} 20. Kd2 Bd7 21. Bd3 Ke7 {Both sides are preparing for an endgame -- that's why the kings belong in the center of the board.} 22. Rc1 Rhc8 {White can't keep hold of the c5 -pawn, but nor can Black hold on to a3 .} 23. Qxa5 Rxa5 24. e4 {Protecting d5 ahead of the exchanges.} Rcxc5 25. Rxc5 Rxc5 26. Rxa3 Kd6 {It's an equal position. White can't infiltrate with the rook in behind, as Black will always be ready to meet Ra8 with Rc8 , offering a rook trade. We shouldn't move the pawn away from b7 because moving forward will only make it more exposed.} *

