1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. Nf3 {White calmly develops, but this doesn't cause any problems for Black as we try to regain the pawn on c5 with the queen.} Qa5+ ({With the knight on c6 , this check is now available because b4 will be met by ...Nxb4: b4??} 9... Nb4) 10. Bd2 {White gets the pieces involved, but at the same time Black gets the pawn back as well as the bishop pair.} Qxc5 {The threat against the f2 -pawn means Black won the pawn back with continued threats.} 11. e3 Nxd2 {Taking out White's bishop pair before it can do any damage.} 12. Nxd2 dxc4 {We're ready to play a symmetrical position, as White is unable to put serious pressure on us.} 13. Nxc4 Ne5 {if given the opportunity, Black should exchange even more pieces. Because of the pin on the c-file, White is unable to avoid the exchange of knights, when there won't be any trickiness left in the position for White to claim an advantage.} 14. b4 Qc7 15. Rc1 Bd7 ({Avoid} 15... Nxc4 16. Bxc4 O-O {because of the awesome} 17. Qxh7+ $1 Kxh7 18. Bd3+ Kg8 19. Rxc7 {when White wins with the extra pawn and active rook.}) 16. Qb2 Rc8 {Creates important pressure against the c1 -rook and leaves white pondering to secure a draw.} *

