1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. Nf3 {White calmly develops, but this doesn't cause any problems for Black as we try to regain the pawn on c5 with the queen.} Qa5+ ({With the knight on c6 , this check is now available because b4 will be met by ...Nxb4: b4??} 9... Nb4) 10. Bd2 {White gets the pieces involved, but at the same time Black gets the pawn back as well as the bishop pair.} Qxc5 {The threat against the f2 -pawn means Black won the pawn back with continued threats.} 11. e3 Nxd2 {Taking out White's bishop pair before it can do any damage.} 12. Nxd2 dxc4 {We're ready to play a symmetrical position, as White is unable to put serious pressure on us.} 13. Bxc4 O-O (13... Ne5 $6 {doesn't work now because of} 14. Ne4 $1 {when White is the chief of tricks. For example} Qc6 $4 15. Bb5 $1 Qxb5 16. Nd6+ Ke7 17. Nxb5 {winning the queen.}) 14. b4 {White forces the Black's queen back to avoid any exchanges.} Qe7 15. Bd3 h6 16. Qc3 {White takes control of the e5 -square, making b5 a threat as Black's knight doesn't have any other good squares.} a6 {It feels counter-intuitive to place the pawns on the same colored square as your only remaining bishop, but securing the knight's placement on c6 takes precedence in this position.} 17. O-O Bd7 {Now it's all about getting the pieces out and about.} 18. Nc4 {White eyes the b6 -square -- an obvious drawback of the a6 -move. But we're not very bothered.} Rfd8 {Note which rook takes its place on the d-file. Black wants to be able to move the bishop back to e8 without blocking in the rook on f8 .} 19. Nb6 Rab8 {Yeah, white got the knight to b6 , but as the rook calmly moved away from the corner, there isn't actually anything to attack for the knight.} 20. Rfd1 Be8 {Black has organized the pieces superbly and is ready to double on the d-file with Rd6 and Rbd8 next.} *

