1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. e3 {Just like in the 9.Nf3 line, White prioritizes getting the pieces out, but Black gets the opportunity to bring the queen out and take back the c5 -pawn.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Nxd2 {Bye bishops!} 11. Qxd2 dxc4 {We're at a crossroads. White can exchange queens, but then the black knight will get involved and protect the c4 -pawn. Alternately White can go after the c4 -pawn immediately, but then Black is free to capture on c5 . Either way, Black is doing fine.} 12. Qxa5 {With the queen exchange White claims it will be easier for them to win c4 than it is for Black to recover c5 . That is actually true, but Black has some magical resources to create counterplay.} Nxa5 13. Rc1 b5 {This is the defense Black relies on, and it's brilliant!} 14. cxb6 {Once again the pawn on c4 is under attack, but we focus on counter threats.} Bb7 {The pressure on g2 prevents Bxc4 .} 15. Nf3 Ke7 16. Nd2 ({White is trying to be too clever.} 16. bxa7 {is better and transposes back to the line with 15.bxa7 .}) 16... axb6 {Black gets queenside play!} 17. Nxc4 Rhc8 {When the pressure on the queenside enables Black to win back the pawn win interest.} 18. Rc3 Nxc4 19. Bxc4 Ra4 {Black forces the bishop to move, thereby gaining entry for one of the rooks.} 20. Bb3 Rxc3 21. Bxa4 Rc1+ {The rook has invaded!} 22. Bd1 Bxg2 {The only good thing about White's position was being up a pawn. Not anymore.} 23. Rg1 Bf3 {All of White's pieces are struggling to deal with the bishop combining threats with the rook.} 24. Kd2 Rb1 25. Kc2 {White tries to chase the rook away.} Be4+ 26. Kc3 g5 {Despite material being equal, Black is winning because White's rook is stuck defending the bishop, while the bishop can't move without losing the rook. Black will just keep pushing pawns on the kingside while White sits and wait for their demise.} *

