1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. e3 {Just like in the 9.Nf3 line, White prioritizes getting the pieces out, but Black gets the opportunity to bring the queen out and take back the c5 -pawn.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Nxd2 {Bye bishops!} 11. Qxd2 dxc4 {We're at a crossroads. White can exchange queens, but then the black knight will get involved and protect the c4 -pawn. Alternately White can go after the c4 -pawn immediately, but then Black is free to capture on c5 . Either way, Black is doing fine.} 12. Qxa5 {With the queen exchange White claims it will be easier for them to win c4 than it is for Black to recover c5 . That is actually true, but Black has some magical resources to create counterplay.} Nxa5 13. Rc1 b5 {This is the defense Black relies on, and it's brilliant!} 14. cxb6 {Once again the pawn on c4 is under attack, but we focus on counter threats.} Bb7 {The pressure on g2 prevents Bxc4 .} 15. bxa7 {White keeps accepting the gifts, but rising from the ashes of Black's pawns there's now plenty of open files for the rooks to put pressure on white's queenside pawns.} Ke7 {The a7 -pawn isn't going anywhere, so we're getting the h8 -rook involved first.} 16. Ne2 {This was an attempt at reviving this line for white. The idea is to use the knight to blockade Black's queenside pressure. How, you ask? Watch this:} Rxa7 17. Nc3 {Where are you going, knight?} Rb8 {We got the rooks perfectly placed to pressure White's pawns on b2 and a3 .} 18. Na2 {Ah, the knight is headed for b4 , but it will be a short-lived station.} Be4 {The bishop is restricting the white rook. Why is that important? We're about to find out.} 19. Nb4 Rxb4 {A shocking sacrifice to open up the queenside with White's pieces still stuck on the other side!} 20. axb4 Nb3 21. Rd1 {it's amazing how such a natural move can be a huge mistake!} Bc2 {The rook is actually trapped.} 22. Be2 Ra2 {The rook isn't going anywhere, so Black goes after the b2 -pawn.} 23. O-O (23. Rd2 {doesn't change anything, as the rook is still trapped after} Rxb2 {Even though the material is equal, Black is actually winning! White is struggling to get the pieces out.}) 23... Bxd1 24. Rxd1 (24. Bxd1 {avoids the immediate trickery, but after} Rxb2 {there is no way to stop the c-pawn long-term. Black is winning.}) 24... c3 {the c-pawn goes from being the problem of this line to being the hero! It will become a queen if White doesn't capture it...} 25. bxc3 Rxe2 {Black wins with the extra knight.} *

