[White "13) 4.Qc2 / 5.a3 Sidelines"]
[Black "4.Qc2 / 5.a3 Sidelines: 8.dxc, 9.e3 #6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E37"]
[PlyCount "48"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. e3 {Just like in the 9.Nf3 line, White prioritizes getting the pieces out, but Black gets the opportunity to bring the queen out and take back the c5 -pawn.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Nxd2 {Bye bishops!} 11. Qxd2 dxc4 {We're at a crossroads. White can exchange queens, but then the black knight will get involved and protect the c4 -pawn. Alternately White can go after the c4 -pawn immediately, but then Black is free to capture on c5 . Either way, Black is doing fine.} 12. Qxa5 {With the queen exchange White claims it will be easier for them to win c4 than it is for Black to recover c5 . That is actually true, but Black has some magical resources to create counterplay.} Nxa5 13. Rc1 b5 {This is the defense Black relies on, and it's brilliant!} 14. cxb6 {Once again the pawn on c4 is under attack, but we focus on counter threats.} Bb7 {The pressure on g2 prevents Bxc4 .} 15. bxa7 {White keeps accepting the gifts, but rising from the ashes of Black's pawns there's now plenty of open files for the rooks to put pressure on white's queenside pawns.} Ke7 {The a7 -pawn isn't going anywhere, so we're getting the h8 -rook involved first.} 16. Nf3 {The knight is headed for d2 to attack the pawn on c4 .} Bxf3 {Permission to attack the c4 -pawn denied. It also helps Black attack the b2 -pawn since the bishop won't be in the way now.} 17. gxf3 Rxa7 18. Rg1 {For once the kingside rook is not a problem for White in this line.} Rb8 {Black can't spend time on defending the g7 -pawn. Instead it's important to start the counter-attack.} 19. Rc2 {White stops the invasion on b2  (temporarily).} Rab7 20. Rg5 {This is White's trickiest try, but Black has tactics.} Rxb2 {Giving up the knight to get access to White's king!} 21. Rxb2 Rxb2 22. Rxa5 Rb1+ {It turns out White's king needs to defend the bishop, but then Black gets a repetition.} 23. Ke2 Rb2+ 24. Kd1 Rb1+ {White can't get away from the checks without losing the bishop. It's a draw.} *

