1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. e3 {Just like in the 9.Nf3 line, White prioritizes getting the pieces out, but Black gets the opportunity to bring the queen out and take back the c5 -pawn.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Nxd2 {Bye bishops!} 11. Qxd2 dxc4 {We're at a crossroads. White can exchange queens, but then the black knight will get involved and protect the c4 -pawn. Alternately White can go after the c4 -pawn immediately, but then Black is free to capture on c5 . Either way, Black is doing fine.} 12. Rc1 {This is an unusual move, trying to get the rook involved early on.} Qxc5 13. Rxc4 Qa5 {there's no need to fear the endgame, even though White will be first to double on the c-file.} 14. Nf3 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Ke7 {We're keeping the king in the center, and then moving the rooks to the middle.} 16. Bd3 Bd7 17. Rhc1 Rhd8 18. Ke2 {The king gets out of Black's rook's scope on the d-file.} h6 {With a bishop on light squares we place the pawns on dark squares. Who said chess was difficult?} 19. g4 f6 20. h4 Rac8 {Black has all the pieces involved with a nice position.} *

