1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. e3 ({This leads to tremendously complicated positions. By playing e3 instead of Nf3 , White discourages Qf6 because it can be met by} 10. f3 {when Black has to go} Qh4+ {moving the queen for a second time in a row. After some flashy tactics} 11. g3 Nxg3 {Qf2 Nf5 Qxh4 Nxh4∞ the resulting position is an interesting endgame with chances for both sides, but where I favor White because of the bishop pair and Black's isolated d5 -pawn.}) 10... O-O {We opt to go for quick development to create an early attack.} 11. b4 {One of the key reasons black often plays Qf6 in these lines is to prevent b4 . In this instance, however, Black is able to put immediate pressure on White's position with Bf5 , eyeing white's queen.} Bf5 12. Qb2 {Gets out of the dangerous diagonal.} a5 13. b5 {The only way to keep the position closed, when Black moves the knight away...} Ne7 {The c5 -pawn is left exposed -- in fact there's no way to save it.} 14. Qd4 {Protects c5 and prepares Bb2 , but both can be stopped.} Be6 {when there's no way to prevent Nf5 next, pushing the queen away from the c5 -pawn's defense. Black will regain the pawn while still making threats on White's position thanks to the superior development.} *

