1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. e3 ({This leads to tremendously complicated positions. By playing e3 instead of Nf3 , White discourages Qf6 because it can be met by} 10. f3 {when Black has to go} Qh4+ {moving the queen for a second time in a row. After some flashy tactics} 11. g3 Nxg3 {Qf2 Nf5 Qxh4 Nxh4∞ the resulting position is an interesting endgame with chances for both sides, but where I favor White because of the bishop pair and Black's isolated d5 -pawn.}) 10... O-O {We opt to go for quick development to create an early attack.} 11. b4 {One of the key reasons black often plays Qf6 in these lines is to prevent b4 . In this instance, however, Black is able to put immediate pressure on White's position with Bf5 , eyeing white's queen.} Bf5 12. Bd3 {The bishop intervenes on the white Queen's behalf, but developing the bishop has left the g2 -pawn undefended, which Black can immediately exploit.} Qg5 13. f4 {Forces the queen to move again while also preventing Black's annoying Ne5 -plan. However, it seriously weakens the e4 -square and opens up white's king to an attack.} Qh4+ 14. Kf1 ({Since} 14. g3 {is met by} Nxg3 {with trouble, White has to abandon any castling plans and leave the king vulnerable in the center.}) 14... a5 {Even with a pawn down Black has a great position. Now it's all about opening up a file for the rooks to participate.} ({Black should avoid greed with} 14... Ng3+ {because white gets a decent play for the rook after} 15. hxg3 Bxd3+ 16. Qxd3 Qxh1 17. Bb2 {Black is better, but White's pawns will be difficult to break down.}) 15. b5 {White desperately tried to keep the queenside shut, but in doing so created a new target on c5 .} Ne7 16. Bb2 Rac8 {Black's rook is knocking on the front door; also known as the c5 -pawn. It's imperative White keeps the rook out.} 17. Bd4 Qg4 {This is the key move -- a silent killer! Black gives extra protection to the f5 -bishop, which will enable tactics starting with Nxc5 next move.} 18. Bxe4 {keeps the extra pawn for White, but completely gives up the light squares.} Bxe4 19. Qe2 Qg6 20. Rd1 Nf5 {Black's attack is still going strong.} *

