1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. e3 ({This leads to tremendously complicated positions. By playing e3 instead of Nf3 , White discourages Qf6 because it can be met by} 10. f3 {when Black has to go} Qh4+ {moving the queen for a second time in a row. After some flashy tactics} 11. g3 Nxg3 {Qf2 Nf5 Qxh4 Nxh4∞ the resulting position is an interesting endgame with chances for both sides, but where I favor White because of the bishop pair and Black's isolated d5 -pawn.}) 10... O-O {We opt to go for quick development to create an early attack.} 11. Nf3 {Having ignored development up to this point, White finally gets the pieces out. It's not a moment too soon.} Bf5 {Black aims at White's queen.} 12. Bd3 {White is up a pawn and now ready to castle. Black needs to strike.} Qa5+ {This is the key to Black's play. White's coordination is disrupted.} 13. b4 {Giving up a rook for a knight is a common theme in this line -- both on the kingside and like now on the queenside. In return Black's queen gets displaced in the corner and White can target Black's central pieces. Most of the time Black can avoid this sacrifice, but faced with b4 , we have no choice but to accept. The positive though is that White gives up an additional pawn to make the trade happen (as opposed to Black just moving the knight to the unoccupied b4 -square next).} Nxb4 14. axb4 Qxa1 15. O-O {Allows the black queen to get back.} Qf6 16. Nd4 Bg6 {Black has managed to keep all the pieces protected and get the queen out of danger, while still being up the exchange.} 17. f4 {Intending to trap the bishop with f5 next.} Bf5 {The bishop returns to its previous square immediately, blocking White's f-pawn from advancing. The initial retreat was caused by white's option of f3 , but since that's no longer on the agenda, Black's bishop can step back where it came from.} *

