1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. e3 ({This leads to tremendously complicated positions. By playing e3 instead of Nf3 , White discourages Qf6 because it can be met by} 10. f3 {when Black has to go} Qh4+ {moving the queen for a second time in a row. After some flashy tactics} 11. g3 Nxg3 {Qf2 Nf5 Qxh4 Nxh4∞ the resulting position is an interesting endgame with chances for both sides, but where I favor White because of the bishop pair and Black's isolated d5 -pawn.}) 10... O-O {We opt to go for quick development to create an early attack.} 11. Nf3 {Having ignored development up to this point, White finally gets the pieces out. It's not a moment too soon.} Bf5 {Black aims at White's queen.} 12. Bd3 {White is up a pawn and now ready to castle. Black needs to strike.} Qa5+ {This is the key to Black's play. White's coordination is disrupted.} 13. Nd2 {This is by far White's safest option, but with little risk comes little reward. Black can get an equal game.} Rad8 {I think this is an accurate moveorder. Black gets ready to push d4 in the future.} 14. O-O {White finally gets the king to safety, but Black regains the pawn.} Nxd2 15. Bxd2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qxc5 {Black got the pawn back, but now there's a new situation on the board: The isolated d-pawn can become a target, so Black will try to exchange it off. White can try to prevent that plan, or allow it to happen, only to claim that the bishop will be better than the knight in the resulting position.} 17. Rac1 Qb6 18. f4 {This is a very interesting plan, used by Alexander Grischuk against Magnus Carlsen. The idea is to prevent d4 by taking control of the e5 -square. Why is that important?} ({d4 White will play} 18. e4 {when the d4 -pawn stands in the way of Black's rook, knight AND queen. All those problems would be solved by Ne5 , pushing the queen away from the blockading square on d3 , but that's why Grischuk pre-emptively played f4 .}) 18... Rfe8 19. b4 a6 {With White putting all the pawns on dark squares, we choose to go for a light-square strategy.} 20. Rc5 Ne7 21. a4 Qe6 {We're about to get the knight to a perfect spot on f5 , while simultaneously keeping everything protected -- precisely the coordination we're looking for.} 22. b5 Nf5 {Black has a good setup.} *

