1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. e3 ({This leads to tremendously complicated positions. By playing e3 instead of Nf3 , White discourages Qf6 because it can be met by} 10. f3 {when Black has to go} Qh4+ {moving the queen for a second time in a row. After some flashy tactics} 11. g3 Nxg3 {Qf2 Nf5 Qxh4 Nxh4∞ the resulting position is an interesting endgame with chances for both sides, but where I favor White because of the bishop pair and Black's isolated d5 -pawn.}) 10... O-O {We opt to go for quick development to create an early attack.} 11. Nf3 {Having ignored development up to this point, White finally gets the pieces out. It's not a moment too soon.} Bf5 {Black aims at White's queen.} 12. Bd3 {White is up a pawn and now ready to castle. Black needs to strike.} Qa5+ {This is the key to Black's play. White's coordination is disrupted.} 13. Nd2 {This is by far White's safest option, but with little risk comes little reward. Black can get an equal game.} Rad8 {I think this is an accurate moveorder. Black gets ready to push d4 in the future.} 14. O-O {White finally gets the king to safety, but Black regains the pawn.} Nxd2 15. Bxd2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qxc5 {Black got the pawn back, but now there's a new situation on the board: The isolated d-pawn can become a target, so Black will try to exchange it off. White can try to prevent that plan, or allow it to happen, only to claim that the bishop will be better than the knight in the resulting position.} 17. Bc3 {White walks straight into the d4 -move, but claims that the bishop will be valueable pointing towards the black king.} d4 18. exd4 Nxd4 19. Rad1 Ne6 {It's seemingly a completely symmetrical and equal position, but I must warn you -- White's tiny initiative can grow very strong if not handled with care.} 20. Qe4 Qc7 {Our plan is simply to play b6 and then exchange off as many rooks as possible.} 21. Rc1 {White tries to keep all rooks on the board, but at the same time this gives up the d-file.} Qd7 22. Rce1 {this seems strange, but with the queen on d7 Black no longer has the option of Qf4 later to exchange queens. It's important to be aware of this Re1 - e3 -plan, as it's the only way White can hope for a win: The rook is headed to g3 where it points towards Black's king, and then White will push the f-pawn forward to chase Black's excellent defensive knight away from e6 .} b6 23. Re3 Nc5 {We're moving the knight away from its excellent position to free the f7 -pawn from its protecting e6 -duty.} 24. Qh4 f6 {when White's bishop has been successfully neutralized without losing control of the center. Black has a good game.} *

