1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. e3 ({This leads to tremendously complicated positions. By playing e3 instead of Nf3 , White discourages Qf6 because it can be met by} 10. f3 {when Black has to go} Qh4+ {moving the queen for a second time in a row. After some flashy tactics} 11. g3 Nxg3 {Qf2 Nf5 Qxh4 Nxh4∞ the resulting position is an interesting endgame with chances for both sides, but where I favor White because of the bishop pair and Black's isolated d5 -pawn.}) 10... O-O {We opt to go for quick development to create an early attack.} 11. Nf3 {Having ignored development up to this point, White finally gets the pieces out. It's not a moment too soon.} Bf5 {Black aims at White's queen.} 12. Bd3 {White is up a pawn and now ready to castle. Black needs to strike.} Qa5+ {This is the key to Black's play. White's coordination is disrupted.} 13. Ke2 {Wow! White really wants to keep hold of that extra pawn, even if the king gets stuck in the center.} (13. Bd2 $4 {is simply a blunder. Black wins after} Nxd2 14. Nxd2 (14. Bxf5 Nxf3+ {Nasty double-check.}) (14. Qxd2 Bxd3 {exploits the pin.}) 14... Nb4 {when White is forced to give up the exchange under very bad circumstances.} 15. axb4 Qxa1+ 16. Qb1 Qxb1+ 17. Bxb1 Bxb1 18. Nxb1 a5 {There's no way of keeping the queenside pawns defended and Black will win with the extra rook.}) 13... b6 {An excellent response for Black. We need to get the rooks involved pronto.} 14. Bd2 {White desperately needs to get the pieces out.} (14. cxb6 $2 {is inadvisable. After} Qxb6 {Black will get the rook to the c-file and cause all sorts of problems.}) 14... Nxd2 15. Bxf5 {This is White's best to keep the positon chaotic.} Nxf3 16. gxf3 (16. Bxh7+ {There are some subtle differences depending on when White captures on h7 -- but most of the time it just transposes back to the main line. For example} Kh8 17. gxf3 bxc5 18. b4 Qb5+ 19. Qd3 c4 20. Qf5 g6 21. Bxg6 fxg6 22. Qxg6 Ne7 {With the same position we study in the main line.}) 16... bxc5 {White's king is very vulnerable in the center, but it turns out Black's king won't be safe either as the h7 -pawn is lost. Both players keep attacking, with very unclear consequences.} 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Kf1 {is an approach where White prioritizes getting the king to safety. On the other hand, it also forces White to take a more defensive approach.} Ne7 {threatening g6 , so the bishop has to retreat.} 19. Bd3 c4 {Once again forcing the bishop to retreat, but also establishing the b2 -pawn as a weakness to target.} 20. Be2 Rab8 {White is up a pawn, but it's very easy for Black to pile up heavy pieces on the b2 -pawn.} 21. Rg1 Qb6 22. Rg3 {Threatening Rh3 + with checkmate.} Kg8 23. Rb1 {White's rook is forced into a defensive position.} Rfc8 {We have a very tense position. White is up a pawn, but black's pieces are much better coordinated. Engines give it as approximately equal, but there's certainly room to play for a win with either color.} *

