these, it's almost nice being Black, since you're not spending any time; You're just making forced moves to avoid checkmate. White, on the other hand, will have to make many difficult decisions to justify being down a knight.} 27. Rd1 {A brave move, I'd say, as it allows Black to get the c-pawn going.} c3+ 28. Ke1 c2 29. Rc1 Rc8 {This is the kind of position where you need to do some self-study with an engine. Short summary: With best play, it's 0.00, but both players will be prone to mistakes in such a tense situation.} 30. Qe6 {The queen directs her attention to both Black's knight on e7 and the rook on c8 .} Rc7 {A necessity to keep everything protected, but now the c2 -pawn falls.} 31. Rxc2 Qd7 {With this move Black guarantees the exchange of queens, or so you would think.} 32. Qxe7+ {WOW! White gives up the queen to get two connected rooks on the seventh rank.} Qxe7 33. Rxc7 Qe6 ({Incredibly,} 33... Qd8 $4 {loses to} 34. h4 $3 {when there's nothing stopping the pawn's march} d4 35. e4 d3 36. h5 d2+ 37. Kd1 Rxf3 38. h6 Rxf2 39. Rg8+ Rf8 40. Rxf8+ $1 Kxf8 41. h7 {and White wins!}) 34. Rxa7 Qc8 {Black keeps everything protected, and will be ready to play d4 and/or Rxf3 next, starting to pose some questions to white's poorly defended king.} *

