1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. h4 {It's a weird-looking move, no doubt -- but it deserves to be taken seriously as White tries to get the bishop outside the pawn chain to g5 before playing e3 .} Bf5 {An added benefit of the Qf6 -move is that the bishop is now protected on f5 .} 12. Bg5 Qe6 {As has become tradition in this line: Black is down a pawn but has fantastic development. It's a great struggle.} 13. Qd1 {This has never been tried in grandmaster games, but it makes sense taking control of the d4 -square.} O-O {As always we're prioritizing our development.} 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 {White hopes to somehow give back the c5 -pawn in a way that transitions the game into a superior endgame, but Black won't cooperate.} Rfc8 {Putting pressure on the queenside pawns. Black is trying to get the rooks involved.} 16. b4 b6 17. Rc1 a5 {We're guaranteed to get the rooks in behind White's pawns. Extreme accuracy is needed just to stay alive for White.} *

