1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. h4 {It's a weird-looking move, no doubt -- but it deserves to be taken seriously as White tries to get the bishop outside the pawn chain to g5 before playing e3 .} Bf5 {An added benefit of the Qf6 -move is that the bishop is now protected on f5 .} 12. Bg5 Qe6 {As has become tradition in this line: Black is down a pawn but has fantastic development. It's a great struggle.} 13. Qc1 d4 {Starts Black's attack and tries to punish White's slow play.} 14. e3 Nxg5 {Firstly, eliminating White's bishop pair. Secondly, preparing queenside castling, when Black's rooks will quickly come to life.} 15. Nxg5 Qg6 16. Bc4 {White threatens on f7 , but it's nothing to be concerned about.} O-O 17. O-O {yeah, White got the king away from the center, but at what cost?} h6 18. Nf3 Rad8 {Black's pieces are very well-placed for an attack. The h4 -pawn looks strange compared to the rest of White's setup. Black has a nice advantage.} *

