1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. e3 {Having already gotten a long-term advantage by stealing a pawn in the opening, White now prioritizes neutralizing Black's short-term advantage by catching up on development.} Bg4 {Developing and putting pressure on White -- what more can you ask from in a move?} 12. Be2 O-O 13. Bd2 {White can delay castling, but Black gets good play.} Rac8 {putting immediate pressure on the c5 -pawn.} 14. O-O Ne5 {There's pressure on both c5 and f3 , and Black gets a good position.} 15. Nxe5 {This was played between two top 100 grandmasters: Lysyj versus Sargissian. With the Black pieces, Sargissian showed perfect preparation in the tactical battle that ensues and got an advantage.} Bxe2 16. Nd7 {White gets the fork on the queen and rook, but White's rook is also in trouble on f1 .} Qa6 17. Nxf8 Bd3 {This is a brilliant intermediate move because it forces white's queen to f1 , where it no longer will protect the d2 -bishop.} 18. Qd1 Bxf1 19. Qxf1 Qxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Nxd2 {As a result of the Bd3 -move, we got to grab White's undefended bishop. But the trickiness isn't over just yet.} 21. Rd1 Rxc5 {Indirectly protecting the knight on d2 by getting the back rank checkmate ready.} 22. Nd7 Rc2 23. b4 b6 {This was all played in Lysysj-Sargissian. Despite having an isolated pawn on d5 , black has the better chances in the endgame because of the active rook and knight.} *

