1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. e3 {Having already gotten a long-term advantage by stealing a pawn in the opening, White now prioritizes neutralizing Black's short-term advantage by catching up on development.} Bg4 {Developing and putting pressure on White -- what more can you ask from in a move?} 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Rfe8 {Black's focus is the e-file. By giving the e4 -knight extra protection, we get ready to push d4 next, further increasing the pressure.} ({Trying to win back the pawn immediately with} 13... Rac8 $2 {is severely punished by} 14. b4 {when it turns out the traditional consideration of material doesn't work here.} Qxa1 $2 15. Bb2 Qa2 16. Ra1 Qxa1+ 17. Bxa1 {White's pawns work harmoniously together and the rooks don't have any open files to control. White has a winning advantage despite having given up two rooks for a queen (and a pawn).}) 14. b4 {This is one of White's most exciting tries. White offers the rook in the corner, but it's a trap!} Bxf3 ({Just as in the 13...Rac8 line, taking the present is not a good idea. The queen is trapped after} 14... Qxa1 $2 15. Bb2 Qa2 16. Ra1 Qxa1+ 17. Bxa1 {White's pawns work harmoniously together and the rooks don't have any open files to control. White has a winning advantage despite having given up two rooks for a queen and a pawn.}) 15. Bb2 {Since the recaptures on f3 are bad, White resorts to huge complications, vacuuming pieces off the board.} Bxe2 {We give up the queen to capture loads of pieces!} 16. Bxf6 Bxf1 {Current material count: Two knights and a rook for a queen and a pawn.} 17. Bxg7 {White tries to create trouble around Black's king.} Bxg2 {Ditto.} 18. Kxg2 Kxg7 {Materially black is doing great -- but there are some problems with the king situation.} 19. Qb2+ f6 20. h4 {The e4 -knight is out of available squares!} Kf7 21. f3 Rg8+ {Whose king is in more trouble now? It's honestly hard to tell.} 22. Kh2 Ne5 {Sure, we could have saved the knight, but where's the fun in that?} 23. fxe4 Rg4 {Black's general plan: Get the other rook on the g-file and then checkmate with Rxh4 .} 24. Kh3 Rag8 25. Qf2 {White tries to cover all the important squares around the king.} Nd3 26. Qh2 {Would be a winning move if not for the surprising turnaround...} Rxe4 {When black's attack suddenly swifts attention to the e3 -pawn instead.} 27. Qd2 Rge8 28. Kg2 Rxe3 {It turns out White's king can't find a safe hiding spot.} 29. Kf1 Re1+ 30. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 31. Kg2 Re2+ 32. Qxe2 Nf4+ 33. Kf3 Nxe2 34. Kxe2 Ke6 {With a winning pawn endgame.} *

