1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. e3 {Having already gotten a long-term advantage by stealing a pawn in the opening, White now prioritizes neutralizing Black's short-term advantage by catching up on development.} Bg4 {Developing and putting pressure on White -- what more can you ask from in a move?} 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Rfe8 {Black's focus is the e-file. By giving the e4 -knight extra protection, we get ready to push d4 next, further increasing the pressure.} ({Trying to win back the pawn immediately with} 13... Rac8 $2 {is severely punished by} 14. b4 {when it turns out the traditional consideration of material doesn't work here.} Qxa1 $2 15. Bb2 Qa2 16. Ra1 Qxa1+ 17. Bxa1 {White's pawns work harmoniously together and the rooks don't have any open files to control. White has a winning advantage despite having given up two rooks for a queen (and a pawn).}) 14. h3 {This was a common move in the infancy of this variation, but it hasn't been played since 2013! Could Black's tremendous score have something to do with it?} Bf5 {The bishop takes aim at the queen, forcing White to move her again instead of developing pieces.} 15. Qb3 {This is exceptionally greedy. The queen will capture on b7 and create a distraction so Black can't get enough pieces into the attack on the other side. I haven't been able to find a win for Black, which frankly surprises me -- there's so much attacking power close to White's king.} Qe6 {The queen takes aim at the White's kingside -- specifically the h3 -pawn.} 16. Qxb7 (16. Rd1 {doesn't change much. Black still sacrifices with} Bxh3 17. gxh3 Qxh3 {when Black's attack secures a perpetual check as the bare minimum.}) 16... Bxh3 {Suddenly White's king is feeling very chilly.} 17. gxh3 Qxh3 18. Qxc6 {White's strategy here is basically 'take everything and hope for the best'.} Qg4+ 19. Kh1 Qh5+ {It's important to choose this square for the check, since we want the x-ray towards White's e2 -bishop.} 20. Nh2 {This is an (overly) risky attempt at continuing the game. (White would be well-advised to take the cautious route while it's still an option. After)} (20. Kg2 Qg4+ {it's an instant draw.}) ({Qxe2} 20. Kg2 $2 {If Black could get the rook to the sixth rank, it would be game over for White. But since the queen attacks the rook on a8 , it's very difficult for Black to get the e8 -rook to g6 .}) 20... Qxe2 21. Kg2 {If Black could get the rook to the sixth rank, it would be game over for White. But since the queen attacks the rook on a8 , it's very difficult for Black to get the e8 -rook to g6 .} (21. b4 {is preferable, when the engines inform me Black has nothing better than} Nxf2+ 22. Kg1 Nh3+ 23. Kh1 Nf2+ {with a draw.}) 21... h6 {It turns out Black has all the time in the world to get the rook involved! But first, we need to create an escape square for the king.} 22. b4 Re5 {Ah, there's not only the sixth rank -- we can also use the fifth rank for our rook lift.} 23. Qxa8+ Kh7 24. Qd8 {White tries to sacrifice the queen for the rook about to land on g5 , but we are not having it!} (24. Nf3 {changes nothing. The knight is chased away after} Rf5 {with checkmate coming up soon.}) 24... f6 {One of those quiet killer moves. White is helpless.} 25. Ra2 {A final trap.} Rg5+ {It's important to insert this check first, as otherwise White would get the knight involved to stop the rook.} 26. Kh1 Qxa2 27. Nf3 {The knight arrives to help out, but it's too late. Black finishes in style.} Qe2 28. Nxg5+ {It's check, so Black can't capture the f1 -rook. But yet it doesn't matter...} Nxg5 {The queen and knight combo is all black needs!} 29. Rg1 Qh5+ 30. Kg2 Qh3# {A stunning end to a stunning line.} *

