1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. e3 {Having already gotten a long-term advantage by stealing a pawn in the opening, White now prioritizes neutralizing Black's short-term advantage by catching up on development.} Bg4 {Developing and putting pressure on White -- what more can you ask from in a move?} 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Rfe8 {Black's focus is the e-file. By giving the e4 -knight extra protection, we get ready to push d4 next, further increasing the pressure.} ({Trying to win back the pawn immediately with} 13... Rac8 $2 {is severely punished by} 14. b4 {when it turns out the traditional consideration of material doesn't work here.} Qxa1 $2 15. Bb2 Qa2 16. Ra1 Qxa1+ 17. Bxa1 {White's pawns work harmoniously together and the rooks don't have any open files to control. White has a winning advantage despite having given up two rooks for a queen (and a pawn).}) 14. h3 {This was a common move in the infancy of this variation, but it hasn't been played since 2013! Could Black's tremendous score have something to do with it?} Bf5 {The bishop takes aim at the queen, forcing White to move her again instead of developing pieces.} 15. Qd1 {The attack on d5 while reinforcing the d4 -square has been White's main choice, but Black's attack plays itself.} (15. Bd3 $2 Bxh3 {is a handy trick to know. Black regains the pawn with an ongoing attack.}) 15... Rad8 16. Nd4 {White gets the knights traded off, but is that really an accomplishment? The f3 -knight was a key defender of White's king.} Bd7 {we're happy to trade knights, but we don't want White to capture our bishop (which we need for the breakthrough sacrifice on h3 ), nor do we want to give the c1 -bishop breathing space by allowing an exd4 recapture in the center.} 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. f3 {For better or worse, White needs to do this, when Black still keeps a firm hand on proceedings...} Ng3 19. Rf2 h5 {Black has good compensation for a pawn with the knight permanently camping around White's king, with reinforcements arriving in form of a pawn being pushed to h4 . But at least White isn't being checkmated.} *

