 files to control. White has a winning advantage despite having given up two rooks for a queen (and a pawn).}) 14. Bd2 {White continues the quest of getting the pieces out.} d4 {We're ready to strike in the center.} 15. Be1 {White tries to conserve the bishop pair.} Rad8 {We gets all the pieces involved. Black preserves the option to go for d3 in addition to taking on e3 .} 16. Rd1 Bf5 17. Bd3 {Is the inaccuracy we were trying to provoke. Black has the great (temporary) exchange sacrifice.} dxe3 18. fxe3 Rxd3 {When the tactics work brilliantly.} 19. Qxd3 {This is a big mistake, but requires precise moves from Black.} (19. Rxd3 {is better, but Black keeps an advantage after} Nxc5) 19... Nf2 ({Avoid} 19... Ng3 $4 20. Nd4 {when it's White who wins in one of the most chaotic situations I've ever witnessed.}) 20. Qd6 Nxd1 21. Qxd1 Qxb2 {Black gets the pawn back on b2 in the best possible way. White's pawn structure is a complete disaster and further pawns will be lost.} *

