1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair, but at the cost of having to move the queen around.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 {I like this move, trying to punish White's lack of development by immediately going after the queen.} 7. Qc2 c5 {We're eager to blast open the center and start an attack while White's king is still stuck in the middle.} 8. dxc5 Nc6 {Black's intention was not to recapture the pawn on c5 . We're all about getting the pieces involved quickly and creating an attack on White's king.} 9. cxd5 {This is clearly the most testing move. It forces black to take on an isolated pawn in the center, and in addition white's queen is now defending the extra pawn white grabbed on c5 .   On the other hand, the exchange opens up the diagonal for black's bishop to get into play and also opens up for a black rook on the e-file. A complicated struggle ensues.} ({Protecting c5 with} 9. b4 $4 {doesn't work because of} Qf6 {with a double threat on f2 and a1 .}) 9... exd5 ({b4?? is still a huge mistake because of} 9... Qf6 {hitting both f2 and a1 .}) 10. Nf3 {The main line. White continues development.} Qf6 {By playing the queen out early Black prevents any hope White had of playing b4 safe-guarding the extra pawn on c5 .} 11. e3 {Having already gotten a long-term advantage by stealing a pawn in the opening, White now prioritizes neutralizing Black's short-term advantage by catching up on development.} Bg4 {Developing and putting pressure on White -- what more can you ask from in a move?} 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Rfe8 {Black's focus is the e-file. By giving the e4 -knight extra protection, we get ready to push d4 next, further increasing the pressure.} ({Trying to win back the pawn immediately with} 13... Rac8 $2 {is severely punished by} 14. b4 {when it turns out the traditional consideration of material doesn't work here.} Qxa1 $2 15. Bb2 Qa2 16. Ra1 Qxa1+ 17. Bxa1 {White's pawns work harmoniously together and the rooks don't have any open files to control. White has a winning advantage despite having given up two rooks for a queen (and a pawn).}) 14. Bd2 {White continues the quest of getting the pieces out.} d4 {We're ready to strike in the center.} 15. Be1 {White tries to conserve the bishop pair.} Rad8 {We gets all the pieces involved. Black preserves the option to go for d3 in addition to taking on e3 .} 16. Rd1 Bf5 17. Qc1 Bg4 {The bishop paradoxically returns on g4 , eyeing the undefended bishop on e2 . White should defend it.} 18. Qc2 Bf5 {when we're just walking around in circles.} *

