1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 {Taking with the queen is very uncommon, but Black needs to be resolute in facing it.} Nc6 {I like this direct assault on White's center.} 8. Nf3 {White both protects the d4 -pawn and keeps tabs on the e5 -square, but even so, it turns out we can go for the immediate central conflict.} (8. e3 $6 {allows Black to seize the initiative immediately with} e5) 8... Ne4 9. Qc2 {It's easy to be tempted by the free pawn on d4 .} e5 {But this is even better - to open up for the c8 -bishop to join.} 10. e3 {White desperately needs to get the pieces out, and the bishop will get to c4 with an attack on Black's queen.} Bf5 11. Bc4 Qa5+ {Getting out of the threats while making some against White's king.} 12. Bd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 O-O-O {Black has comfortable development. It's white who has to play accurately to keep the position equal.} *

