1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 {Taking with the queen is very uncommon, but Black needs to be resolute in facing it.} Nc6 {I like this direct assault on White's center.} 8. Nf3 {White both protects the d4 -pawn and keeps tabs on the e5 -square, but even so, it turns out we can go for the immediate central conflict.} (8. e3 $6 {allows Black to seize the initiative immediately with} e5) 8... Ne4 9. Qd3 e5 {We strike again!} 10. dxe5 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Qxd2+ {Black has temporarily sacrificed a pawn on e5 , but it's not going anywhere.} 13. Nxd2 {This has been White's main choice, giving back the e5 -pawn, but hoping to get an edge in the endgame.} (13. Kxd2 {White can try to hold on to the e5 -pawn, but it's just a question of time before it falls.} Bg4 {Getting ready to remove the defender.} 14. Kc3 O-O-O {= Black has great development and will win back the e5 -pawn. Either through capturing the f3 -knight, or by playing Rhe8 .}) 13... Nxe5 14. Rc1 {The threat on c7 causes Black some problems.} Bd7 {This is the right antidote! It was actually played by Colle way back in 1929 when he got a big win against Rubenstein. Black prepares to castle queenside, so the big question is what happens if White's rook captures the pawn.} (14... c6 {but this allows white to seize the center with} 15. f4 Ng4 16. e4 {when White is somewhat better. Instead Black has a tricky way of indirectly defending the c7 -pawn.}) 15. f4 {White tries to chase the knight away from the protection of the f7 -pawn, to give the rook more freedom once it gets shut in on c7 .} (15. Rxc7 $2 Bc6 {sees the rook being trapped with Kd8 next.}) 15... Ng4 16. Rxc7 Bc6 {For the moment Black doesn't have the threat of Kd8 since the f7 -pawn is undefended. But defending that pawn is only a matter of playing Rf8 next, so White needs to hurry to extract the rook.} 17. Nc4 O-O {We got a good news and bad news situation for White. They successfully chased Black's king away from the white rook, but on the other hand there's a major problem developing the kingside. Black has excellent compensation for a pawn and will likely win it back in White's struggle to untangle.} *

