1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 {This is very similar to the 6. e3 line where white plays 8. bxc3 . The only difference is that White has played a3 instead of Bd2 .} b6 {It's important to get the c8 -bishop involved early. Preferably to a6 , where it will trade off White's bishop pair.} 9. Nf3 cxd4 {I like this move because it creates a crossroads where white's decision will tell us about White's upcoming plans, which in turn allows us to prepare for them.} 10. cxd4 {The disadvantage of this pawn structure is the lack of light-squared control. Black will play Ba6 in the future to exchange off White's bishop pair, and then come invading with the rooks on the c-file.} O-O {It's important to get castled to avoid any Qa4 + nastiness.} 11. Bc4 Qc6 12. O-O (12. Qe2 $4 {to prevent Ba6 was once played by a 2600-rated grandmaster, but after} b5 $1 13. Bxb5 Qc3+ {Black wins.}) 12... Ba6 {Black gets the desired bishop trade.} 13. Ne5 Qb7 {The Black rooks are coming to the c-file and White's bishop pair will be eliminated momentarily. Black has no problems.} *

