1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 {This is very similar to the 6. e3 line where white plays 8. bxc3 . The only difference is that White has played a3 instead of Bd2 .} b6 {It's important to get the c8 -bishop involved early. Preferably to a6 , where it will trade off White's bishop pair.} 9. Nf3 cxd4 {I like this move because it creates a crossroads where white's decision will tell us about White's upcoming plans, which in turn allows us to prepare for them.} 10. exd4 Qe4+ {With a favorable queen trade for Black. White's position becomes difficult to handle because every Black piece will try to attack the c4 -square.} 11. Qxe4 Nxe4 12. c4 Ba6 13. Bf4 {White needs to prevent Nd6 , otherwise this will very quickly become a disaster for the c4 -pawn.} Nc6 14. Bd3 Nf6 15. O-O {White got the pieces into play, but there's some extreme pressure on the c4 -pawn to deal with.} Na5 16. Rac1 Rc8 {The engines claim white is fine with correct play, but I would be very nervous in their shoes. The central pawns are very easy targets and Black has a clear plan to go after them.} *

