1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. a3 {White immediately grabs the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 {This is very similar to the 6. e3 line where white plays 8. bxc3 . The only difference is that White has played a3 instead of Bd2 .} b6 {It's important to get the c8 -bishop involved early. Preferably to a6 , where it will trade off White's bishop pair.} 9. Nf3 cxd4 {I like this move because it creates a crossroads where white's decision will tell us about White's upcoming plans, which in turn allows us to prepare for them.} 10. c4 {An unexpected, but brilliant move. White prevents the trade of bishops along the a6 - f1 diagonal in such a way that Black won't get the desired queen trade like in the 10. exd4  line.} Qe4 {Black tries to get the queen trade.} 11. Bd3 {Request denied! This move is actually a stunning sacrifice.} Qg4 {The attack on the g2 -pawn make it seem like Black is winning a pawn, but it's all an illusion.} 12. O-O Bb7 {We sensibly develop instead of opening up the position for all of White's pieces.} ({Greed with} 12... dxe3 $6 {is punished by the amazing} 13. h3 $1 Qf4 (13... exf2+ $4 {doesn't work because of} 14. Rxf2 Qh5 15. Be4 {when the rook is trapped.}) 14. c5 {A double pawn sacrifice from white unleashes the full potential in White's army! Notice the huge difference in development. Black's position is very scary.}) 13. h3 Qh5 14. Nxd4 {White is happy to sit with the bishop pair, but the queenside pawn structure has been ruined. Even so, Black should definitely take care to neutralize the bishops as soon as possible.} Nbd7 {Black delays castling to go after the d3 -bishop as soon as possible.} 15. a4 {White is trying to play a5 , which will exchange off White's broken pawn structure.} Nc5 16. Be2 Qg5 {This is clever. Black forces the nicely centralized knight back before offering the queen trade.} 17. Nf3 Qg6 18. Qxg6 hxg6 {White is slightly better, but Black's well-placed knight on c5 does a good job of neutralizing White's bishop pair.} *

