1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. a3 {This nets White the bishops, but only temporarily.} Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 ({(} 8. bxc3 {is studied in the 6. a3  line. ) If White were allowed to develop unhindered, they would have an advantage with the bishop pair. However, because White opened up for the f1 -bishop with e3 on move 6, we're able to trade them off...}) 8... b6 {Black will play Ba6 next and thereby exchange off White's bishop pair.} 9. dxc5 Ba6 {We don't even care about that pawn! We're all about quick development and getting favorable trades.} 10. cxb6 Bxf1 {Black lost a pawn, but we've forced White's king to move, which prevents castling.} 11. Kxf1 axb6 12. f3 O-O 13. Ne2 Nbd7 {White's pawn snatching has come at a price: Both White rooks are undeveloped in the corner, and Black is about to chase White's queen with a rook arriving on the c-file. Black has great compensation for a pawn.} *

