1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. f3 {White ambitiously tries to take control of the light squares in the center.} O-O 10. e4 Qd7 {This is the optimal square for the queen. We want to keep the pressure on White's new weakness: the d4 -pawn. Next, we're able to go Nc6 and Rd8 .} 11. Be3 {gives Black good timing to exchange off the bishops.} Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Ne2 Rfc8 {White will have to move the queen regardless, when Be3 turns out to have been an unnecessary move. It would have been better spending that time to castle.} 14. Qb3 ({If} 14. Qb2 {Black has a beautiful plan in} Ne8 15. O-O Nd6 {when there's a black knight arriving on the c4 -square after all.}) 14... Nb8 {The knight is re-routed towards the c4 -square, and since it gets there via a5 it will push back White's queen on its way.} 15. dxc5 {White tries to create a distraction for the knight manuever, but we care more about getting to c4 than that c5 -pawn.} Nc6 {A typical pawn sacrifice in such positions: Black is happy to open the a-file for the rook, and will not be delayed in the mission of getting the knight to c4 .} 16. cxb6 Na5 17. Qc2 Nc4 18. Bf2 axb6 {Black has good play for a pawn. The knight on c4 is a monster and there's great potential to create pressure down the a-file.} *

