1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. f3 {White ambitiously tries to take control of the light squares in the center.} O-O 10. e4 Qd7 {This is the optimal square for the queen. We want to keep the pressure on White's new weakness: the d4 -pawn. Next, we're able to go Nc6 and Rd8 .} 11. Qb2 {This is an accurate choice for White, since the queen evacuates from the c-file while giving protection to the d4 -pawn at the same time. The c-file is bound to open sooner or later, and the queen would rather not be around when Black's rooks arrive.} Nc6 {We go after the d4 -pawn.} (11... Ba6 {is an option, but compared to the 11. Be3 -line White gets development going one move quicker since there's no need to spend time on Be3 now.} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Ne2 {. The d4 -pawn is well-protected and White can get castled next.}) 12. Be3 {Now Be3 became a neccesity to keep the center defended.} Rd8 {This is technically a pawn sacrifice, since the c5 -pawn is under attack -- but Black would welcome White surrendering the center and opening up files for Black's pieces.} 13. dxc5 bxc5 {White would be ill-adviced to capture the c5 -pawn, as it's time-consuming and gives Black more open files to attack on.} 14. Nh3 {is better, when Black gets a good position...} Qc7 15. Be2 Qa5 16. O-O Ba6 {when Black is eliminating White's bishop pair and fighting for control of the c4 -square, in hopes of maneuvering a knight there in the future.} *

