1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. f3 {White ambitiously tries to take control of the light squares in the center.} O-O 10. e4 Qd7 {This is the optimal square for the queen. We want to keep the pressure on White's new weakness: the d4 -pawn. Next, we're able to go Nc6 and Rd8 .} 11. Qb2 {This is an accurate choice for White, since the queen evacuates from the c-file while giving protection to the d4 -pawn at the same time. The c-file is bound to open sooner or later, and the queen would rather not be around when Black's rooks arrive.} Nc6 {We go after the d4 -pawn.} (11... Ba6 {is an option, but compared to the 11. Be3 -line White gets development going one move quicker since there's no need to spend time on Be3 now.} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Ne2 {. The d4 -pawn is well-protected and White can get castled next.}) 12. Be3 {Now Be3 became a neccesity to keep the center defended.} Rd8 {This is technically a pawn sacrifice, since the c5 -pawn is under attack -- but Black would welcome White surrendering the center and opening up files for Black's pieces.} 13. Rd1 {White keeps the center defended. So what's next for Black?} Ne8 {This is a very clever maneuver. When on f6 , the knight was blocked out of play by White's f3 - e4 pawn structure. It's time to find better pastures for the horsie.} 14. Bd3 {White needs to get the pieces out as soon as possible, and this move exploits potential e5 and Bxh7 + tactics to keep the d4 -pawn indirectly protected.} Qe7 {The idea is to use the b4 -square for the knight to disrupt White and get pieces in good positions – In particular getting the bishop out to a6 .} (14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Nxd4 {is the attempt to punish White’s play but after} 16. e5 Nf5 17. Bg5 {we get a tricky position where I prefer White.}) 15. Ne2 cxd4 16. cxd4 Nb4 17. Bb1 Ba6 {Mission accomplished!} 18. a3 Nc6 {The knight is forced back, but we got the bishop out, so it was all worth it.} 19. e5 {An important move for White to restrict the black knight on e8 .} Rac8 20. h4 {White needs the g5 -square for the bishop.} Qd7 {We’re just avoiding Bg5 , while also making the e7 -square available for our knight.} 21. Kf2 (21. Qc2 $2 {This makes a big threat for White, but the queen also steps into a dangerous file. If the attack is averted the queen will rue stepping into the c8 -rook’s influence.} f5 $1 22. exf6 Nxf6 {=+ The attack has been stopped, and Black has some yummy squares in the center and active pieces.}) 21... Ne7 {It’s a very complicated position. Black has to be careful of the pieces pointing towards their king, but there’s also a great square for Black’s pieces on d5 , and both knights are en route.} *

