1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. f3 {White ambitiously tries to take control of the light squares in the center.} O-O 10. e4 Qd7 {This is the optimal square for the queen. We want to keep the pressure on White's new weakness: the d4 -pawn. Next, we're able to go Nc6 and Rd8 .} 11. Qb2 {This is an accurate choice for White, since the queen evacuates from the c-file while giving protection to the d4 -pawn at the same time. The c-file is bound to open sooner or later, and the queen would rather not be around when Black's rooks arrive.} Nc6 {We go after the d4 -pawn.} (11... Ba6 {is an option, but compared to the 11. Be3 -line White gets development going one move quicker since there's no need to spend time on Be3 now.} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Ne2 {. The d4 -pawn is well-protected and White can get castled next.}) 12. Be3 {Now Be3 became a neccesity to keep the center defended.} Rd8 {This is technically a pawn sacrifice, since the c5 -pawn is under attack -- but Black would welcome White surrendering the center and opening up files for Black's pieces.} 13. Rd1 {White keeps the center defended. So what's next for Black?} Ne8 {This is a very clever maneuver. When on f6 , the knight was blocked out of play by White's f3 - e4 pawn structure. It's time to find better pastures for the horsie.} 14. Bb5 {Putting further pressure on Black while also developing.} Nd6 {A good move, initiating complicated tactics while White's king is yet to be evacuated away from the center.} 15. dxc5 {White must accept the gambit, as otherwise Black would eliminate the important light-squared bishop.} bxc5 16. Bxc5 Qb7 {First we sacrifice a pawn, then a piece! We'll get it back though, as Black's queen creates a pin on white's b5 -bishop.} 17. Bxd6 a6 {Taking out white's light-squared bishop is a major accomplishment as there's several light-square weaknesses in the position -- in particular the c4 -square.} 18. a4 {White tries to hold on to as much material as possible.} axb5 19. axb5 {A quick count sees white two pawns up, but White's king is still in the center.} e5 20. Qb1 {White defends the queen.} h5 {An amazing move! It turns out the c6 -knight is indirectly protected, and there are several variations where Black needs an escape square for the king on h7 . As if that wasn't enough, the pawn is actually getting involved in an attack. It will push on to h4 and restrict the options for White's knight.} 21. Ne2 Be6 {The bishop is headed for an amazing outpost on c4 .} 22. bxc6 {It's time for white to get the queens off the board.} Qxb1 23. Rxb1 Rxd6 24. c7 {Trying to promote the pawn is the only way to play for a win.} (24. Kf2 {This is the way to play it safe for White. But with minimum risk also comes minimum reward.} Rxc6 25. Ra1 Rac8 {. The pawn on c3 isn't going anywhere.}) 24... Ra7 {A very unorthodox way of stopping the pawn, we need to avoid Rb8 .} 25. Rb8+ {Getting a new queen doesn't work out for white.} Kh7 26. c8=Q Bxc8 27. Rxc8 {Technically this is the mistake -- but it was the whole idea behind getting a new queen.} Ra1+ {Swift punishment. White loses the rook in the corner.} *

