ry clever maneuver. When on f6 , the knight was blocked out of play by White's f3 - e4 pawn structure. It's time to find better pastures for the horsie.} 14. Bb5 {Putting further pressure on Black while also developing.} Nd6 {A good move, initiating complicated tactics while White's king is yet to be evacuated away from the center.} 15. dxc5 {White must accept the gambit, as otherwise Black would eliminate the important light-squared bishop.} bxc5 16. Bxc5 Qb7 {First we sacrifice a pawn, then a piece! We'll get it back though, as Black's queen creates a pin on white's b5 -bishop.} 17. Bxd6 a6 {Taking out white's light-squared bishop is a major accomplishment as there's several light-square weaknesses in the position -- in particular the c4 -square.} 18. a4 {White tries to hold on to as much material as possible.} axb5 19. axb5 {A quick count sees white two pawns up, but White's king is still in the center.} e5 20. Qb1 {White defends the queen.} h5 {An amazing move! It turns out the c6 -knight is indirectly protected, and there are several variations where Black needs an escape square for the king on h7 . As if that wasn't enough, the pawn is actually getting involved in an attack. It will push on to h4 and restrict the options for White's knight.} 21. Ne2 Be6 {The bishop is headed for an amazing outpost on c4 .} 22. bxc6 {It's time for white to get the queens off the board.} Qxb1 23. Rxb1 Rxd6 24. c7 {Trying to promote the pawn is the only way to play for a win.} (24. Kf2 {This is the way to play it safe for White. But with minimum risk also comes minimum reward.} Rxc6 25. Ra1 Rac8 {. The pawn on c3 isn't going anywhere.}) 24... Ra7 {A very unorthodox way of stopping the pawn, we need to avoid Rb8 .} 25. Ng3 {White goes after the h5 -pawn, while simultaneously protecting the rook in the corner.} Ra2 {An unbelieveable move! We move the rook for a second time and allow the c-pawn to live. All because the second rank is now open. Black's rooks will create lot of trouble for White's king.} 26. Rb8+ Kh7 27. c8=Q {The promotion wins White a bishop, but Black's rooks are devestating on the counterattack.} Bxc8 28. Rxc8 Rb6 {The rooks are ready to do some damage!} 29. O-O {This actually loses for White!} Rbb2 {Two rooks on the second rank live up to their stellar reputation!} 30. Rd1 Rxg2+ 31. Kf1 h4 {The final nail in the coffin: The h-pawn.} 32. Nf5 Rxh2 33. Kg1 Rag2+ 34. Kf1 h3 {There's a checkmate coming up.} *

