ry clever maneuver. When on f6 , the knight was blocked out of play by White's f3 - e4 pawn structure. It's time to find better pastures for the horsie.} 14. Bb5 {Putting further pressure on Black while also developing.} Nd6 {A good move, initiating complicated tactics while White's king is yet to be evacuated away from the center.} 15. dxc5 {White must accept the gambit, as otherwise Black would eliminate the important light-squared bishop.} bxc5 16. Bxc5 Qb7 {First we sacrifice a pawn, then a piece! We'll get it back though, as Black's queen creates a pin on white's b5 -bishop.} 17. Bxd6 a6 {Taking out white's light-squared bishop is a major accomplishment as there's several light-square weaknesses in the position -- in particular the c4 -square.} 18. a4 {White tries to hold on to as much material as possible.} axb5 19. axb5 {A quick count sees white two pawns up, but White's king is still in the center.} e5 20. Qe2 {By getting out of the b-file, White forces the knight to move.} Ne7 {It's best to keep the knight in the center. It can find new life on f4 via g6 later.} 21. Bxe7 {Giving up the bishop is not the way for white. It allows for the trade of rooks, which will make White's king position even more precarious. It also gives up control of the dark squares, which is unfortunate considering the light squares on the queenside was already a problem.} Qxe7 {There's no need to help White's development by capturing on d1 , which would open up the e2 -square for White's knight.} 22. Rxd8+ Qxd8 23. Kf2 {White tries to run the king out to g3 (after first playing h4 or Qe3 to cover the g5 -square).} Qh4+ 24. g3 Qd8 {The back and forth check has taken away the g3 -square for White's king. Despite being two pawns up, White is in serious trouble. The king has nowhere to hide.} *

