1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. f3 {White ambitiously tries to take control of the light squares in the center.} O-O 10. e4 Qd7 {This is the optimal square for the queen. We want to keep the pressure on White's new weakness: the d4 -pawn. Next, we're able to go Nc6 and Rd8 .} 11. Qb2 {This is an accurate choice for White, since the queen evacuates from the c-file while giving protection to the d4 -pawn at the same time. The c-file is bound to open sooner or later, and the queen would rather not be around when Black's rooks arrive.} Nc6 {We go after the d4 -pawn.} (11... Ba6 {is an option, but compared to the 11. Be3 -line White gets development going one move quicker since there's no need to spend time on Be3 now.} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Ne2 {. The d4 -pawn is well-protected and White can get castled next.}) 12. Be3 {Now Be3 became a neccesity to keep the center defended.} Rd8 {This is technically a pawn sacrifice, since the c5 -pawn is under attack -- but Black would welcome White surrendering the center and opening up files for Black's pieces.} 13. Rd1 {White keeps the center defended. So what's next for Black?} Ne8 {This is a very clever maneuver. When on f6 , the knight was blocked out of play by White's f3 - e4 pawn structure. It's time to find better pastures for the horsie.} 14. Bb5 {Putting further pressure on Black while also developing.} Nd6 {A good move, initiating complicated tactics while White's king is yet to be evacuated away from the center.} 15. dxc5 {White must accept the gambit, as otherwise Black would eliminate the important light-squared bishop.} bxc5 16. Bxc5 Qb7 {First we sacrifice a pawn, then a piece! We'll get it back though, as Black's queen creates a pin on white's b5 -bishop.} 17. Bxd6 a6 {Taking out white's light-squared bishop is a major accomplishment as there's several light-square weaknesses in the position -- in particular the c4 -square.} 18. a4 {White tries to hold on to as much material as possible.} axb5 19. axb5 {A quick count sees white two pawns up, but White's king is still in the center.} e5 20. Qe2 {By getting out of the b-file, White forces the knight to move.} Ne7 {It's best to keep the knight in the center. It can find new life on f4 via g6 later.} 21. c4 {The best defense is a good offense! White tries to re-take control of the queenside by pushing the passed pawns.} Be6 22. Nh3 {White is one move away from getting the king to safety. Black needs to strike quickly.} Rdc8 {We're encouraging White's c-pawn to move forward because we need to access the a2 -square.} 23. c5 (23. Rc1 Ra4 24. c5 Ra2 {is similar to the mainline.}) 23... Ra2 24. Qd3 ({If White has had enough adventure for one game, there's a draw available with} 24. Rd2 Ra1+ 25. Rd1 Ra2 {.}) 24... Bxh3 {Black permanently damages White's pawn structure, as well as White's king safety.} 25. gxh3 Ng6 26. Bxe5 {White exploits the back rank checkmate to get control of the f4 -square, in addition to winning yet another pawn.} Qe7 {White's king will never feel safe, but three pawns is a huge investment. The engines say it's equal -- 0.00 -- but anything could happen. Black could get a checkmate, White could queen a pawn or anything in between.} *

