1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. Nf3 Bb7 {I think this is a very accurate moveorder for Black. We need control of the e4 -square for a knight.} 10. c4 {White can start early aggression, but Black is ready for it.} Qd6 {It's important to place the queen here, for reasons that will become obvious.} 11. Be2 Ne4 {We're going after the bishop pair before White's king gets out of danger. Good thing we got our bishop to b7 early to enable this lunge.} 12. Bc1 cxd4 13. exd4 Qb4+ {Now we see why d6 was the right square for the queen! White's efforts to keep the bishop pair forces one retreat after another.} 14. Nd2 Qc3 {We're deep in enemy territory and creating all sorts of problems. The so-called hanging pawns on c4 and d4 will provide plenty of defensive headaches for White in the queenless middlegame.} *

