1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. Nf3 Bb7 {I think this is a very accurate moveorder for Black. We need control of the e4 -square for a knight.} 10. Be2 {We reach a crossroads, where Black has two very different ways of playing.} c4 {To me it feels very wrong to release the pressure on White's center, but at the same time we establish a long-term space advantage and prevent White from kicking the queen off her dominating position on d5 .} 11. O-O Nbd7 {We need the knight involved early to support the e5 -push.} 12. Ne1 {White's idea is to play f3 and e4 , which would block Black's wonderful diagonal and completely dominate the center. It must be prevented.} e5 {If not for this move, Black would be strategically lost.} 13. f3 e4 {This is the key. We manage to prevent e4 from White by pushing our own pawn there. Black's grip on the light squares in the center has been fully secured and White's bishops have been boxed in. Black is better.} *

