1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. bxc3 {This is a very interesting and underrated option. It's closely related to the 6.a3 -line -- the only difference being that White has a bishop on d2 instead of a pawn on a3 .} b6 {I think this is a very important move. Black needs to get the bishop involved before castling.} 9. Nf3 Bb7 {I think this is a very accurate moveorder for Black. We need control of the e4 -square for a knight.} 10. Be2 {We reach a crossroads, where Black has two very different ways of playing.} c4 {To me it feels very wrong to release the pressure on White's center, but at the same time we establish a long-term space advantage and prevent White from kicking the queen off her dominating position on d5 .} 11. O-O Nbd7 {We need the knight involved early to support the e5 -push.} 12. a4 O-O 13. Rfb1 {White's last two moves have been trying to separate the c4 -pawn from the rest of the pack by preventing b5 .} a6 {We're getting ready to support the c4 -pawn with b5 next.} 14. Ne1 e5 15. dxe5 ({Once again it's crucial to meet} 15. f3 {with} e4 {to stop White from playing e4 themselves.}) 15... Qxe5 {Because of the threat on the b6 -pawn we have to take back with the queen on this occasion.} 16. f3 (16. Bxc4 $2 {would be good if not for} Ng4 {when White faces serious problems on the kingside.}) 16... Bd5 {Our method of keeping the c4 -pawn defended is very unorthodox, but it works out since we have a good reply in response to white's e4 -move.} 17. e4 Nc5 {Turns out we don't have to move our bishop, due to the queen's x-ray on the e2 -bishop. In the meantime our knight is headed for the b3 -square, where it will shut down White's queenside intentions.} 18. Bf1 {is a natural move, but is met with overwhelming force.} Ncxe4 19. fxe4 Bxe4 {It looks as though we're going after White's rook on b1 , but it's actually all about White's king!} 20. Qc1 {White covers against Qc5 +, but leaves the g4 -square undefended.} Ng4 21. Bf4 Qc5+ {Game over.} *

