1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. Bxc3 {White gets the bishop involved early, but as a consequence Black can target the bishop to get quick development.} cxd4 9. Bxd4 Nc6 {We're happy to develop pieces while attacking White's bishop in the process. This gives White a big decision: do you protect the bishop at the expense of tune for development, or do you give away the bishop so saddle Black with doubled pawns?} 10. Bxf6 gxf6 {Black doesn't need to be very concerned about the doubled pawns. It helps Black's influence in the center and sometimes we can use the open g-file for attacking purposes.} 11. Ne2 Bd7 {All the best moves have more than one purpose. This one prepares Nb4 without any Qa4 counter-check, as well as getting ready for a rook to the c-file.} 12. a3 (12. Nc3 {allows} Nb4 {when Black is doing just fine. For example} 13. Qd1 Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Ke7 15. a3 Nc6 {There's no need to fear in the endgame. Black has a nicely centralized king, and the doubled f-pawns give extra central control.}) 12... Qa5+ 13. Nc3 Ne7 {The knight gets out of the way of the rook which may want to point down the c-file, and the bishop which wants to point down towards the kingside from c6 .   In addition, there's a threat of Nd5 White needs to deal with.} 14. Bc4 Bc6 {The bishop finds its diagonal.} 15. O-O Qg5 {This seems like a very crude move, but the checkmate threat isn't actually that easy to face.} 16. g3 {This is a move White wanted to avoid. The light squares around the king is weakened, and the h5 - h4 -plan becomes much stronger when there's a pawn to latch on to.} (16. e4 $6 {doesn't change much, as Black can play} Rg8 {when White again must play} 17. g3 {which allows} h5 {and a brewing attack.}) 16... h5 17. h4 {A necessity to stop ... h4 .} Qe5 {Black has interesting attacking chances.} *

