1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. e3 {White defends the pawn while opening up for the bishop.} c5 {It's crucial to strike against White's center pawns as soon as possible.} 7. Bd2 {Unpinning the knight, which means Black has to deal with the threat on the queen.} Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop is Black's best bet. We're counting on quick development to deal with White's bishop pair.} 8. Bxc3 {White gets the bishop involved early, but as a consequence Black can target the bishop to get quick development.} cxd4 9. Bxd4 Nc6 {We're happy to develop pieces while attacking White's bishop in the process. This gives White a big decision: do you protect the bishop at the expense of tune for development, or do you give away the bishop so saddle Black with doubled pawns?} 10. Bc3 {Keeping the bishops is the best way to fight for an advantage.} O-O {As always in the Nimzo: Quick development is black's antidote to giving away the bishop pair.} 11. Nf3 Rd8 {The bishop on c3 may look great, but it's also exposed to attack from Black's pieces. That's the mission now: Finding a good way to eliminate the bishop. First up is stopping Bd3 , which will enable Qe4 next.} ({Stay away from} 11... Ne4 $4 {since} 12. Rd1 Qf5 13. Bd3 {wins the e4 -knight.}) 12. Be2 (12. a3 {is too slow, as Black gets rid of the c3 -bishop with} Ne4 {and the symmetrical position doesn't promise white an advantage after} 13. Be2 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Bd7 15. O-O Be8 {This standard plan gives Black a nice position. The bishop gets out of the way so the rooks can fight on the open files.}) 12... Qe4 {This is partly about the queen trade, but just as much about making the e4 -square secure for Black's knight.} 13. Rc1 Qxc2 14. Rxc2 Bd7 ({Patience is a virtue! The immediate} 14... Ne4 $6 {is well met by} 15. Ne5 {when it turns out the bishop manages to create an escape square for itself, which makes Black's defensive task significantly more difficult.}) 15. Ne5 {White needs access to the e5 -square as an escape for the c3 -bishop.} (15. O-O {plays into Black's hands, as} Ne4 {eliminates the c3 -bishop. A retreat with} 16. Be1 {is very risky, as the f1 -rook is locked completely out of play.} Be8 {Black's knight on e4 is ruining the coordination in White's pieces. With the last move we prevented Bd3 , so the central knight keeps its outpost.}) 15... Rac8 16. Nxd7 {White is playing with the philosophy of 'when offered bishops, take them'. It's usually a strategy I can get behind, but here Black's development advantage is creating plenty of threats on White's position, which keeps the game balanced.} Rxd7 17. Bd2 {Running away doesn't let white keep the bishop pair.} Ne4 18. Bc1 Rdd8 {It turns out the c1 -bishop is in grave danger of being trapped where it sits, with Nb4 - a2 coming up. Stopping the knight's entry doesn't work...} 19. a3 Nd4 {showcases Black's tactical potential. Black has winning tactics.} 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Bd2 {At this point Black won't settle for a bishop in exchange of a knight.} Nc2+ 22. Kd1 Nxf2+ {There's a whole rook on offer! Black wins.} *

