1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qxf5 exf5 {This endgame is considered very decent for Black.} 8. Bf4 {It looks like White is going after the c7 -pawn, but it's actually just as much about preventing Bd6 by luring the c-pawn forward.} Be6 9. a3 Bxc3+ {Retreating to d6 is possible, but White's play has given black an additional option.} 10. bxc3 Nd5 {The double attack on c3 and f4 forces White back while the knight runs around to find its perfect home.} 11. Bd2 Nb6 {The knight is headed for c4 ! Black has amazing control of the light squares.} 12. a4 Nc6 {Now there's a second knight headed for c4 , via a5 .} 13. a5 Nc4 14. a6 b5 {The knight on c4 is great, and as is Black's light-squared control.} *

