1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qxf5 exf5 {This endgame is considered very decent for Black.} 8. a3 {Immediately forcing the bishop to show its intentions.} Bd6 {I think there's no doubt d6 is the best square for the bishop, but there's a question of whether Black should fear losing the bishop pair to Nb5 . Studying the lines has made me decide there's no reason to worry.} 9. Bg5 {White's intention is to provoke Black forward, making Black's pawns easier to attack.} Ne4 {We're happy to move forward.} 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Nd2 f5 12. e3 Nc6 ({Avoid} 12... Be6 $2 {because of the undermining move} 13. g4 {when Black really will regret having moved the pawns forward so aggressively.}) 13. Nc4 {White goes for the bishop pair, but we don't really mind.} (13. g4 $4 {allows} h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 f4 {when black is dominating.}) ({It's worth noting that the tricky} 13. Bh4 $5 {should be met with} h6 $1 {to keep the g5 -plan alive if White tries g4 .} (13... Be6 $2 14. g4 {causes Black's center to collapse.})) 13... Be6 14. Nxd6+ cxd6 {Black's light-squared control makes up for losing the bishop pair. Black's plan is Kd7 , Rfc8 and getting the knight to d5 .} 15. d5 {This direct approach tries to eliminate some pawns to make the bishop pair more prominent.} Bxd5 16. Rd1 Bb3 17. Rxd6 h6 {Black needs to do something quickly to exploit the huge lead in development before White gets the bishops coordinated.} 18. Bf4 g5 19. Bg3 Ke7 {The threat of pushing the pawn to f4 and disrupting the rook's protection forces White to retreat.} 20. Rd2 Ke6 {Black will get the knight to e5 or White will have to move the rook back for a repetition of moves. Either way it's equal.} *

