1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qxf5 exf5 {This endgame is considered very decent for Black.} 8. a3 {Immediately forcing the bishop to show its intentions.} Bd6 {I think there's no doubt d6 is the best square for the bishop, but there's a question of whether Black should fear losing the bishop pair to Nb5 . Studying the lines has made me decide there's no reason to worry.} 9. Nb5 {White wins the bishop pair, but at the cost of surrendering the light squares in the center.} Be6 10. e3 Nc6 {Na5- b3 is a potential plan for Black.} 11. Bd2 {Stops any Na5 -ideas.} Ne4 12. Bd3 a6 {It's time for the knight to open the c-file for Black.} 13. Nxd6+ cxd6 {The d6 -pawn is a very important part of Black's scheme. You can't exclusively rely on a light-squared strategy -- you must cover some of the dark squares as well, and the d6 -pawn does just that.} 14. O-O Kd7 15. Rfc1 Nxd2 {I'm a big believer in the long-term value of the bishops, and I think this is the right timing to take out white's bishop. Now that the f1 -rook has been involved on the queenside, White was planning Be1 next which saves the bishop without blocking in the rook.} 16. Nxd2 g6 {We've protected everything. Next up on the agenda is rook trades on the c-file.} 17. Nc4 {The Nb6 -threat prevents Black from using the c-file -- for the time being.} Rab8 {Patience is a virtue: We're preparing b5 to kick the knight out, and then we're ready to challenge the c-file.} 18. d5 {White initiates tactics, but Black's active king is actually an asset, not a liability.} Bxd5 19. Nb6+ Ke6 20. Nxd5 Kxd5 21. Bc4+ Ke5 22. Bxf7 d5 {Black's king is seemingly exposed, but it's the white bishop on f7 that should worry about its safety.} *

