1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qxf5 exf5 {This endgame is considered very decent for Black.} 8. a3 {Immediately forcing the bishop to show its intentions.} Bd6 {I think there's no doubt d6 is the best square for the bishop, but there's a question of whether Black should fear losing the bishop pair to Nb5 . Studying the lines has made me decide there's no reason to worry.} 9. Nb5 {White wins the bishop pair, but at the cost of surrendering the light squares in the center.} Be6 10. e3 Nc6 {Na5- b3 is a potential plan for Black.} 11. Bd2 {Stops any Na5 -ideas.} Ne4 12. Bd3 a6 {It's time for the knight to open the c-file for Black.} 13. Nxd6+ cxd6 14. Ke2 {Keeping the king in the center for the endgame makes perfect sense, and is the choice made by Anand when he played Kramnik in 1998. However, we’re going to use the semi-open e-file to make White’s king a little uncomfortable.} Kd7 15. Rhc1 Bd5 {This is a very different plan than the one chosen in the 14. O-O line. Normally we would like to capture the bishop pair now that White is ready to play Be1 without locking the h1 -rook out of the game, but after} (15... Nxd2 $6 16. Nxd2 g6 17. Nc4 {We get a position that was fine for Black when White’s king was out of play on g1 , but is not okay now that White’s king is ready for the endgame action on e2 . So we have to let White keep the bishops, but make up for it with a stunning pawn sacrifice.}) 16. Be1 f4 {An incredible move! We’re giving away a pawn for seemingly no good reason.} 17. exf4 f5 {So we gave away the f5 -pawn on f4 , and then we follow up by getting a new pawn to that square? What did Black gain in all of this? The answer is the d5 -square. White had a long-term plan of going f3 and e4 to push Black away from the amazing d5 -outpost. The pawn sacrifice has secured Black an amazing positioning on d5 for the remainder of the game.} 18. Kf1 g6 {White’s king takes a step back, realizing the e2 -square has become much less safe with the removal of the e3 -pawn g6 Such calm play! It’s useful to protect the f5 -pawn in case we’re forced to move the e4 -knight away.} 19. a4 {White tries to push the queenside pawns, but Black simply ignores it and continues their plans.} Rhc8 20. b4 Ne7 {With compensation. Black is down a pawn, but has extremely good control of the d5 -square, and a king that can get involved quicker than White’s. The white dark-squared bishop is a big problem because it’s being blocked by its own pawns in pretty much every direction. As a result, Black has a decent position.} *

