1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. a3 Ba5 {There's no need to give away the bishop. You could argue it's better on a5 , as now Black has the added possibility of Bb6 to put pressure on White's center.} 9. h3 {While h3 and g4 is a common plan in this line to trouble Black's queen, it's unusual to see it this early.} e5 {White didn't protect the a5 - e1 -diagonal by playing Bd2 , nor did they reinforce the center with e3 . That gives Black an opportunity to strike in the center earlier than normal.} 10. d5 (10. dxe5 $6 Ne4 {Gives black uncomfortable pressure.}) 10... Nd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Qa4+ {If not for this resource, White would already be toast.} Bd7 13. Qxa5 dxc3 {Black has given away the bishop pair as well as the central pawns, but the big difference is development: Black will get the rooks involved much quicker than White.} 14. Qxc3 O-O {White struggles to get the king to safety and the pieces into play.} *

