1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. a3 Ba5 {There's no need to give away the bishop. You could argue it's better on a5 , as now Black has the added possibility of Bb6 to put pressure on White's center.} 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 {This is not at all as innocent as it looks. White tries to do an extended fianchetto with g4 , which simultaneously will create problems for Black's queen.} Rd8 {Black responds to the flank aggression with pressure on the center.} 11. g4 Qg6 {Black's queen is seriously uncomfortable on g6 , but tactics prevent White from trapping her outright.} 12. e3 {White reinforces the center, but the new light-squared weaknesses become very prominent.} e5 {Black seizes the initiative!} 13. dxe5 Be6 {A double pawn sacrifice sees Black making serious threats.} 14. Qxb7 Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Bd5 {White remains undeveloped. Surviving the opening has become the main priority.} *

