1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. a3 Ba5 {There's no need to give away the bishop. You could argue it's better on a5 , as now Black has the added possibility of Bb6 to put pressure on White's center.} 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 {This is not at all as innocent as it looks. White tries to do an extended fianchetto with g4 , which simultaneously will create problems for Black's queen.} Rd8 {Black responds to the flank aggression with pressure on the center.} 11. g4 Qg6 {Black's queen is seriously uncomfortable on g6 , but tactics prevent White from trapping her outright.} 12. Qc4 {White tries to defend the c4 -pawn, but the queen is prone to getting kicked around.} e5 {This thematic pawn sacrifice allows Black to get the inactive bishop to join the action with an attack on the queen.} 13. dxe5 Be6 14. Qa4 Nd7 {This leads to very difficult and complicated play, where a single misstep would be disastrous for white.} 15. Nh4 {doesn't trap the queen...} Nc5 {When Black escapes through fancy tactics...} 16. Nxg6 Nxa4 {Thanks to the rook on d8 and the bishop on a5 , the knight on a4 is immune.} 17. b4 {White tries to break the pin on the c3 -knight, but there's a beautiful strike for Black.} Rxd2 {BOOM!} 18. Kxd2 (18. Ne7+ {trying to deflect c6 knight also loses.} Nxe7 19. Kxd2 Rd8+ 20. Kc2 Nxc3 21. Kxc3 Bb6 {.}) 18... Rd8+ 19. Kc2 Nd4+ {White's king has to move away from the protection of the c3 -knight, so Black wins.} *

