1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. a3 Ba5 {There's no need to give away the bishop. You could argue it's better on a5 , as now Black has the added possibility of Bb6 to put pressure on White's center.} 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 {This is not at all as innocent as it looks. White tries to do an extended fianchetto with g4 , which simultaneously will create problems for Black's queen.} Rd8 {Black responds to the flank aggression with pressure on the center.} 11. g4 Qg6 {Black's queen is seriously uncomfortable on g6 , but tactics prevent White from trapping her outright.} 12. Qc4 {White tries to defend the c4 -pawn, but the queen is prone to getting kicked around.} e5 {This thematic pawn sacrifice allows Black to get the inactive bishop to join the action with an attack on the queen.} 13. dxe5 Be6 14. Qa4 Nd7 {This leads to very difficult and complicated play, where a single misstep would be disastrous for white.} 15. b4 {White tries to push Black's bishop back while simultanously preventing Nc5 .} Nc5 {What kind of sorcery is this? The knight comes to c5 anyway!} 16. Qd1 (16. bxc5 $2 {allows Black to demonstrate the big point} Rxd2 $1 17. Kxd2 Rd8+ 18. Ke3 Bxc3 {Black has a massive attack for the exchange.}) 16... Bxb4 {Black has several interesting possibilities here, but I've chosen to go with one where we eliminate White's queenside pawns. One likely scenario is the a-pawn rushing down the board to become a new queen.} 17. axb4 Nxb4 18. Bg2 {White has to focus on getting the king away.} Bb3 19. Qb1 Nc2+ {The knight check is key to our plans. It wins the rook in the corner, but just as importantly: It disrupts White's development. The king has to move, preventing castling, which in turn sees the rook stuck on h1 for the foreseeable future.} 20. Kf1 Nxa1 21. Qxa1 Qc2 22. Be1 Na4 {Black has an extraordinary amount of pressure on White's position. In short, Black's plan is to trade as much as possible and then run the a-pawn up the board. For example:} 23. Kg1 {Getting the king away is a sensible course of action, but the computer is not a fan because it allows Black to execute their main plan.} Nxc3 24. Qxc3 Qxc3 25. Bxc3 Rd1+ 26. Kh2 Rxh1+ 27. Kxh1 Bd5 {It's time for the a-pawn to rush up the board and get a new queen. White's pieces are unable to offer much resistance. By trading off the h1 -rook and eyeing the g2 -bishop, we minimize White's potential of creating counter threats.} *

