1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. a3 Ba5 {There's no need to give away the bishop. You could argue it's better on a5 , as now Black has the added possibility of Bb6 to put pressure on White's center.} 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 {This is not at all as innocent as it looks. White tries to do an extended fianchetto with g4 , which simultaneously will create problems for Black's queen.} Rd8 {Black responds to the flank aggression with pressure on the center.} 11. g4 Qg6 {Black's queen is seriously uncomfortable on g6 , but tactics prevent White from trapping her outright.} 12. Qa4 {White defends the d4 -pawn while simultaneously covering the Black queen's escape square on c2 . Black needs to take immediate action to stop Nh4 .} (12. Nh4 $4 {traps the queen, but runs into} Nxd4 {with a counter threat on White's queen. After} 13. Qa4 Qc2 {the queen gets out. And Black wins material after} 14. Qxa5 Nb3) 12... Bxc3 {Black wants to start aggression in the center with Ne4 , but first the c3 -knight must be eliminated.} 13. bxc3 Ne4 14. Bg2 Nxd2 {There's no need to let White's bishop pair survive.} 15. Nxd2 Bd7 {Black's position looks passive, but that will change over the coming moves. The plan is to go after the dark squares with e5 and/or c5 , but to accomplish that you need to insert Na5 and Rac8 too.} 16. Qc4 {The queen needs to step out of the bishop's diagonal, but it's not clear where it should go.} Rac8 {The c7 -pawn needs protection before we push e5 , due to White's option of d5 to kick the knight away.} 17. e3 {Solidifies the center, but allows Black to complete the plan:} Na5 18. Qe2 c5 {Finally we got a pawn involved in the fight for the center. Black has a really solid position and can open the c-file at will.} *

