tection before we push e5 , due to White's option of d5 to kick the knight away.} 17. Be4 {White needs to create threats to distract Black's from the easy Na5 and c5 -plan.} (17. O-O h5 {White struggles to get castled as it allows black to start an immediate attack on the overly aggressive kingside pawns. Black is in the driving seat.}) 17... Qh6 {A weird placement for the queen, but it has the benefit of keeping the h7 -pawn protected in case of Qd3 .} 18. h4 e5 {In lieu of the pawns storming forward on the kingside, black's queen needs a route to d6 to get away. And we put more pressure on White's center. Is that last part a coincidence? I think not.} 19. d5 Na5 20. Qb4 b6 {At this point White's king can't find a safe place anywhere.} 21. g5 Qd6 22. Rg1 h5 {I like this move, making sure Black doesn't get steamrolled on the kingside.} 23. gxh6 {White has to take the opportunity to open up for the rook towards Black's king, but it does break up White's pawn structure and allow more direct pressure on White's king.} Qxh6 {It's a tremendously complicated position, but I like Black's chances since we will soon open up in the center with c6 , when the rooks join the party.} *

