1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. h3 {While h3 and g4 is a common plan in this line to trouble Black's queen, it's unusual to see it this early.} a5 {The early pawn advance works out very well for Black because White's queen gets kicked around.} 9. a3 a4 {Kicking White's queen back and freeing up the a5 -square for Black's queen.} 10. Qd1 Bxc3+ {We give up the bishop pair to prioritize development. Black will strike with e5 in the center when White must focus on getting the king to safety rather than punish Black's aggression.} 11. bxc3 O-O 12. g4 Qa5 {There's no need for the normal retreat to obscurity on g6 now. The queen finds a great position both targeting c3 and supporting e5 .} 13. Bd2 e5 {The central strike arrives before White is even able to castle.} 14. Bg2 {Finally White is ready to castle next.} Ne4 {Black has succeeded in creating pressure before White got the king to safety.} 15. Nxe5 {Some trickery bails White out.} Nxd2 16. Nxc6 Qxc3 {We're treated to some tactical fireworks, but just like the real deal, it quickly burns out.} 17. Qc1 {Allowing the double-check is both fancy and surprisingly safe.} Nf3+ 18. Kf1 Nd2+ 19. Ke1 Nf3+ {Black must accept the perpetual.} *

