[PlyCount "30"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. e3 Bd6 {The combination of e3 and Bd2 make White well-placed to deal with the immediate e5 -pawn break, so we're in need of a prepatory move to facilitate it.} 10. Nb5 {This is the only way to cause some problems for Black's e5 -plan.} e5 {It turns out the threat against the bishop doesn't prevent us from striking in the center.} 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. dxe5 dxe5 {Grabbing the bishop pair doesn't bring White success as the king situation is still a cause for concern.} 13. Bc4 Qg6 14. O-O e4 15. Ne1 (15. Nd4 $4 {loses to} Bh3 {.}) 15... a6 {White has been forced back with the knight, and now we're preparing to chase the bishop away too, with b5 coming up next. Black is better.} *

