1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. h3 {9. h3 and the plans associated with it caused a big revival of this line from White's perspective when Vishy Anand introduced it against Vladimir Kramnik in their 2008 World Championship Match -- a game Anand won.} (9. a3 {transposes back to the 8.a3 line after} Ba5 {.}) 9... a5 {Pushing for queenside space, including dislodging the queen off the b3 -square with a4 next, has become Black's main antidote.} 10. g4 Qg6 11. Nh4 {traps Black's queen, but also gives up the protection of the d4 -pawn.} Nxd4 {By a slight miracle Black manages to get their queen out of trouble by putting pressure on White's queen instead.} 12. Qc4 Qc2 {The only escape square for the queen, but it's good enough -- even despite the d4 -knight dropping off.} 13. Qxd4 Qxb2 {it turns out the important pin on the c3 -knight is not the b4 - e1 -diagonal, but rather the queen's pressure on the opposing queen from b2 to d4 . With Black's knight coming in to d5 next move, the material deficit will be recovered in no time.} 14. Rc1 Nd5 15. Bg2 Qxc1+ {A gorgeous little diversion!} 16. Bxc1 Bxc3+ 17. Qxc3 Nxc3 {The complications paid off in a big way for Black.} *

