1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. h3 {9. h3 and the plans associated with it caused a big revival of this line from White's perspective when Vishy Anand introduced it against Vladimir Kramnik in their 2008 World Championship Match -- a game Anand won.} (9. a3 {transposes back to the 8.a3 line after} Ba5 {.}) 9... a5 {Pushing for queenside space, including dislodging the queen off the b3 -square with a4 next, has become Black's main antidote.} 10. g4 Qg6 11. a3 Bxc3 ({This is uncommon, but I think this is a very clever move-order. Often Black plays} 11... a4 {to force the queen back with} 12. Qd1 {and only then does Black give up the bishop} Bxc3 {However, after} 13. Bxc3 {I believe White has an interesting position with good reinforcements in the center. If Black now strikes with} e5 $6 {then White has} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Qd3 {With a good position, which is why I would rather strike in the middle as soon as possible, and the 11... Bxc3 move order allows us to do just that.}) 12. bxc3 {This is rarely played in these positions, but it's very logical as it increases White's protection in the center. In addition the newly available square on b2 can be a good position for White's queen.} a4 {White has a decision where to place the queen.} 13. Qa2 {To me this is most logical, as Black's main plan is to establish a knight on c4 . However, by moving away from the protection of the c3 -pawn, White loses the option of Bf4 to put pressure on the vulnerable c7 -pawn when black moves the knight forward in the center.} Ne4 14. Bg2 f5 {With White's queen keeping the c4 -square in its sights, black has to find a different method for counterplay than Na5 , and f5 does just that -- It's a horrendous weakening of the e5 -square, but takes control of the light squares and launches a pre-emptive attack on the kingside, where White's king is likely to reside in the near future. It's a complicated game where Black has good chances.} 15. g5 {Protecting the pawn makes a lot of sense and reinforces the impression that White is fighting for the dark squares while Black has the light squares under control.} Qe8 {The queen returns to avoid being attacked by Ne5 in the future.} 16. Rc1 {White needs to protect the c3 -pawn before playing Bf4 .} Na5 17. Bf4 b5 {White's control of e5 is undisputed, but that's only one square. In the meantime Black has control of b3 , c4 , d5 and e4 and getting pieces ready to occupy those squares. Overall Black is having the best of it.} *

