1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. h3 {9. h3 and the plans associated with it caused a big revival of this line from White's perspective when Vishy Anand introduced it against Vladimir Kramnik in their 2008 World Championship Match -- a game Anand won.} (9. a3 {transposes back to the 8.a3 line after} Ba5 {.}) 9... a5 {Pushing for queenside space, including dislodging the queen off the b3 -square with a4 next, has become Black's main antidote.} 10. g4 Qg6 11. a3 Bxc3 ({This is uncommon, but I think this is a very clever move-order. Often Black plays} 11... a4 {to force the queen back with} 12. Qd1 {and only then does Black give up the bishop} Bxc3 {However, after} 13. Bxc3 {I believe White has an interesting position with good reinforcements in the center. If Black now strikes with} e5 $6 {then White has} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Qd3 {With a good position, which is why I would rather strike in the middle as soon as possible, and the 11... Bxc3 move order allows us to do just that.}) 12. bxc3 {This is rarely played in these positions, but it's very logical as it increases White's protection in the center. In addition the newly available square on b2 can be a good position for White's queen.} a4 {White has a decision where to place the queen.} 13. Qb2 {White anticipates Ne4 coming soon, giving the c3 -pawn extra protection so the d2 -bishop can be relieved of its tasks and go attack the c7 -pawn instead.} Nd7 {Black is eyeing the c4 -square with the knights, while also having a plan to deal with Bf4 .} 14. Bf4 e5 {When Black is able to strengthen their central pressure while also keeping the c7 -pawn protected.} 15. Bg3 (15. dxe5 $2 {is no good because of} Qe4 {when Black gets the pawn back after successfully comprimising white's pawn structure in the center.}) 15... Re8 {This line primarily sees Black taking control of the light squares, which is why it's nice to have the e5 -move and some dark-squared control as well. Re8 is just a reinforcing move.} 16. Bg2 {White tries to get developed, but we have our standard response.} h5 {A complicated struggle lies ahead, but Black's pressure on White's weakened kingside guarantees fair chances for a win.} *

