[PlyCount "52"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. h3 {9. h3 and the plans associated with it caused a big revival of this line from White's perspective when Vishy Anand introduced it against Vladimir Kramnik in their 2008 World Championship Match -- a game Anand won.} (9. a3 {transposes back to the 8.a3 line after} Ba5 {.}) 9... a5 {Pushing for queenside space, including dislodging the queen off the b3 -square with a4 next, has become Black's main antidote.} 10. g4 Qg6 11. a3 Bxc3 ({This is uncommon, but I think this is a very clever move-order. Often Black plays} 11... a4 {to force the queen back with} 12. Qd1 {and only then does Black give up the bishop} Bxc3 {However, after} 13. Bxc3 {I believe White has an interesting position with good reinforcements in the center. If Black now strikes with} e5 $6 {then White has} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Qd3 {With a good position, which is why I would rather strike in the middle as soon as possible, and the 11... Bxc3 move order allows us to do just that.}) 12. bxc3 {This is rarely played in these positions, but it's very logical as it increases White's protection in the center. In addition the newly available square on b2 can be a good position for White's queen.} a4 {White has a decision where to place the queen.} 13. Qb2 {White anticipates Ne4 coming soon, giving the c3 -pawn extra protection so the d2 -bishop can be relieved of its tasks and go attack the c7 -pawn instead.} Nd7 {Black is eyeing the c4 -square with the knights, while also having a plan to deal with Bf4 .} 14. Bg2 Nb6 {Destination: the c4 -square.} 15. Bf4 {With the queen stuck out on g6 , it's very difficult to keep the c7 -pawn protected, so it's a great target for White.} (15. O-O {White wants to get the king to safety, but the timing of it is crucial -- with the pawn on g4 , castling may sometimes land you in more trouble than safety, and this is one of those times. Black strikes with} h5 {when White faces some difficult decisions to keep the king safe.}) 15... Nc4 16. Qa2 N6a5 {Black's knight are creating trouble on the queenside. This is a pawn sacrifice, as the c7 -pawn is left to its own devices. But Black will get very active piece play as compensation.} 17. Bxc7 {Accepts the gift immediately.} Nb3 18. Rd1 Qf6 {A very tricky move, trying to get the queen back into play and targeting the a3 -pawn. It also helps keep the knight on c4 as White's plan of Ne5 is discouraged.} 19. O-O (19. Ne5 $6 {allows black to execute the main plan} Qe7 20. Nxc4 Qxc7 {The knight must move, when Black will regain the pawn on c3 .} 21. Nd2 Qxc3 {Black is doing well.}) 19... Qe7 20. Bf4 Bd7 {This is a great show of restraint -- Black could capture the pawn with} (20... Qxa3 {but then White will get pieces focused towards Black's king after} 21. Qc2 {Ng5 and Ne5 are both good plans for white, while the move that defends against both,} f6 {, gives white another target in their attack after} 22. g5 {when White will try to open up the g-file to attack there.}) 21. Nd2 {Guarantees White some trades, and it looks like the complications will favor White, but this is not the case...} Qxa3 22. Qxa3 Nxa3 23. Bd6 Nxd2 24. Bxf8 Nac4 25. Bb4 Bc6 26. Bxc6 bxc6 {It turns out the black knights are worth just as much as a rook and bishop, with the a-pawn storming down the board next.} *

