.} Nd7 {Black is eyeing the c4 -square with the knights, while also having a plan to deal with Bf4 .} 14. Bg2 Nb6 {Destination: the c4 -square.} 15. Bf4 {With the queen stuck out on g6 , it's very difficult to keep the c7 -pawn protected, so it's a great target for White.} (15. O-O {White wants to get the king to safety, but the timing of it is crucial -- with the pawn on g4 , castling may sometimes land you in more trouble than safety, and this is one of those times. Black strikes with} h5 {when White faces some difficult decisions to keep the king safe.}) 15... Nc4 16. Qa2 N6a5 {Black's knight are creating trouble on the queenside. This is a pawn sacrifice, as the c7 -pawn is left to its own devices. But Black will get very active piece play as compensation.} 17. Ne5 {White wants the pawn on c7 , but chooses to eliminate the annoying c4 -knight first.} Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bd7 {The only way to save the c7 -pawn was to push it forward, when Black's pawns would completely shut in the c8 -bishop. We're not having any of that! Instead we're going for a pawn sacrifice to get rid of White's bishop pair.} 19. Bxc7 Nb3 20. Rd1 Bc6 {White faces a rough choice: Either trade off the bishop pair and an important protector of the king, or allow Black to get the bishop pointing down on White's queen.} 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. O-O {White is up a pawn, but the queen is out of play and the king is somewhat uncomfortable.} Rfc8 {Right now the rook is just pointing into its own pawn, but long-term Black's plan is to play c5 and get the rook into white's position down the c-file.} 23. Bg3 h5 {Poking at White's pawns to create some weaknesses.} 24. f3 Qg5 {This is a great move, taking control of both e3 and d5 . While White deals with the threat of Qe3 +, Black will have time to play c5 without having to worry about White responding with d5 .} (24... c5 $2 {is what Black wants to play, to get the c8 -rook into play, but here White goes} 25. d5 {when it's White's d1 -rook, not Black's c8 -rook, that gets into play.}) 25. Kg2 {White avoids Qe3 +, but now we strike.} c5 26. dxc5 Rxc5 {It's time to pile up on the c3 -pawn.} 27. Qc2 Rac8 28. Rd3 {White managed to defend c3 , so now it's time to create a new flank of attack.} hxg4 29. hxg4 f5 {White is struggling to defend everything without losing their extra pawn. Chances are balanced.} *

