1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. h3 {9. h3 and the plans associated with it caused a big revival of this line from White's perspective when Vishy Anand introduced it against Vladimir Kramnik in their 2008 World Championship Match -- a game Anand won.} (9. a3 {transposes back to the 8.a3 line after} Ba5 {.}) 9... a5 {Pushing for queenside space, including dislodging the queen off the b3 -square with a4 next, has become Black's main antidote.} 10. g4 Qg6 11. a3 Bxc3 ({This is uncommon, but I think this is a very clever move-order. Often Black plays} 11... a4 {to force the queen back with} 12. Qd1 {and only then does Black give up the bishop} Bxc3 {However, after} 13. Bxc3 {I believe White has an interesting position with good reinforcements in the center. If Black now strikes with} e5 $6 {then White has} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Qd3 {With a good position, which is why I would rather strike in the middle as soon as possible, and the 11... Bxc3 move order allows us to do just that.}) 12. Bxc3 e5 {This move is the big point behind delaying the a4 -move -- we would rather kick White's queen around with Be6 next, which allows us to get a dangerous initiative with all our pieces involved.} 13. dxe5 {The critical test of Black's concept: Just take the pawn.} a4 {This is the right moment to kick the queen around. Now that we've provoked White into opening the center, it's more difficult to find a safe, long-term square for the queen.} 14. Qb5 {This is White's trickiest option, as it keeps the pressure on the b7 -pawn, making it more difficult to develop the c8 -bishop.} Ne4 15. Bb4 {This looks weird to me, but it's surprisingly effective. The bishop needed to move, and now it's also attacking Black's rook.} Nxb4 {As always we're taking out the bishop pair when given the opportunity.} 16. Qxb4 (16. axb4 {The attack on the a4 -pawn is just a mirage, as the pawn cannot be captured without losing the rook to the disruptive c6 from Black. In addition, Black now gets an option to invade with the queen.} Ng5 {Trying to exchange off the protection of the e5 -pawn.} 17. Bg2 Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Qc2 {The b2 -pawn can't be defended. Black will regain the pawn with annoying counterplay.}) 16... c5 {Constantly going after the queen is the best way of getting a nice position.} 17. Qb5 Rd8 {Pointing down the d-file is nice, but first and foremost this move is about giving Black's bishop the d7 -square.} 18. Bg2 Bd7 19. Qc4 (19. Qxb7 {Pawn snatching can be a good idea, but after} Bc6 20. Qe7 Re8 21. Qh4 Rab8 {White's queen is stuck on the side while Black's rook is invading down the b-file. Black has good counterplay.}) 19... Bc6 {Black has coordinated the pieces well, but is playing with a pawn less than White.} 20. O-O {This allows Black to highlight the precarious state of White's king.} Nd2 21. Nxd2 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Rxd2 {There's lots of threats along the second rank and White's king is starting to feel a bit chilly sitting in the draught.} 23. Rad1 {Attempting to trade off Black's dangerous rook is the best bet...} Qc6+ 24. Kg1 b5 {We'd rather capture e2 than b2 , because taking the e2 -pawn makes White's king more vulnerable.} 25. Qc3 Rxe2 {Black has everything under control.} *

