1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black immediately starts the counter-attack! Normally we wouldn't bring the queen out this early, but White did it, so why not? Our justification is putting pressure on the undefended d4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 Qf5 7. Qb3 {Avoiding the queen trade is by far White's most challenging option.} Nc6 ({The bishop needed protection, and unfortunately the strategically preferable} 7... c5 $6 {to include the c-pawn in the fight for the center is well met by} 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qc4 {when White gets a serious advantage due to the undefended bishop on c8 .}) 8. Bd2 O-O 9. h3 {9. h3 and the plans associated with it caused a big revival of this line from White's perspective when Vishy Anand introduced it against Vladimir Kramnik in their 2008 World Championship Match -- a game Anand won.} (9. a3 {transposes back to the 8.a3 line after} Ba5 {.}) 9... a5 {Pushing for queenside space, including dislodging the queen off the b3 -square with a4 next, has become Black's main antidote.} 10. g4 Qg6 11. a3 Bxc3 ({This is uncommon, but I think this is a very clever move-order. Often Black plays} 11... a4 {to force the queen back with} 12. Qd1 {and only then does Black give up the bishop} Bxc3 {However, after} 13. Bxc3 {I believe White has an interesting position with good reinforcements in the center. If Black now strikes with} e5 $6 {then White has} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Qd3 {With a good position, which is why I would rather strike in the middle as soon as possible, and the 11... Bxc3 move order allows us to do just that.}) 12. Bxc3 e5 {This move is the big point behind delaying the a4 -move -- we would rather kick White's queen around with Be6 next, which allows us to get a dangerous initiative with all our pieces involved.} 13. dxe5 {The critical test of Black's concept: Just take the pawn.} a4 {This is the right moment to kick the queen around. Now that we've provoked White into opening the center, it's more difficult to find a safe, long-term square for the queen.} 14. Qd1 {Going back may be considered the safest option, but Black will manage to create play against the e5 -pawn.} Ne4 {First order of business: Eliminate White's bishop pair.} 15. Qc1 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Ra5 {Next plan: Put pressure on the e5 -pawn.} 17. Bg2 Rb5 {The rook was a little bit scared on a5 , as there was only the knight on c6 defending it, but now the rook is perfectly placed pointing against both the pawn on b2 and the one on e5 .} 18. O-O {White wants to finish development, but the recurring problem in this line is that castling will inevitably be followed by Black starting an attack on White's king.} h5 {Black strikes on the kingside immediately!} 19. g5 {The further out white's g-pawn explores, the more unsafe the king.} Bf5 20. Rad1 Qe6 {Black's pressure on e5 and h3 will win back the missing pawn, at a minimum.} *

